[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction: The King's Indian Defence"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7
{ The King's Indian Defence @@StartBracket@@KID@@EndBracket@@ is one of the most famous openings in chess. Its popularity stems from the mid-50s when the players with Black, led by Boleslavsky, Geller, Bronstein and Gligoric understood the enormous dynamic potential that was hidden in Black's compact position. In the years and decades that followed its popularity only increased with the World Champions Tal, Fischer and Kasparov all adding to the allure of the ultimate counter-attacking weapon.  At first glance Black's plan in the King's Indian Defence is simple: he gives up the centre in order to attack it by playing ...e5 or ...c5. However, this simplicity is only the tip of the iceberg because the underlying strategic and tactical elements that allow Black to achieve his ideas after ...e5 or ...c5 has been played are very complex.  The King's Indian Defence falls into the category of openings that pursue a 'dark square strategy' - this simply means that the importance of the dark squares is what comes to the fore and both players should pay special attention to who gets to control them - whoever does usually has the advantage, or at least equality in Black's case. So as a @@StartBracket@@very@@EndBracket@@ general rule of thumb, whenever you are not sure what you should do, think of the dark squares and how to use them - this should at least give your thoughts a constructive direction.  The King's Indian Defence is a fighting opening that will guarantee a complex middlegame @@StartBracket@@or endgame@@EndBracket@@ where your understanding and experience will be critical factors for success. I have played the opening for many years and it was very important @@StartBracket@@netting me 2 wins@@EndBracket@@ for scoring my first GM norm. I hope you have at least similar success with it! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "01. Gligoric Variation (Lines 05-06)"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 { White naturally takes over the centre. }
4... d6 { Preventing e5. } 5. Nf3 O-O
{ Black finished the development of the kingside and is now ready to play in the centre. }
6. Be2
{ This is White's most natural development, preparing short castle, and that is why this variation is called the Classical Variation. }
6... e5
{ The central strike that characterises the King's Indian Defence. Its idea is to attack the d4-square and either provoke White to react by pushing d5 or by taking on e5,  or to capture on d4 and open the e-file and the long-diagonal for the fianchettoed bishop. Now White has 4 main options to choose from:  1. He can keep the tension in the centre by castling  7.O-O   2. He can keep the tension in the centre by developing the dark-squared bishop to e3 with  7.Be3  - the Gligoric Variation.  3. He can blockade the centre immediately with  7.d5  - the Petrosian Variation.  4. He can exchange the pawns and then the queens after  7.dxe5  - the Exchange Variation. }
7. Be3
{ This is the Gligoric Variation. Its idea is to postpone castling and keep the tension in the centre. It caused Garry Kasparov certain problems in the last match Karpov-Kasparov played in New York and Lyon in 1990. Not surprisingly, the advances of theory and practice since then discovered reliable ways for Black how to deal with this system. }
7... exd4
{ This is the most straightforward and direct approach. Black opens the long diagonal, the centre and the e-file while White's king is still uncastled. }
8. Nxd4
{ The natural and the only good recapture. Taking with a bishop only gives Black a tempo for development after  8.Bxd4?!  Re8  @@StartBracket@@attacking the pawn on e4@@EndBracket@@  9.Nd2  Bh6!  and after ...Nc6 next the bishop on d4 is short of squares - White will have to allow the wrecking of his structure after Be3 ...Bxe3,  fxe3 which gives Black a clear advantage. }
8... Re8 { Attacking the pawn on e4. } 9. f3
{ Strengthening the centre, but now the bishop on e3 is somewhat loose and Black uses this fact to strike in the centre with ...c6 and ...d5. }
9... c6
{ Irrelevant of what White does next, the central thrust ...d5 is inevitably coming on the next move. }
10. Bf2
{ White's only attempt if he tries to achieve an advantage. The alternatives are weaker. }
10... d5 { Black continues as planned. } 11. exd5 cxd5 12. O-O
{ White gets the king out from the centre. The move  12.c5  will likely transpose after  12...Nc6  13.O-O  , though Black has the extra option of  12...Nbd7!?  which gave Black good play in the game Sjugirov-Grischuk from the Russian Championship in 2012. }
12... Nc6 { The usual development for Black. } 13. c5
{ With this move White establishes a queenside majority and his strategic plan now is to keep a strong control or blockade on the d4-square, thus limiting the movement of Black's passed pawn on d5 and use this central control to advance with his majority on the queenside. If allowed to execute this plan White will have an overwhelming position, which means that Black's counterplay must be quick, before White consolidates. }
13... Nh5
{ The start of the re-routing of the knight. The first idea is to jump to f4 and when White prevents that Black will continue with ...Be5 @@StartBracket@@again threatening ...Nf4 or ...Bf4@@EndBracket@@ and after White's g3 he will play ...Ng7, with the idea to fight for control over the d4-square by putting the knight on e6 or f5. This manoeuvre is Black's key idea in the positions that arise in the Gligoric Variation. }
14. Qd2 { White prevents ...Nf4 and continues with his development. } 14... Be5
{ Activating the bishop and again threatening ...Nf4 or ...Bf4. } 15. g3
{ White should prevent a black piece from appearing on f4. } 15... Ng7
{ Black continues with the plan. Now he has ideas based on the exchange of the knight on d4 and jumping to f5, in addition to the simple ...Ne6.  Main Chapter and Extended Variations    The Classical Variation  Line 05  Line 06 }
