[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "02. Petrosian Variation (Lines 12-13)"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 { White naturally takes over the centre. }
4... d6 { Preventing e5. } 5. Nf3 O-O
{ Black finished the development of the kingside and is now ready to play in the centre. }
6. Be2
{ This is White's most natural development, preparing short castle, and that is why this variation is called the Classical Variation. }
6... e5
{ The central strike that characterises the King's Indian Defence. Its idea is to attack the d4-square and either provoke White to react by pushing d5 or by taking on e5,  or to capture on d4 and open the e-file and the long-diagonal for the fianchettoed bishop. Now White has 4 main options to choose from:  1. He can keep the tension in the centre by castling  7.O-O   2. He can keep the tension in the centre by developing the dark-squared bishop to e3 with  7.Be3  - the Gligoric Variation.  3. He can blockade the centre immediately with  7.d5  - the Petrosian Variation.  4. He can exchange the pawns and then the queens after  7.dxe5  - the Exchange Variation. }
7. d5
{ The Petrosian Variation, invented and made popular by the 9th World Champion in the late 50s and early 60s. White immediately closes the centre and intends to start his usual queenside play by advancing the pawns with b4 and c5. }
7... Nbd7
{ The idea of this move is to develop and keep an eye on the c5-square, where the knight can jump in order to attack the pawn on e4 and stop or slow down White's intended queenside expansion.  When the Petrosian Variation was at the height of its popularity in the late 50s and early 60s this move was the most common way to meet it. Later on the move 7...a5 came to the fore while the third option 7...Na6 never really caught on. }
8. Bg5
{ This is Petrosian's prophylactic idea - with the pin on the h4-d8 diagonal White tries to slow down Black's plan of kingside expansion that consists of moving the knight from f6 and pushing ...f5. }
8... h6 { Black naturally wants to get rid of the bishop. } 9. Bh4 g5
{ Forcing the bishop to the passive square on g3. } 10. Bg3 Nh5
{ From here the knight can either take the bishop on g3 when the time is right, or it can jump to f4. }
11. h4
{ In the early 60s this was considered the main move as it challenges Black's kingside expansion. }
11... g4 { The only plausible move for Black, hitting the knight on f3. } 12.
Nh2
{ From h2 the knight attacks the pawn on g4. It's a double-edged decision as the knight can easily be left completely passive after ...h5, but on the other hand, it gives White the tactical idea of a piece sacrifice on g4. }
12... Nxg3 { The only way to save the pawn on g4 is to protect it with ...h5. }
13. fxg3 h5
{ Now everything will evolve around whether White will manage to activate his knight from h2 - he will either try to sacrifice on g4 or to re-route it via f1 to e3. }
14. O-O
{ White cannot start immediately with  14.Nf1  as it allows  14...f5  with great play for Black. }
14... Nc5
{ An important move. First of all, it prevents a sacrifice on g4,  which would be possible after  14...Bh6!?  15.Bxg4!?  hxg4  16.Nxg4  Bg7  which is playable for Black, as White has nothing concrete, but it is rather murky.  The second idea is to provoke White's b4 because then Black will play ...a5 and open the a-file for his rook. Then he will combine play on the a-file with the threat of pushing ...f5. }
15. b4
{ White must play this move as otherwise Black would stabilise his knight after ...a5. }
15... Nd7
{ Black achieved his goal and now threatens ...a5 to open the a-file.  Main Chapter and Extended Variations    The Classical Variation  Line 12  Line 13 }
