[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "03. Exchange Variation (Line 14)"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 { White naturally takes over the centre. }
4... d6 { Preventing e5. } 5. Nf3 O-O
{ Black finished the development of the kingside and is now ready to play in the centre. }
6. Be2
{ This is White's most natural development, preparing short castle, and that is why this variation is called the Classical Variation. }
6... e5
{ The central strike that characterises the King's Indian Defence. Its idea is to attack the d4-square and either provoke White to react by pushing d5 or by taking on e5,  or to capture on d4 and open the e-file and the long-diagonal for the fianchettoed bishop. Now White has 4 main options to choose from:  1. He can keep the tension in the centre by castling  7.O-O   2. He can keep the tension in the centre by developing the dark-squared bishop to e3 with  7.Be3  - the Gligoric Variation.  3. He can blockade the centre immediately with  7.d5  - the Petrosian Variation.  4. He can exchange the pawns and then the queens after  7.dxe5  - the Exchange Variation. }
7. dxe5
{ The Exchange Variation is rather harmless, though Black needs to know how to react to it. }
7... dxe5 8. Qxd8 Rxd8
{ The pawn structure is in Black's favour now in view of the hole on d4. } 9.
Bg5
{ This is the main move. White should be incisive in this endgame because he has the worse pawn structure - the gaping hole on d4 cannot be controlled by a pawn, while Black can cover the d5-square by ...c6.  Many KID endgames have been won by Black rather effortlessly following the scenario of exchanging the dark-squared bishops, giving up the light-squared bishop for the knight on f3 and then planting a knight on d4,  which leads to the dream position for Black of a dominating knight on d4 versus an awful bishop on e2.  Note that the pawn on e5 is taboo in view of the trick  9.Nxe5?!  Nxe4!  and the bishop on g7 springs to life on the open diagonal. }
9... Re8
{ Getting away from the pin and defending the pawn on e5. Now Black wants to play ...c6, so White's next move is the critical one. }
10. Nd5 Nxd5 { The knight has to be eliminated. } 11. cxd5 c6
{ Black naturally wants to undermine White's strong point on d5, at the same time getting rid of the backward pawn on c7. }
12. Bc4 { White intends to recapture on d5 with a bishop. } 12... cxd5
{ Eliminating the d5-pawn. } 13. Bxd5 Nd7
{ This is important to remember. The natural move is to put the knight on c6, but from d7 the knight has two important tasks: one is to control the d5-square, either from f6 @@StartBracket@@from here the knight also targets the pawn on e4@@EndBracket@@ or b6, and the other is to go to c5 in order to allow for ...Be6 and after the exchange of bishops to land on e6, from where it can further go to d4 or f4.  Main Chapter and Extended Variations    The Classical Variation  Line 14 }
