[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "04. Classical Main Line #1 (Line 16)"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 { White naturally takes over the centre. }
4... d6 { Preventing e5. } 5. Nf3 O-O
{ Black finished the development of the kingside and is now ready to play in the centre. }
6. Be2
{ This is White's most natural development, preparing short castle, and that is why this variation is called the Classical Variation. }
6... e5
{ The central strike that characterises the King's Indian Defence. Its idea is to attack the d4-square and either provoke White to react by pushing d5 or by taking on e5,  or to capture on d4 and open the e-file and the long-diagonal for the fianchettoed bishop. Now White has 4 main options to choose from:  1. He can keep the tension in the centre by castling  7.O-O   2. He can keep the tension in the centre by developing the dark-squared bishop to e3 with  7.Be3  - the Gligoric Variation.  3. He can blockade the centre immediately with  7.d5  - the Petrosian Variation.  4. He can exchange the pawns and then the queens after  7.dxe5  - the Exchange Variation. }
7. O-O { The most natural move for White, getting the king out of the centre. }
7... Bg4
{ This rare move has been known since the 50s, but it was never considered to be good. This conclusion changed when it was successfully used by Caruana to convincingly defeat Wojtaszek in the Wijk aan Zee tournament in 2021.  In fact, the move is a logical one as Black fights for the control of the dark squares by attacking the knight on f3 that controls both e5 and d4. It also has the benefit of not being explored as deeply as the more theoretical alternatives, which allows Black to obtain a fresh position without the need for massive memorisation. }
8. Be3
{ This move looks natural, supporting the centre, but now Black has a forced sequence that gives him good play. }
8... Bxf3
{ Following the plan by eliminating the piece that covers the dark squares in the centre. }
9. Bxf3 exd4
{ Opening the long diagonal for the dark-squared bishop and liberating the e5-square for a knight. Once the pawn on d4 is gone, Black's knights have access to the comfortable squares on c5 and e5. }
10. Bxd4 Nc6
{ Developing with tempo and forcing the bishop to go back to e3 because White cannot possibly allow the exchange of his dark-squared bishop for a knight. In that case, Black will be the absolute master of the dark squares and this will give him a big advantage, especially as White's light-squared bishop is passive and limited by his own pawns. }
11. Be3 Re8
{ Developing the rook on the semi-open file. The forced sequence is finished and Black is quite comfortable here, with all his pieces developed. His plan now is to use the dark squares, especially c5 and e5 and the long diagonal, to create play against White's centre.  Main Chapter and Extended Variations    The Classical Variation  Line 16 }
