8. d5
{ This is the only critical option, as the alternatives give Black easy play. }
8... a5
{ A typical move on the queenside for Black. He increases his control over the squares b4 and c5, thus slowing down White's expansion by b4 and c5. The pawn on a5 also ensures a safe spot on c5 for the knight. }
9. h3
{ Normally White doesn't play like this in the KID, weakening the kingside, but in this case it forces the exchange of Black's light-squared bishop. This is a double-edged decision as even though White obtains the pair of bishops he does weaken his kingside and slows down his queenside play. }
9... Bxf3
{ Black would have liked to keep this bishop @@StartBracket@@his pawns on the dark squares in the centre mean that he needs that piece to control the light squares@@EndBracket@@, but unfortunately keeping it allows  9...Bd7?!  10.c5!  when White starts queenside play immediately. }
10. Bxf3 Nbd7
{ Black finishes development. Now he has two main ideas: to prepare and execute the ...f5 push @@StartBracket@@by moving the knight from f6 first@@EndBracket@@ and to exchange the dark-squared bishops. The latter can be done in more than one way: by playing ...Kh8, ...Ng8 and ...Bh6, by playing ...h5, ...Kh7 and ...Bh6, by moving the knight from f6 and going ...Bf6-g5 @@StartBracket@@with or without ...f5@@EndBracket@@.  Note that after the exchange of the dark-squared bishops Black will have the advantage of having the better minor pieces because White's remaining bishop will be severely limited due to White's own pawns placed on the light squares. Additionally, the exchange of the dark-squared bishops will weaken White's dark squares because without the bishop White will have one piece less to control them.  While these positional considerations are valid for a lot of KID positions of a similar type, this particular position is practically unexplored and there is vast room for finding new paths. Let's take a look now at two ways for White - one is to prepare the queenside expansion immediately, while the other is to finish development first before doing so. }
11. a3 { With this move White starts his queenside play immediately. } 11... h5
{ Since White wants to start immediate play on the queenside with Rb1 and b4 Black's plan with ...f5 is rather slow. To illustrate, after  11...Ne8?!  12.Rb1  f5  13.b4  White is ready to crash through with c5 even at the expense of a pawn, while Black's kingside play has little to show for.  That is why he switches to the strategic idea of the exchange of the dark-squared bishops and plans to exchange them in one of the two ways: with ...Kh7 and ...Bh6,  or ...Nh7 followed by ...Bf6-g5. }
12. Rb1 Nh7
{ With the intention of ...Bf6-g5.  The alternative is  12...Kh7  , which is also possible. Now White should try to stop Black's plan by playing  13.g4!?  , intending to meet Black's ...Bh6 with g5. So Black should adjust his plan and play  13...hxg4  14.hxg4  Kg8!  with the idea of ...Nh7 and then either ...Ng5 or ...Bf6-g5. This leads to a very complex middlegame. }
13. b4 Bf6
{ It is important not to open the a-file prematurely because in that case, White can seize it after Bb2, Qd3 and Ra1. }
14. Nb5 Bg5
{ Black continues with his plan. Now he has activated his dark-squared bishop so even in case White avoids the exchange he will no longer have passive pieces.  Main Chapter and Extended Variations    The Classical Variation  Line 21 }
