[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "08. Saemisch Variation #1 (Line 25)"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 { White naturally takes over the centre. }
4... d6 { Preventing e5. } 5. f3
{ This move is typical for the Saemisch Variation, named after the German Grandmaster Friedrich Saemisch. The idea is quite simple: since one aspect of Black's counterplay in the KID is the attack on the e4-pawn White immediately defends it securely. As an additional bonus the pawn on f3 covers the g4-square so this ensures a safe spot for the dark-squared bishop on e3.  However, there is a price to be paid for all these advantages. A long time ago, when GM Eduard Gufeld, a life-long and very successful KID player, was asked about the disadvantages of the Saemisch Variation he simply replied: 'Just ask the knight on g1!'  And he was right, the pawn on f3 takes away the natural developing square from the knight and the knight finds it difficult to get into the game - even when developed on e2 it blocks the bishop on f1 and needs further redeployment. As we shall see Black uses this problematic knight to create his counterplay. }
5... O-O
{ Black finishes development and is now ready to start play against White's centre. Now White has a choice where to develop his dark-squared bishop, to e3 or to g5.  Note that the move  6.Nge2  has no independent value because after  6...Nc6  White again needs to make the same choice about the development of the bishop, hence transposing to the main lines either after 6.Be3 or 6.Bg5. }
6. Bg5
{ A slightly provocative move. White seeks to provoke ...h6 when the bishop will drop back to its natural square on e3 when White can gain a tempo against the pawn on h6 by attacking it with Qd2.  However, if Black refrains from ...h6 then the bishop may turn out to be somewhat out or play and the pawn on d4 may feel the lack of protection @@StartBracket@@unlike when the bishop is on e3@@EndBracket@@. }
6... Nc6
{ Black's play is the same as in the line after 6.Be3. He intends ...e5 and ...Nd4, so White's next move is forced. }
7. Nge2 a6 { The preparatory move for a possible ...b5. } 8. Qd2 Na5
{ Black immediately attacks the pawn on c4, thus taking advantage of the clumsy position of the knight on e2. }
9. Nc1 c5
{ Without a bishop on e3 Black doesn't need the move ...Nd7 and this move is immediately possible. }
10. d5 { The most ambitious. } 10... Rb8 { Preparing the ...b5 push. } 11. Be2
b5
{ Executing the plan. Now Black's counterplay speeds up.  Main Chapter and Extended Variations    The Saemisch Variation  Line 25 }
