[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "09. Saemisch Variation #2 (Lines 33-35)"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 { White naturally takes over the centre. }
4... d6 { Preventing e5. } 5. f3
{ This move is typical for the Saemisch Variation, named after the German Grandmaster Friedrich Saemisch. The idea is quite simple: since one aspect of Black's counterplay in the KID is the attack on the e4-pawn White immediately defends it securely. As an additional bonus the pawn on f3 covers the g4-square so this ensures a safe spot for the dark-squared bishop on e3.  However, there is a price to be paid for all these advantages. A long time ago, when GM Eduard Gufeld, a life-long and very successful KID player, was asked about the disadvantages of the Saemisch Variation he simply replied: 'Just ask the knight on g1!'  And he was right, the pawn on f3 takes away the natural developing square from the knight and the knight finds it difficult to get into the game - even when developed on e2 it blocks the bishop on f1 and needs further redeployment. As we shall see Black uses this problematic knight to create his counterplay. }
5... O-O
{ Black finishes development and is now ready to start play against White's centre. Now White has a choice where to develop his dark-squared bishop, to e3 or to g5.  Note that the move  6.Nge2  has no independent value because after  6...Nc6  White again needs to make the same choice about the development of the bishop, hence transposing to the main lines either after 6.Be3 or 6.Bg5. }
6. Be3 { This is the typical Saemisch development. } 6... Nc6
{ This is the Panno Variation. Black puts pressure on the d4-square and wants to play ...e5 and ...Nd4 if allowed. }
7. Nge2
{ In view of Black's threat of ...e5 and ...Nd4 this is White's only reasonable move. For example, the careless  7.Qd2?!  is met by  7...e5  8.d5  Nd4  with great play. }
7... a6
{ Black prepares for the possibility to push ...b5 and attack White's vulnerable c4-pawn. }
8. Qd2
{ The usual move. White finishes development and prepares Bh6,  0-0-0 or Rd1.  The move  8.h4  is met by  8...h5  and then play will be analogous as White again will likely play Qd2. }
8... Na5
{ A relatively fresh idea compared to the traditional move  8...Rb8  . Black immediately starts counterplay against the pawn on c4 and keeping the rook on a8 for now gives him additional tactical chances based on the fork ...Nb3. }
9. Nc1
{ This is White's best attempt. He safely covers the b3-square.  The naive  9.b3?!  shows the point of having the rook on a8 after  9...b5!  10.cxb5  axb5  11.Nxb5?  Nxb3  Black wins the exchange thanks to the pin on the a-file. }
9... Nd7 { Preparing the ...c5 push. } 10. Rb1
{ White removes the rook from the long diagonal and prepares b4 when the pawn on b4 will be defended by the rook. }
10... Rb8
{ Since there are no more tricks based on ...Nb3 @@StartBracket@@as we saw in some of the other lines when the a-file was opened@@EndBracket@@ Black moves the rook on the b-file and stays flexible with his plans.  One idea of the move is to support the ...b5 push in a more direct fashion @@StartBracket@@for example after ...c5, d5, ...b5 when Black hopes to obtain counterplay in Benko Gambit style@@EndBracket@@. }
11. b4 { White expands on the queenside. } 11... Nc6
{ The only retreat, now Black threatens ...e5 followed by ...Nd4. } 12. N1e2
{ The knight cannot defend the d4-square from b3 because the pawn on b4 is lost. The other moves allow ...e5 followed by ...Nd4. }
12... h5
{ A very interesting move that puts White in a strange situation that resembles a zugzwang! White's problem is the knight on e2 that cannot find its proper place and with it stuck on e2 @@StartBracket@@from where it controls d4 and prevents ...e5 and ...Nd4@@EndBracket@@ White cannot develop his kingside.  With his last move, Black takes away the g3-square from the knight as now Ng3 can be met by ...h4. So White is stuck!  Main Chapter and Extended Variations    The Saemisch Variation  Line 33  Line 34  Line 35 }
