[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "11. Averbakh Variation #1 (Line 45)"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 { White naturally takes over the centre. }
4... d6 { Preventing e5. } 5. Be2 O-O 6. Be3
{ This system is one of the most popular against the KID nowadays. Its idea is similar to the Makagonov System - White wants to advance on the kingside with g4, h4 etc. thus either suffocating Black's counterplay there or creating an attack on the kingside himself. The difference with the Makagonov is that here White controls the g4-square with the bishop on e2, while there White plays h3. }
6... e5 { Black strikes in the centre with the usual move. } 7. d5
{ White closes the centre and will continue with g4 and h4.  Note that the move  7.Nf3  leads to theGligoric Variation. }
7... Na6
{ Black develops the knight on a6 in order not to block the bishop on c8 and intends to put it on c5 to attack the pawn on e4. }
8. g4 { White continues with his plan. } 8... Nc5
{ Attacking the pawn on e4. Now White can defend it in two ways, with a pawn or with a bishop. }
9. f3 h5
{ Black undermines White's expanded kingside, using the fact that with his last move White closed the d1-h5 diagonal so there is no pressure on the h5-pawn. }
10. g5 { The most natural and main move. } 10... Nh7
{ Getting away with tempo. } 11. h4 f6
{ Black continues to put pressure on the pawn on g5 and manages to open the f-file. After the exchange of pawns the pawn on h4 will also become vulnerable. Now White has a choice, to exchange on f6 or to allow Black to take on g5. }
12. gxf6 Bxf6 { Black attacks the pawn on h4 so White's next move is forced. }
13. Bf2 { The only way to defend the pawn on h4. } 13... Be7
{ With this move Black opens the f-file and allows for ...Rf4, the typical move for Black in this line.  Main Chapter and Extended Variations    The Averbakh Variation  Line 45 }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "12. Averbakh Variation #2 (Line 48)"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 { White naturally takes over the centre. }
4... d6 { Preventing e5. } 5. Be2 O-O 6. Bg5
{ This development of the bishops on e2 and g5 is characteristic for the Averbakh Variation. The idea to put the bishop on g5 is to stop Black's typical central push ...e5. }
6... c5
{ To illustrate White's idea, pushing ...e5 loses after  6...e5??  7.dxe5  dxe5  8.Qxd8  Rxd8  9.Nd5  and Black loses material because of the pin on the h4-d8 diagonal and the weakness of the pawn on c7.  Pushing the c-pawn however aims to take immediate advantage of the lack of protection of the d4-square and the weakening of the long diagonal, the b2-pawn in particular, as White's dark-squared bishop left the c1-square. }
7. d5 { The only critical try. } 7... e6
{ Undermining White's centre and intending to open the e-file after ...exd5. }
8. Qd2
{ This is the main move and the reason why for many years Black's last move was considered imprecise because White stops ...h6. However, modern theory and practice have shown that Black can play ...h6 at a later stage with a powerful effect. }
8... exd5 { Black follows his plan and opens the e-file. } 9. exd5
{ Taking with the other pawn is worse as it gives White a problematic Modern Benoni position. After  9.cxd5?!  Re8  White's problem is the knight on g1. }
9... Qb6
{ The key move that rehabilitated the line for Black. For a very long time, it was considered that White's space advantage coupled with the pin on the h4-d8 diagonal give White a stable edge, but with the queen move Black introduces strong dynamism in the position.  There are two ideas to this move: the first one is to allow for ...Bf5 and ...Ne4 @@StartBracket@@the knight is free to jump now that there is no pin@@EndBracket@@ and the second one is to put pressure on the b2-pawn. }
10. Nf3 Bf5
{ Black follows his plan, he intends ...Ne4 next, so White's move is forced. }
11. Nh4 { Harassing the bishop on f5. } 11... Ne4
{ Black executes his main idea. } 12. Nxe4 Bxe4 13. f3
{ This was White's idea with 11.Nh4 - it seems the bishop is trapped on e4. }
13... h6
{ The absolutely key move for Black in the whole variation and one that makes the variation playable. As we had seen in the other lines the move ...h6 is often played and is always very strong. Here perhaps that strength is shown at its best.  The idea of the move is to chase away the bishop from g5 so that after taking on b2 the queen has a retreat to f6. }
14. Bxh6 { The natural capture. } 14... Bxh6
{ Forcing the queen to abandon the pawn on b2. } 15. Qxh6 Qxb2
{ Attacking the rook on a1 and allowing the queen to return to the kingside if needed along the long diagonal.  Main Chapter and Extended Variations    The Averbakh Variation  Line 48 }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "13. Makagonov System (Line 58)"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 { White naturally takes over the centre. }
4... d6 { Preventing e5. } 5. h3
{ This little move is the start of the Makagonov Variation, one of the most critical tries against the KID today. The 'little' move is quite venomous: White covers the g4-square like in the Saemisch Variation, only that he doesn't take away the f3-square from his knight. Additionally, by leaving the pawn on f2 his bishop on e3 will be more stable.  The move h3 also supports the g4-advance, aimed either at limiting Black's kingside counterplay by exerting more control over the f5-square or with the idea to start an attack on the kingside, by opening the g-file by gxf5 or by advancing g4-g5 and h4-h5.  Note that White can also start with  5.Nf3  O-O  6.h3  , but that just transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/2PPP3/2N5/PP3PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.h3  O-O  6.Nf3  . }
5... O-O
{ Black completes his kingside development. Now White has a choice to make - whether to develop the dark-squared bishop @@StartBracket@@to g5 or e3@@EndBracket@@ or to develop the knight to f3, keeping both possibilities for the dark-squared bishop @@StartBracket@@g5 or e3@@EndBracket@@ available.  Against all of these Black needs to decide in which direction he would like the game to proceed. He has three options: to go for the typical KID positions after executing ...e5, to aim for Modern Benoni positions with ...c5 or to give the game an original character with some alternative ideas. In this repertoire, we will go for the third option. }
6. Nf3
{ White develops the knight on its natural square from where it covers the d4-square and controls the e5-square. }
6... Nc6
{ Black fights for the central d4-square and threatens ...e5,  thus forcing White's next move. This move takes the game into less explored territory compared to the more common  6...e5  or  6...c5  . }
7. d5
{ Practically forced. Otherwise Black plays ...e5 and ...Nd4,  for example  7.Be3?!  e5  8.d5  Nd4  is great for Black and it's a transposition to the line @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/2PPP3/2N4P/PP3PP1/R1BQKBNR w KQ - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Be3  Nc6  7.Nf3?!  e5  8.d5  Nd4  @@StartBracket@@seethis line@@EndBracket@@. }
7... Nb4
{ Unlikethe line with 6.Be3 here the knight on f3 controls the e5-square so Black's knight has to go to b4. }
8. Be2
{ It's better for White to refrain from chasing away the knight on b4 too early because the knight wants to go to a6 and c5 anyway. }
8... e6
{ Black undermines White's pawn on d5. His idea is to put a rook on e8 and take on d5 when thanks to the pressure on e4 White will be forced to recapture with the e-pawn, resulting in a comfortable symmetrical pawn structure for Black. }
9. Be3
{ By developing the dark-squared bishop White allows for Nd2 to cover the pawn on e4 so as to be able to recapture cxd5 when Black takes ...exd5.  After the simple  9.O-O  Re8  play will likely transpose after White develops his dark-squared bishop to e3 or g5. }
9... Re8
{ Black continues with the plan, he wants to take on d5 now to force exd5 in view of the pressure on the pawn on e4. }
10. Nd2
{ White defends the pawn to allow cxd5.  After  10.O-O  exd5  11.exd5  a5  apart from the idea of ...Na6-c5 Black also has the typical exchange sacrifice ...Rxe3 at his disposal when his compensation will consist of his control of the dark squares and White's weaknesses on the e-file, the e3-pawn and the e4- and e5-squares. }
10... a5
{ The standard move on the queenside, obtaining better control over the dark squares c5 and b4. }
11. O-O Nd7
{ Black maintains flexibility and introduces the positional threat of ...Bxc3. This move is an improvement over the move  11...Bd7  played in the game Aronian-Carlsen from the Wijk aan Zee tournament in 2013.  Main Chapter and Extended Variations    The Makagonov System  Line 58 }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "14. Fianchetto Variation (Line 67)"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nf3
{ If White wishes to play the Fianchetto Variation he can also start with  3.g3  , but the game will transpose after  3...Bg7  4.Nf3  O-O  . }
3... Bg7 4. g3 O-O 5. Bg2 d6 { Black plays the usual KID moves. } 6. Nc3
{ White can also start with  6.O-O  c6  7.Nc3  , but this move gives him an additional possibility on the next move. }
6... c6
{ A very flexible move for Black. First of all, he shuts the long diagonal for White's fianchettoed bishop. He also keeps his options open:    He can play ...e5, ...d5 or even ...c5.  He prepares a possible ...b5.  He can develop his knight from b8 to d7 or a6.  The pawn move also opens the a5-d8 diagonal for the queen, giving her access to the b6 and a5 squares. }
7. O-O
{ This is by far the most common move and is often automatically played. } 7...
Bf5
{ Black develops the bishop and controls the e4-square, thus preventing White's expansion with e4. Now White has a wide choice, but his most ambitious moves revolve around the fight for the e4-square. }
8. Nh4
{ The most commonly played move. White attacks the bishop on f5 and intends to play e4. The drawback of the move is obvious - the knight is now on the rim. }
8... Be6 { Black moves away with tempo and provokes White to push d5. } 9. d5
{ The most ambitious.  After  9.b3  d5  10.cxd5  cxd5  followed by ...Nc6 Black has easy play as he has harmonious development and can play along the c-file while White still needs to get his knight on h4 back into the game. }
9... cxd5
{ Black opens the c-file as he intends to use it to create counterplay.  He has the interesting alternative  9...Bd7!?  at his disposal, postponing the capture on d5. }
10. cxd5 Bd7
{ From d7 the bishop supports the ...b5 push though Black should be careful about it as it weakens the c6-square. }
11. Nf3
{ White brings the knight back from the rim. Against other moves Black's play won't differ much from the main line. Generally speaking Black's piece placement in these lines is fairly straightforward:    The knight goes to a6 and likely to c5.  The queen to a5 or b6.  One rook comes to c8.  Then he plays on the queenside using the c5 and b4 squares in combination with a possible pawn advance with ...a5-a4 or ...b5.  
Examples for this set-up can be seen after  11.e4  Na6  12.Be3  Rc8  with ...Nc5 next...   ... or  11.Be3  Na6  12.Bd4  Nc5  . }
11... Na6 { Black follows his plan. } 12. Nd4
{ Centralising the knight. White's ideal set-up here is to place a bishop on e3,  the queen on d2 and put the rooks on the c- and d-files.  If White decides to centralise the bishop instead, then after  12.Be3  Qa5  13.Bd4  Nc5  Black again obtains comfortable development. }
12... Qb6
{ Targeting the knight on d4 and the pawn on b2.  Here the typical  12...Qa5  can be met by  13.Nb3  , but @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pp1bppbp/n2p1np1/3P4/3N4/2N3P1/PP2PPBP/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 4 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Nc5  13.Rb1  a5  is possible. }
13. Nb3 { Getting away from harm's way. } 13... Nc5
{ Attacking the knight on b3.  The alternative is another typical rearrangement of Black's pieces after  13...Rfc8  14.Be3  Qd8  followed by ...Nc5 or ...Nc7 and a possible advance of the queenside pawns. }
14. Be3 Ng4 { Harassing White's bishop. } 15. Nxc5
{ The exchange of the dark-squared bishops is in Black's favour.  After  15.Bd4  Bxd4  16.Qxd4  Rfc8  White is left with a passive bishop on g2 and Black has unhindered control over the dark squares, e5 and c5 in particular. }
15... dxc5 16. Bd2 Ne5
{ Black has a comfortable position. His immediate threats are ...Nc4 and ...Qxb2 while more generally he'd like to advance his queenside majority, for example by ...Rac8 and ...c4.  Main Chapter and Extended Variations    The Fianchetto Variation  Line 67 }
