[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "15. Various Systems #1 (Line 68)"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 { White naturally takes over the centre. }
4... d6 { Preventing e5. } 5. Nge2
{ The knight is en route to g3, from where it controls the f5 and e4 squares. From g3 it also aids the h4-h5 advance. }
5... O-O 6. Ng3 e5 { Black reacts in a typical KID fashion. } 7. d5 a5
{ Another typical move after White has closed the centre: Black grabs some space on the queenside and obtains better control over the dark squares on the queenside, b4 and c5 in particular. }
8. Be2 { The bishop from e2 supports the h4-h5 idea. } 8... Na6
{ Black develops the knight on a6 from where it is ready to join the game by jumping to c5. }
9. h4 h5
{ It is important to stop White's idea of h5 because allowing it gives White the options to either open the h-file by taking on g6 or to shut Black's kingside by playing h6. }
10. Bg5
{ The pin on the h4-d8 diagonal introduces the threat of Bxh5, so Black is well-advised to avoid it. }
10... Qe8
{ Removing the queen from the pin and avoiding the dangerous sacrifice on h5. }
11. Qd2 Nc5
{ Activating the knight and putting more pressure on the pawn on e4. Black can play on both sides of the board, with ...c6 on the queenside and with ...Nh7 and ...f5 on the kingside.  Main Chapter and Extended Variations    Various Systems  Line 68 }
