[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "16. Various Systems #2 (Line 77)"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 { White naturally takes over the centre. }
4... d6 { Preventing e5. } 5. Bd3
{ This system was popularised by GM Yasser Seirawan. White intends to develop his king's knight to e2, thus allowing several things:    f3 to support the pawn on e4, like in the Saemisch Variation.  To play f4 as a reply to Black's ...f5, thus stopping Black's kingside advance.  To play Ng3, increasing White's control over the e4- and f5-squares.  
The drawback of this setup is the decreased control over the d4-square as the bishop on d3 severs the connection between the queen on d1 and the pawn on d4. }
5... O-O 6. Nge2 Nc6
{ Black immediately targets the weakened spot in White's position. } 7. O-O e5
{ Black attacks White's vulnerable d4-spot. } 8. d5 Nd4
{ Again Black takes advantage of White's insufficient control over the d4-square by placing his knight in a dominant position. }
9. Bg5 c5
{ Black secures his knight on d4. Now in case of an exchange he will have a protected passed pawn there. }
10. Qd2 a6
{ Both a prophylactic move @@StartBracket@@taking away the b5-square from the white knight so Black can play ...Qc7 not fearing attacks on his queen@@EndBracket@@ and an active move @@StartBracket@@preparing the ...b5-push, an idea we also see in the line @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp2pbp/3p1np1/3Pp3/2PnP3/2N3P1/PP2NPBP/R1BQK2R w KQ - 1 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Nxd4  exd4  10.Ne2  @@StartBracket@@seethis line@@EndBracket@@ @@EndBracket@@. }
11. Nxd4
{ If White doesn't take then Black plays ...Qa5, ...Rb8 in order to achieve the ...b5-push. }
11... exd4
{ Black takes with the e-pawn in order to have a pawn mass in the centre connected with his queenside. The capture with the e-pawn also gives him access to the e5-square. }
12. Ne2 b5
{ Activating the queenside pawn mass.  Main Chapter and Extended Variations    Various Systems  Line 77 }
