[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. The Classical Variations"]
[Black "01. Gligoric Variation (7.Be3) with 9.Qc2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 { White naturally takes over the centre. }
4... d6 { Preventing e5. } 5. Nf3 O-O
{ Black finished the development of the kingside and is now ready to play in the centre. }
6. Be2
{ This is White's most natural development, preparing short castle, and that is why this variation is called the Classical Variation. }
6... e5
{ The central strike that characterises the King's Indian Defence. Its idea is to attack the d4-square and either provoke White to react by pushing d5 or by taking on e5,  or to capture on d4 and open the e-file and the long-diagonal for the fianchettoed bishop. Now White has 4 main options to choose from:  1. He can keep the tension in the centre by castling.  2. He can keep the tension in the centre by developing the dark-squared bishop to e3 with  7.Be3  - the Gligoric Variation.  3. He can blockade the centre immediately with  7.d5  - the Petrosian Variation.  4. He can exchange the pawns and then the queens after  7.dxe5  - the Exchange Variation. }
7. Be3
{ This is the Gligoric Variation. Its idea is to postpone castling and keep the tension in the centre. It caused Garry Kasparov certain problems in the last match Karpov-Kasparov played in New York and Lyon in 1990. Not surprisingly, the advances of theory and practice since then discovered reliable ways for Black how to deal with this system. }
7... exd4
{ This is the most straightforward and direct approach. Black opens the long diagonal, the centre and the e-file while White's king is still uncastled. }
8. Nxd4
{ The natural and the only good recapture. Taking with a bishop only gives Black a tempo for development after  8.Bxd4?!  Re8  @@StartBracket@@attacking the pawn on e4@@EndBracket@@  9.Nd2  Bh6!  and after ...Nc6 next the bishop on d4 is short of squares - White will have to allow the wrecking of his structure after Be3 ...Bxe3,  fxe3 which gives Black a clear advantage. }
8... Re8 { Attacking the pawn on e4. } 9. Qc2
{ This is almost never played, but it's not bad. Black should continue along the same lines with: }
9... c6 { Preparing ...d5. } 10. O-O-O
{ If White is aggressive and plays 10.0-0-0 then Black has: } 10... Na6
{ Intending ...Nb4 to harass the queen and indirectly the pawn on e4 she is defending. }
11. f3 d5 { Black obtains good counterplay in the centre. A sample line is: }
12. cxd5 Nxd5 { Black uses the pin on the e-file. } 13. exd5 Rxe3 14. Bxa6 bxa6
15. Nxc6 Qb6
{ With fantastic compensation for the pawn in view of the pair of bishops and the great activity of Black's pieces that can easily transform into an attack on the queenside. }
*

