{ The central strike that characterises the King's Indian Defence. Its idea is to attack the d4-square and either provoke White to react by pushing d5 or by taking on e5,  or to capture on d4 and open the e-file and the long-diagonal for the fianchettoed bishop. Now White has 4 main options to choose from:  1. He can keep the tension in the centre by castling  7.O-O   2. He can keep the tension in the centre by developing the dark-squared bishop to e3 with  7.Be3  - the Gligoric Variation.  3. He can blockade the centre immediately with  7.d5  - the Petrosian Variation.  4. He can exchange the pawns and then the queens after  7.dxe5  - the Exchange Variation. }
7. Be3
{ This is the Gligoric Variation. Its idea is to postpone castling and keep the tension in the centre. It caused Garry Kasparov certain problems in the last match Karpov-Kasparov played in New York and Lyon in 1990. Not surprisingly, the advances of theory and practice since then discovered reliable ways for Black how to deal with this system. }
7... exd4
{ This is the most straightforward and direct approach. Black opens the long diagonal, the centre and the e-file while White's king is still uncastled. }
8. Nxd4
{ The natural and the only good recapture. Taking with a bishop only gives Black a tempo for development after  8.Bxd4?!  Re8  @@StartBracket@@attacking the pawn on e4@@EndBracket@@  9.Nd2  Bh6!  and after ...Nc6 next the bishop on d4 is short of squares - White will have to allow the wrecking of his structure after Be3 ...Bxe3,  fxe3 which gives Black a clear advantage. }
8... Re8 { Attacking the pawn on e4. } 9. f3
{ Strengthening the centre, but now the bishop on e3 is somewhat loose and Black uses this fact to strike in the centre with ...c6 and ...d5. }
9... c6
{ Irrelevant of what White does next, the central thrust ...d5 is inevitably coming on the next move. }
10. O-O { This is the most natural move, but also the most harmless one. }
10... d5 { Black executes his plan. } 11. cxd5 Nxd5
{ Is the move Black should remember because  11...cxd5?!  12.Qb3  with Rad1 to come gives White an initiative. }
12. Nxd5 { Otherwise, the bishop has to move, allowing  12.Bf2?!  Nf4  . }
12... cxd5 13. Qb3
{ Liberating the d-file for the rook. The alternative is  13.Rc1  when the simplest is to play for quick development with  13...Nc6  14.Nxc6  bxc6  15.Rxc6  Bb7  with ...dxe4 next with comfortable equality. }
13... Nc6 { Black continues with his development. } 14. Rad1
{ White's hope is to put pressure on the d-file and use the opposition of the rook on d1 and the queen on d8. However his attempts are crippled by the loose position of the bishop on e3. }
14... Be5
{ A rare, but very good move that also serves as a shortcut to avoid the massive theory after  14...Nxd4  15.Bxd4  Bxd4  16.Rxd4  Qf6  which equalises for Black but the lines go deep into the endgame. With the bishop move, Black threatens ...Qh4,  thus forcing White to do something. }
15. Nxc6 { A timid move like  15.Nc2  allows  15...d4  . } 15... bxc6 16. Qc2
{ Targeting the pawn on c6 and avoiding a possible attack on the b-file after ...Rb8,  for example  16.exd5?!  is not very good in view of  16...Rb8  and White's position becomes loose as both the pawn on b2 and the bishops on the e-file need protection. }
16... d4
{ Black advances the d-pawn and this takes the sting out of White's pressure on the d-file. The alternative  16...Bd7  is perfectly playable too. }
17. Qxc6
{ This is the most direct, taking the pawn. The alternatives are easy to deal with, for example:  A@@EndBracket@@  17.Bf2  Qd6  puts pressure on the h2-b8 diagonal.   B@@EndBracket@@  17.f4  Qb6!  removes the queen from the d-file and attacks the bishop on e3.   C@@EndBracket@@  17.Qc5  Qh4  is tricky for White as the natural  18.g3?  loses to  18...Bxg3!  19.hxg3  Qxg3  20.Kh1  dxe3  . }
17... Bd7 { Breaking the pin on the d-file with tempo. } 18. Qb7
{ Still keeping an eye on the bishop on d7. } 18... dxe3
{ Black has more than one decent move here, for example,  18...Rb8  , or the more complex  18...Be6  , all of which give him satisfactory play. }
19. Rxd7 Qh4 { Black now forces a perpetual after: } 20. g3 Bxg3 21. hxg3 Qxg3+
{ With a draw. } *

