{ Irrelevant of what White does next, the central thrust ...d5 is inevitably coming on the next move. }
10. Qd2 { White defends the bishop but his king is still in the centre. } 10...
d5 { Black executes his idea, attacking the pawn on e4. } 11. exd5
{ White takes with the e-pawn so that it doesn't hang anymore. } 11... cxd5 12.
O-O
{ The most common move and one where the others transpose, for example,  12.Rd1  Nc6  13.O-O  we transpose to @@StartFEN@@rnbqr1k1/pp3pbp/5np1/3p4/2PN4/2N1BP2/PP1QB1PP/R3K2R w KQ - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12.O-O  Nc6  13.Rad1  .   Or  12.c5  Nc6  @@StartBracket@@though Black can try to take advantage of this move-order by playing 12...Nbd7!?@@EndBracket@@  13.O-O  and we have transposed to @@StartFEN@@rnbqr1k1/pp3pbp/5np1/3p4/2PN4/2N1BP2/PP1QB1PP/R3K2R w KQ - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12.O-O  Nc6  13.c5  . }
12... Nc6 { Black continues with his natural development. } 13. c5
{ The most ambitious move, creating a queenside majority. As in the lines after  10.Bf2  White's hope is to keep the d5-pawn safely blockaded and to advance on the queenside. }
13... Bf8
{ Kasparov's spectacular idea from the 11th game of his last match with Karpov in New York and Lyon in 1990 is still playable, though after  13...Rxe3!?  14.Qxe3  Qf8  a possible improvement for White is  15.Rfd1!?  when it appears that White has some slight pull, for example,  15...Qxc5  16.Bb5  Bh6  17.Qf2!   Still, Kasparov's exchange sacrifice is up in the air in all these lines, as we shall see. Apart from the obvious idea to attack the pawn on c5,  the move ...Bf8 prepares the re-routing of the knight on f6 via h5 and g7 and then either to f5 or to e6. This re-routing is a typical idea in these positions and one that we also see in the lines after 10.Bf2. }
14. Nxc6
{ The only way for White to defend the pawn on c5 and continue with his plan of queenside expansion, but now Black safely defends the pawn on d5. }
14... bxc6 { Establishing a more solid central structure. } 15. b4
{ White continues with his plan. } 15... Nh5
{ Following the plan. Black has other good options as well, for example, he can try the sharper  15...a5  16.b5  Rxe3!  17.Qxe3  d4  18.Rad1  Bxc5  with good compensation.   Or he can start with  15...Rb8  16.a3  a5  17.b5  cxb5  18.Bxb5  and now sacrifice on e3 with  18...Rxe3!  19.Qxe3  d4  20.Qd3  Bf5  21.Ne4  Bxc5  again with good compensation in view of the activity of his pieces. }
16. Rfd1 { If  16.b5  Bd7  Black keeps his position solid. } 16... Ng7
{ Black will put the knight either on f5 or e6, depending on White's reaction. }
17. Bf2
{ Getting out of harm's way on the e-file. In the case of  17.b5  Bb7  18.Bf2  Ne6!  is correct as White's b5 weakened the pawn on c5,  so the knight is better placed on e6 from where it attacks it. }
17... Nf5 { From f5 the knight also allows for ideas based on ...Bh6. } 18. b5
{ White waited for Black to move the knight to f5 so he now advances with the b-pawn, not fearing an attack on his pawn on c5 as in the note to White's 17th move. }
18... Bd7
{ Black calmly defends the pawn on c6. The middlegame is complex but Black's position is very harmonious. His ideas are to play ...Bh6 and invade the e3-square, ...Qf6 to develop the queen on the long diagonal, or simply ...Qc7, connecting the rooks. He should also always have in mind the advance of his passed d-pawn with ...d4 as this can suddenly give him tactical possibilities. }
