{ Black's most active attempt. Now with his development finished he wants to take on d4 and advance his d5-pawn with the help from the knight on g7 after ...Ne6. To help this operation the bishop on f5 covers the e4-square so the attacked knight on c3 @@StartBracket@@after Black's ...d4@@EndBracket@@ won't be able to safely come to e4. }
17. Rac1
{ With this move White finishes development and lends extra support to the c5-pawn. White has many moves at his disposal here, but generally speaking, if Black is allowed he should take ...Bxd4 and follow up with ...Ne6. Here's a brief overview of White's options:  A@@EndBracket@@ After  17.Nxf5  Nxf5  18.f4  Bd4!  Black exchanges the dark-squared bishops and follows up with ...d4.   B@@EndBracket@@ In case of the consolidatory  17.Bf1  Bxd4  18.Bxd4  Ne6  19.Bf2  d4  Black executes his plan perfectly - note that once the knight moves from c3 the queen can come to d5.   C@@EndBracket@@ Similar is  17.Bb5  Bxd4  18.Bxd4  Ne6  as was played in the game Sarana-Grischuk from the World Rapid Championship in 2019.   D@@EndBracket@@ The move  17.Ndb5  avoids the exchange on d4 but it allows the pawn to advance with  17...d4!  the point being that  18.Nxd4  Bxd4  19.Bxd4  Bc2!  makes sure Black regains the pawn in view of the many tactical threats. }
17... Bxd4
{ Following the general rule Black eliminates the blockading knight and follows up with ...Ne6, increasing control over the d4-square. }
18. Bxd4 Ne6
{ Apart from attacking the bishop on d4 and supporting the advance of the d-pawn the knight from e6 also has another option, to go to g5 from where it can cause problems on the light squares h3 and f3. }
19. Bf2 d4 { The pawn was attacked so it moves forward. } 20. Nb5
{ Note the importance of the bishop on f5,  the knight couldn't go to e4 in view of  20.Ne4?  Bxe4  21.fxe4  Ng5!  and White's position collapses as the pawn on e4 falls. }
20... Qf6
{ A very important novelty that gives Black fantastic tactical counterplay. The idea of the move is to prepare ...Ng5 by liberating the d8-square for the rook @@StartBracket@@the immediate  20...Ng5?  doesn't work in view of the simple capture  21.Nxd4  - after the queen move to f6 Black would have the move ...Rad8 pinning the knight on d4@@EndBracket@@.  What is curious and quite surprising for this position is that Black creates strong tactical counterplay without his dark-squared bishop, a rare case for the KID. But its absence is heftily compensated by the synergy of all the remaining pieces! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. The Classical Variations"]
[Black "07. Petrosian Variation (7.d5) with 8.h3. White plays 10.Be3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 { White naturally takes over the centre. }
4... d6 { Preventing e5. } 5. Nf3 O-O
{ Black finished the development of the kingside and is now ready to play in the centre. }
6. Be2
{ This is White's most natural development, preparing short castle, and that is why this variation is called the Classical Variation. }
6... e5
{ The central strike that characterises the King's Indian Defence. Its idea is to attack the d4-square and either provoke White to react by pushing d5 or by taking on e5,  or to capture on d4 and open the e-file and the long-diagonal for the fianchettoed bishop. Now White has 4 main options to choose from:  1. He can keep the tension in the centre by castling  7.O-O   2. He can keep the tension in the centre by developing the dark-squared bishop to e3 with  7.Be3  - the Gligoric Variation.  3. He can blockade the centre immediately with  7.d5  - the Petrosian Variation.  4. He can exchange the pawns and then the queens after  7.dxe5  - the Exchange Variation. }
7. d5
{ The Petrosian Variation, invented and made popular by the 9th World Champion in the late 50s and early 60s. White immediately closes the centre and intends to start his usual queenside play by advancing the pawns with b4 and c5. }
7... Nbd7
{ The idea of this move is to develop and keep an eye on the c5-square, where the knight can jump in order to attack the pawn on e4 and stop or slow down White's intended queenside expansion.  When the Petrosian Variation was at the height of its popularity in the late 50s and early 60s this move was the most common way to meet it. Later on the move 7...a5 came to the fore while the third option 7...Na6 never really caught on.  Today the move  7...a5  is considered the main line against the Petrosian Variation, but from a practical perspective, it is not an easy move to play because all White's 3 main moves against it -  8.Bg5  ,  8.Be3  and  8.h3  lead to a lot of deeply analysed theoretical lines.   Therefore I turned my attention to the alternatives and I soon discovered that the problem with  7...Na6  was the move  8.Nd2!  when I couldn't find a satisfactory way for Black.   Luckily, the 'original' reaction with  7...Nbd7  hid quite a few improvements and turned out to be very compact theoretically. }
8. h3
{ With this move White tries to transpose to the Makagonov System where he would have avoided many options Black has against it @@StartBracket@@and our proposed reaction in particular@@EndBracket@@. However, nothing comes for free and there is a big difference here that works in Black's favour. }
8... Nc5 { Continuing naturally, attacking the pawn on e4. } 9. Qc2 Nh5
{ The first important point. In case of the automatic  9...a5  10.Bg5  @@StartBracket@@or  10.g4  @@EndBracket@@ White would have achieved his desirable transposition to theMakagonov. }
10. Be3 { In case of  10.Bg5  f6  11.Be3  f5  we have a transposition. } 10...
f5 { Black continues with his usual kingside play. } 11. Bxc5
{ A typical exchange in the positions that arise from theMakagonov Variation. White voluntarily gives his important dark-squared bishop in order to establish stronger control over the light squares.  The underlying logic is that the knight on c5 was controlling both d3 and e4 and White eliminates it so that he can play Bd3 to put pressure on the pawn on f5. }
11... dxc5 12. O-O-O
{ In case of  12.Nd2  Nf6  13.Bd3  Ne8!  Black lands the knight on the comfortable blockading square d6 with excellent play - after the elimination of the knight on c5 it is the other knight that takes over the control over the light squares in the centre. }
12... Qe7
{ Removing the queen from the d-file. Black can also start with  12...a6  , as his plan to create play on the queenside includes the moves ...a6,  ...Bd7 and ...b5. }
13. Nd2 Nf6
{ Black naturally re-routes the knight to the ideal blockading square on d6 from where it will also support the ...b5-push. }
14. Bd3 { Attacking the pawn on f5. } 14... Ne8
{ Defending the pawn on f5 and continuing with the plan. } 15. exf5 gxf5
{ Black must take with a pawn in order not to give White absolute control over the e4-square. }
16. f3
{ White consistently continues with his plan to increase his control over the light squares. He now prepares g4. }
16... Nd6 { Black lands the knight on its best square. } 17. g4 Kh8
{ Getting the king out of the g-file that can be opened at any moment. Now if White does nothing Black wants to play ...a6, ...Bd7, ...b5, ...Rb8 and start an attack on the queenside. }
18. gxf5
{ If White continues with his plan to obtain control over the e4-square with 18.gxf5 then: }
18... Nxf5 { The knight wants to land on d4, so White must eliminate it. } 19.
Bxf5 Bxf5 20. Nde4
{ White achieved his plan, but Black now has the pair of bishops. } 20... Bh6+
21. Kb1 Be3
{ Black activates the dark-squared bishop by putting it on the dominating d4-square. The position is dynamically balanced but with the active bishops Black has very good chances as he still wants to open the b-file on the queenside by pushing ...b5. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. The Classical Variations"]
[Black "08. Petrosian Variation (7.d5) with 8.h3. White plays 10.g3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 { White naturally takes over the centre. }
4... d6 { Preventing e5. } 5. Nf3 O-O
{ Black finished the development of the kingside and is now ready to play in the centre. }
6. Be2
{ This is White's most natural development, preparing short castle, and that is why this variation is called the Classical Variation. }
6... e5
{ The central strike that characterises the King's Indian Defence. Its idea is to attack the d4-square and either provoke White to react by pushing d5 or by taking on e5,  or to capture on d4 and open the e-file and the long-diagonal for the fianchettoed bishop. Now White has 4 main options to choose from:  1. He can keep the tension in the centre by castling  7.O-O   2. He can keep the tension in the centre by developing the dark-squared bishop to e3 with  7.Be3  - the Gligoric Variation.  3. He can blockade the centre immediately with  7.d5  - the Petrosian Variation.  4. He can exchange the pawns and then the queens after  7.dxe5  - the Exchange Variation. }
7. d5
{ The Petrosian Variation, invented and made popular by the 9th World Champion in the late 50s and early 60s. White immediately closes the centre and intends to start his usual queenside play by advancing the pawns with b4 and c5. }
7... Nbd7
{ The idea of this move is to develop and keep an eye on the c5-square, where the knight can jump in order to attack the pawn on e4 and stop or slow down White's intended queenside expansion.  When the Petrosian Variation was at the height of its popularity in the late 50s and early 60s this move was the most common way to meet it. Later on the move 7...a5 came to the fore while the third option 7...Na6 never really caught on.  Today the move  7...a5  is considered the main line against the Petrosian Variation, but from a practical perspective, it is not an easy move to play because all White's 3 main moves against it -  8.Bg5  ,  8.Be3  and  8.h3  lead to a lot of deeply analysed theoretical lines.   Therefore I turned my attention to the alternatives and I soon discovered that the problem with  7...Na6  was the move  8.Nd2!  when I couldn't find a satisfactory way for Black.   Luckily, the 'original' reaction with  7...Nbd7  hid quite a few improvements and turned out to be very compact theoretically. }
8. h3
{ With this move White tries to transpose to the Makagonov System where he would have avoided many options Black has against it @@StartBracket@@and our proposed reaction in particular@@EndBracket@@. However, nothing comes for free and there is a big difference here that works in Black's favour. }
8... Nc5 { Continuing naturally, attacking the pawn on e4. } 9. Qc2 Nh5
{ The first important point. In case of the automatic  9...a5  10.Bg5  @@StartBracket@@or  10.g4  @@EndBracket@@ White would have achieved his desirable transposition to theMakagonov. }
10. g3
{ White prevents ...Nf4. In case of  10.b4?!  Nd7  White again won't have safe shelter for his king as Black can open the a-file by a timely ...a5,  especially as the rook on a1 is not defended. }
10... f5
{ Black continues naturally. He will either put more pressure on the e4-pawn with ...Nf6 or he will open the f-file and the b1-h7 diagonal with ...fxe4 followed by ...Bf5. }
11. Bg5
{ In this moment we see the second important difference from the usual Makagonov positions. In these positions, White usually likes to have exf5 ...gxf5 inserted so that he can then attack the f5-pawn by g4 or Bd3 @@StartBracket@@after eliminating the knight on c5@@EndBracket@@. However here that is not possible because after  11.exf5?  Bxf5  White is weak on the a2-g8 diagonal and after  12.Qd1  e4!  Black has a big advantage in view of the threat ...Nd3.   The tension between the pawns on e4 and f5 is in Black's favour because only he can release it, thus limiting White's active possibilities. Another tactical point that works for Black here is that the typical developing move  11.Be3?  doesn't work in view of  11...Nxe4  12.Nxe4  fxe4  13.Nd2  @@StartBracket@@in case of  13.Qxe4  Black follows with the same move  13...Nf4  @@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp3bp/3p2p1/3Pp2n/2P1p3/4B1PP/PPQNBP2/R3K2R b KQ - 1 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Nf4!  when Black wins the pair of bishops either after ...Ng2-Nxe3 or the simple ...Nxe2. }
11... Qe8
{ Black moves the queen to e8 from where she keeps an eye on the knight on h5. It is sometimes important to have the knight on h5 defended after exf5 ...gxf5 as then White won't have tactics based on the discovered attacks like Nxe5, when the bishop on e2 attacks the knight on h5. }
12. Nd2 Bd7
{ Black can play  12...Nf6  , which is perfectly viable, but it's better to start queenside play faster. Black wants to support the ...b5 push and also to allow for ...Na4. }
13. O-O-O
{ In case of  13.b4  Nxe4  14.Ncxe4  fxe4  15.Nxe4  Bf5  Black has good play because the white king has no safe shelter on either wing nor is he safe in the centre. }
13... a6 { Preparing ...b5. } 14. Be3 Na4
{ Now Black can avoid the exchange on c5 thanks to the move ...Bd7. After the exchange on a4 he will provoke a weakening of White's queenside by b3. Additionally, by removing the knight on c5 he also threatens ...f4 to trap the bishop on e3. }
15. Nxa4 Bxa4 16. b3 Bd7 { The threat is still ...f4. } 17. exf5 Bxf5
{ It is also possible to take with the pawn,  17...gxf5  18.g4  Nf4  with unclear play. }
18. Ne4 b5 { Introducing tension on the queenside. } 19. g4 Bxe4 20. Qxe4 Nf4
{ Black has good play as the long-term problem of White's king will never disappear. }
