[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. The Classical Variations"]
[Black "09. Petrosian Variation (7.d5) with 8.Be3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 { White naturally takes over the centre. }
4... d6 { Preventing e5. } 5. Nf3 O-O
{ Black finished the development of the kingside and is now ready to play in the centre. }
6. Be2
{ This is White's most natural development, preparing short castle, and that is why this variation is called the Classical Variation. }
6... e5
{ The central strike that characterises the King's Indian Defence. Its idea is to attack the d4-square and either provoke White to react by pushing d5 or by taking on e5,  or to capture on d4 and open the e-file and the long-diagonal for the fianchettoed bishop. Now White has 4 main options to choose from:  1. He can keep the tension in the centre by castling  7.O-O   2. He can keep the tension in the centre by developing the dark-squared bishop to e3 with  7.Be3  - the Gligoric Variation.  3. He can blockade the centre immediately with  7.d5  - the Petrosian Variation.  4. He can exchange the pawns and then the queens after  7.dxe5  - the Exchange Variation. }
7. d5
{ The Petrosian Variation, invented and made popular by the 9th World Champion in the late 50s and early 60s. White immediately closes the centre and intends to start his usual queenside play by advancing the pawns with b4 and c5. }
7... Nbd7
{ The idea of this move is to develop and keep an eye on the c5-square, where the knight can jump in order to attack the pawn on e4 and stop or slow down White's intended queenside expansion.  When the Petrosian Variation was at the height of its popularity in the late 50s and early 60s this move was the most common way to meet it. Later on the move 7...a5 came to the fore while the third option 7...Na6 never really caught on.  Today the move  7...a5  is considered the main line against the Petrosian Variation, but from a practical perspective, it is not an easy move to play because all White's 3 main moves against it -  8.Bg5  ,  8.Be3  and  8.h3  lead to a lot of deeply analysed theoretical lines.   Therefore I turned my attention to the alternatives and I soon discovered that the problem with  7...Na6  was the move  8.Nd2!  when I couldn't find a satisfactory way for Black.   Luckily, the 'original' reaction with  7...Nbd7  hid quite a few improvements and turned out to be very compact theoretically. }
8. Be3
{ White develops the bishop with the idea to achieve the ideal set-up after Nd2 next, but Black easily prevents this with his next move. }
8... Ng4 { Harassing the bishop and preventing White's intention. } 9. Bg5 f6
{ Continuing to harass the bishop. } 10. Bh4
{ Going back along the c1-h6 diagonal allows for a quick ...f5,  for example  10.Bd2  f5  11.Ng5  Nc5  with good play for Black. }
10... a5
{ Securing the c5-square for the knight. The move  10...h5?!  , which was played by Kasparov in his rapid game against Kramnik in 1994 is not very good because White can use the h5-pawn to latch onto with a later g4 to speed up his kingside attack. }
11. Nd2 Nh6
{ The knight is en route to f7, from where it will be very useful: it lends extra cover to the d6-pawn and also will defend the bishop on h6. In some lines it can also jump to g5. }
12. f3
{ White liberates the f2-square for the bishop from where it can support White's play on the queenside. }
12... Nf7 { Black continues with his plan. } 13. Qc2
{ The most flexible move, keeping both options for castling. } 13... Nc5
{ Landing the knight on the comfortable c5-square. } 14. O-O-O
{ This is more testing than the alternative castling. After  14.O-O  Bh6  @@StartBracket@@with the idea of ...Be3-d4@@EndBracket@@  15.Bf2  b6  @@StartBracket@@securing the knight on c5 so Black can recapture ...bxc5 in case White takes Bxc5@@EndBracket@@  16.b3  f5  with ...Bf4 and ...Qg5 next with a pleasant initiative on the kingside. }
14... a4
{ Controlling the b3-square and intending ...a3 at some point, to weaken the dark squares around White's king. }
15. Bf2
{ White removes the bishop from in front of the h-pawn and now intends to advance with h4 and g4. }
15... f5
{ Without a pin on the h4-d8 diagonal now this move is possible. Black has an interesting alternative in  15...c6!?  with the idea of ...Qa5,  which leads to very complicated play. }
16. h4 Bd7
{ Finishing the development of the last light piece. Black's idea now is to push ...a3 when the bishop on d7 allows for ...Na4 in case White reacts with b4. }
17. h5
{ White also continues with his plan. If he stops ...a3 by playing the move himself, this allows Black the following idea:  17.a3  Bh6!  18.Kb1  Bxd2!  19.Qxd2  Nb3  which gives him good counterplay - he got rid of the passive dark-squared bishop and will soon land the knight on the dominant d4-square, after preparing the jump by pushing ...c5. }
17... a3 { Black achieves his goal to weaken the position of White's king. }
18. b3
{ In case of  18.b4  Na4  we see the importance of having the bishop on d7. }
18... Na6
{ The knight is immediately coming to a more active square - from b4 it will harass the white queen and keep an eye on the a2-pawn. }
19. hxg6 { Opening the h-file. } 19... hxg6 20. Kb1
{ Liberating the c1-square for the queen. } 20... Nb4 21. Qc1 c5
{ Cemeting the knight on b4. Now if given time Black will prepare the ...b5 push. The middlegame is a typical complex KID. One idea for Black to have in mind is that in case of the opening of the f-file after g4, ...fxg4, fxg4 the typical exchange sacrifice ...Rf4 would be very good. Here's a sample line: }
22. g4 fxg4 23. Be3 { The automatic  23.fxg4?!  allows  23...Bh6! } 23... Ng5
24. fxg4 Rf4
{ With good counterplay as White can never take that rook as it will lead to the awakening of the bishop on g7 with catastrophic consequences for White on the long diagonal. }
