[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. The Classical Variations"]
[Black "10. Petrosian Variation (7.d5) with 8.Bg5. White plays 11.Nd2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 { White naturally takes over the centre. }
4... d6 { Preventing e5. } 5. Nf3 O-O
{ Black finished the development of the kingside and is now ready to play in the centre. }
6. Be2
{ This is White's most natural development, preparing short castle, and that is why this variation is called the Classical Variation. }
6... e5
{ The central strike that characterises the King's Indian Defence. Its idea is to attack the d4-square and either provoke White to react by pushing d5 or by taking on e5,  or to capture on d4 and open the e-file and the long-diagonal for the fianchettoed bishop. Now White has 4 main options to choose from:  1. He can keep the tension in the centre by castling  7.O-O   2. He can keep the tension in the centre by developing the dark-squared bishop to e3 with  7.Be3  - the Gligoric Variation.  3. He can blockade the centre immediately with  7.d5  - the Petrosian Variation.  4. He can exchange the pawns and then the queens after  7.dxe5  - the Exchange Variation. }
7. d5
{ The Petrosian Variation, invented and made popular by the 9th World Champion in the late 50s and early 60s. White immediately closes the centre and intends to start his usual queenside play by advancing the pawns with b4 and c5. }
7... Nbd7
{ The idea of this move is to develop and keep an eye on the c5-square, where the knight can jump in order to attack the pawn on e4 and stop or slow down White's intended queenside expansion.  When the Petrosian Variation was at the height of its popularity in the late 50s and early 60s this move was the most common way to meet it. Later on the move 7...a5 came to the fore while the third option 7...Na6 never really caught on.  Today the move  7...a5  is considered the main line against the Petrosian Variation, but from a practical perspective, it is not an easy move to play because all White's 3 main moves against it -  8.Bg5  ,  8.Be3  and  8.h3  lead to a lot of deeply analysed theoretical lines.   Therefore I turned my attention to the alternatives and I soon discovered that the problem with  7...Na6  was the move  8.Nd2!  when I couldn't find a satisfactory way for Black.   Luckily, the 'original' reaction with  7...Nbd7  hid quite a few improvements and turned out to be very compact theoretically. }
8. Bg5
{ This is Petrosian's prophylactic idea - with the pin on the h4-d8 diagonal White tries to slow down Black's plan of kingside expansion that consists of moving the knight from f6 and pushing ...f5.  Note that the move  8.O-O  is harmless because after  8...Nc5  9.Qc2  a5  Black will first solidify his knight on c5 by playing ...b6 and then will move his knight from f6 to execute the ...f5 push with very easy play as White castled a bit too early and his queenside play is nowhere near to start. }
8... h6 { Black naturally wants to get rid of the bishop. } 9. Bh4 g5
{ Forcing the bishop to the passive square on g3. } 10. Bg3 Nh5
{ From here the knight can either take the bishop on g3 when the time is right, or it can jump to f4. }
11. Nd2
{ Is the main alternative, attacking the knight on h5 and intending to establish control over the light squares with Bg4. }
11... Nf4 { The knight moves with tempo. } 12. O-O Nf6
{ This was played by Carlsen and the idea is to prevent Bg4. But Black's position is good enough even if he allows it, for example,  12...Nc5  13.Bg4  Bxg4  14.Qxg4  h5!  15.Qf5  h4!  16.Bxf4  exf4  when Black managed to open the long diagonal and activate his dark-squared bishop. }
13. Re1
{ This move liberates the f1-square for the knight. After Nf1-e3 White wants to establish control over the squares f5 and g4.  In case of  13.f3  Black's play is similar after  13...h5  14.b4  h4  15.Bf2  N6h5  with ...Qf6-g6 and ...g4 to come. }
13... h5
{ Threatening to trap the bishop and force it to exchange on f4, which would be great for Black after ...exf4, which would make his bishop on g7 a real beast. }
14. f3
{ Firouzja chose the panicky  14.h4?  which after  14...g4  15.Nf1  Nh7!  followed by ...Bf6 led to the loss of the pawn on h4 in the online game Firouzja-Carlsen from 2021.   Note that taking the pawn on h5 is suicidal:  14.Bxf4?  exf4  15.Bxh5  g4  traps the bishop on h5. }
14... h4
{ Following the typical plan. Black has an interesting alternative in  14...Kh8!?  with the idea of ...Rg8,  ...Bh6,  ...Qf8-g7 when the pawn breaks ...h4-h3 and ...g4 gain in strength thanks to the support from the heavy pieces from behind. }
15. Bf2 N6h5
{ Liberating the f6-square for the queen for the ...Qf6-g6 manoeuvre. Once the queen is on g6 Black will push ...f5. Even visually it's clear that Black has excellent play on the kingside. }
*

