[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. The Classical Variations"]
[Black "14. Exchange Variation (7.dxe5)"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 { White naturally takes over the centre. }
4... d6 { Preventing e5. } 5. Nf3 O-O
{ Black finished the development of the kingside and is now ready to play in the centre. }
6. Be2
{ This is White's most natural development, preparing short castle, and that is why this variation is called the Classical Variation. }
6... e5
{ The central strike that characterises the King's Indian Defence. Its idea is to attack the d4-square and either provoke White to react by pushing d5 or by taking on e5,  or to capture on d4 and open the e-file and the long-diagonal for the fianchettoed bishop. Now White has 4 main options to choose from:  1. He can keep the tension in the centre by castling  7.O-O   2. He can keep the tension in the centre by developing the dark-squared bishop to e3 with  7.Be3  - the Gligoric Variation.  3. He can blockade the centre immediately with  7.d5  - the Petrosian Variation.  4. He can exchange the pawns and then the queens after  7.dxe5  - the Exchange Variation. }
7. dxe5
{ The Exchange Variation is rather harmless, though Black needs to know how to react to it. }
7... dxe5 8. Qxd8 Rxd8
{ The pawn structure is in Black's favour now in view of the hole on d4. } 9.
Bg5
{ This is the main move. White should be incisive in this endgame because he has the worse pawn structure - the gaping hole on d4 cannot be controlled by a pawn, while Black can cover the d5-square by ...c6.  Many KID endgames have been won by Black rather effortlessly following the scenario of exchanging the dark-squared bishops, giving up the light-squared bishop for the knight on f3 and then planting a knight on d4,  which leads to the dream position for Black of a dominating knight on d4 versus an awful bishop on e2.  Note that the pawn on e5 is taboo in view of the trick  9.Nxe5?!  Nxe4!  and the bishop on g7 springs to life on the open diagonal.   The alternative to the main move is the immediate  9.Nd5  , but that will likely lead to a transposition after  9...Nxd5  10.cxd5  c6  11.Bc4  cxd5  12.Bxd5  Nd7  13.Bg5  Re8  . }
9... Re8
{ Getting away from the pin and defending the pawn on e5. Now Black wants to play ...c6, so White's next move is the critical one. }
10. Nd5
{ After  10.O-O-O  Black should first play  10...Na6  and then continue with ...c6,  because the immediate  10...c6  allows some complications after  11.Nxe5!?  . }
10... Nxd5 { The knight has to be eliminated. } 11. cxd5 c6
{ Black naturally wants to undermine White's strong point on d5, at the same time getting rid of the backward pawn on c7. }
12. Bc4
{ White intends to recapture on d5 with a bishop. Note that White cannot preserve the d-pawn, as pushing it  12.d6?!  only risks making it weak after  12...f6  followed by ...Be6,  ...Bf8,  ...Rd8 etc. }
12... cxd5
{ Eliminating the d5-pawn.  Black has the initially more dynamic option of  12...b5  13.Bb3  a5  at his disposal. After  14.a4  @@StartBracket@@White should not allow Black's expansion with ...a4,  something that So mistakenly did in his game against Vachier-Lagrave from the Clutch Championship in 2020, though the Frenchman didn't take advantage of it@@EndBracket@@  14...Bd7  15.dxc6  Bxc6  16.O-O  bxa4  17.Bxa4  Bxa4  18.Rxa4  Nc6  the endgame is completely equal. }
13. Bxd5 Nd7
{ This is important to remember. The natural move is to put the knight on c6, but from d7 the knight has two important tasks: one is to control the d5-square, either from f6 @@StartBracket@@from here the knight also targets the pawn on e4@@EndBracket@@ or b6, and the other is to go to c5 in order to allow for ...Be6 and after the exchange of bishops to land on e6, from where it can further go to d4 or f4. }
14. Nd2
{ White is more or less forced to play this move, to defend the pawn on e4 as Black already threatened to play ...h6 and ...Nf6,  for example  14.O-O-O?!  h6  15.Be3  Nf6  when Black is already better because he will obtain the bishop pair by eliminating the bishop on d5 since in that case, it would leave the pawn on e4 without protection. }
14... Nc5
{ A good alternative is  14...Nb6  followed by  ...Be6  , as was played in the game So-Carlsen from the Airthings Masters in 2020. Putting the knight on c5 is more ambitious as Black wants to land it on e6 after the exchange of the light-squared bishops. }
15. Nc4
{ In case of  15.O-O-O  Black can play  15...Be6  16.Bxe6  Nxe6  with an easy game with ideas like ...f5. }
15... Bf8
{ Calmly preventing Nd6 and intending to continue with the plan of ...Be6. }
16. O-O Be6 { Black finishes development and threatens to take on d5. } 17.
Rfd1 Rac8
{ Black equalised comfortably. He can play ...b6 next and also has the idea of ...Bxd5 and ...Ne6. }
