[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. The Classical Variations"]
[Black "17. Classical Main Line (7.0-0) with 8.d5. White plays 9.Bg5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 { White naturally takes over the centre. }
4... d6 { Preventing e5. } 5. Nf3 O-O
{ Black finished the development of the kingside and is now ready to play in the centre. }
6. Be2
{ This is White's most natural development, preparing short castle, and that is why this variation is called the Classical Variation. }
6... e5
{ The central strike that characterises the King's Indian Defence. Its idea is to attack the d4-square and either provoke White to react by pushing d5 or by taking on e5,  or to capture on d4 and open the e-file and the long-diagonal for the fianchettoed bishop. Now White has 4 main options to choose from:  1. He can keep the tension in the centre by castling  7.O-O   2. He can keep the tension in the centre by developing the dark-squared bishop to e3 with  7.Be3  - the Gligoric Variation.  3. He can blockade the centre immediately with  7.d5  - the Petrosian Variation.  4. He can exchange the pawns and then the queens after  7.dxe5  - the Exchange Variation. }
7. O-O { The most natural move for White, getting the king out of the centre. }
7... Bg4
{ This rare move has been known since the 50s, but it was never considered to be good. This conclusion changed when it was successfully used by Caruana to convincingly defeat Wojtaszek in the Wijk aan Zee tournament in 2021.  In fact, the move is a logical one as Black fights for the control of the dark squares by attacking the knight on f3 that controls both e5 and d4. It also has the benefit of not being explored as deeply as the more theoretical alternatives, which allows Black to obtain a fresh position without the need for massive memorisation. }
8. d5
{ This is the only critical option, as the alternatives give Black easy play. }
8... a5
{ A typical move on the queenside for Black. He increases his control over the squares b4 and c5, thus slowing down White's expansion by b4 and c5. The pawn on a5 also ensures a safe spot on c5 for the knight. }
9. Bg5
{ This is an alternative in the spirit of the Petrosian Variation. White pins the knight on f6 in the hope to slow down Black's plan of removing the knight from f6 and pushing ...f5. }
9... Na6
{ Black develops naturally, the knight is comfortable on a6 from where it controls the important dark squares c5 and b4 on the queenside, thus slowing down White's planned expansion with a3 and b4. }
10. Nd2
{ The alternative is  10.Ne1  , which is similar to the line withthe immediate 9.Ne1.  Black continues along the same lines,  10...Bd7  but after  11.Nd3  he should insert the move  11...h6!  in order to avoid White's Qd2 which would make it more difficult to organise his kingside play. After  12.Be3  b6  Black is a tempo up @@StartBracket@@h6@@EndBracket@@ compared to the same position from the line 9.Ne1 and his ideas are the same - play ...Nc5 to challenge the knight on d3 and then follow up with ...Nh5 and most likely ...f5. }
10... Bxe2
{ A surprising exchange, as it usually favours White, but in this particular case Black first wins a tempo by not retreating and starts his kingside play more quickly.  Even objectively this move is better than the automatic  10...Bd7  , which after  11.a3  h6  12.Be3  Nh7  13.Rb1  f5  14.f3  Nc5  15.b4  leads to a position where White's queenside play is considerably faster than Black's play on the kingside. }
11. Qxe2 Qd7
{ The important follow-up. Black removes the queen from the pin and wants to play ...Nh5 and ...f5, thus rendering the bishop on g5 useless. }
12. f3
{ White stabilises the centre and ensures a safe spot for the bishop on e3 as now it cannot be harassed by ...Ng4. }
12... Nh5 { Black continues with his plan of ...f5 and ...Nf4. } 13. Be3
{ The bishop had nothing to do anymore on g5. } 13... b6
{ Black is careful about his queenside. He stops the possible c5-push for a very long time with his preparatory move. }
14. Rab1
{ White doesn't really have a choice, he needs to prepare b4 and eventually c5. }
14... f5
{ Black achieves the typical KID thrust and with White's queenside play still at the initial stage this indicates that he has good play. }
15. b3
{ White must be careful, as the rushed  15.a3?!  allows  15...a4!  , fixing White's queenside and killing off his queenside play. }
15... Nf4
{ Activating the knight. Note that the move  15...f4?  would be bad as after  16.Bf2  Black cannot hope for a kingside attack in view of the absence of his light-squared bishop, which supports the plan of ...g5-g4,  and the fact that his other knight is on the queenside, thus being very far to aid the pawn storm. By closing the position with ...f4 he also dooms his dark-squared bishop to eternal passivity. }
16. Qd1 Bh6
{ A typical activation of the dark-squared bishop. The immediate threat is ...Nh3 @@StartBracket@@since the bishop on e3 is not defended@@EndBracket@@, but Black also has the slower plan of ...Qg7 @@StartBracket@@to defend the bishop on h6@@EndBracket@@ and ...Nh5, which will either exchange the dark-squared bishops @@StartBracket@@which would give Black greater access to the dark squares when White won't have a bishop to control them@@EndBracket@@, or will leave his bishop active on the c1-h6 diagonal. }
