[White "1. The Classical Variations"]
[Black "18. Classical Main Line (7.0-0) with 8.d5. White plays 9.Ne1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 { White naturally takes over the centre. }
4... d6 { Preventing e5. } 5. Nf3 O-O
{ Black finished the development of the kingside and is now ready to play in the centre. }
6. Be2
{ This is White's most natural development, preparing short castle, and that is why this variation is called the Classical Variation. }
6... e5
{ The central strike that characterises the King's Indian Defence. Its idea is to attack the d4-square and either provoke White to react by pushing d5 or by taking on e5,  or to capture on d4 and open the e-file and the long-diagonal for the fianchettoed bishop. Now White has 4 main options to choose from:  1. He can keep the tension in the centre by castling  7.O-O   2. He can keep the tension in the centre by developing the dark-squared bishop to e3 with  7.Be3  - the Gligoric Variation.  3. He can blockade the centre immediately with  7.d5  - the Petrosian Variation.  4. He can exchange the pawns and then the queens after  7.dxe5  - the Exchange Variation. }
7. O-O { The most natural move for White, getting the king out of the centre. }
7... Bg4
{ This rare move has been known since the 50s, but it was never considered to be good. This conclusion changed when it was successfully used by Caruana to convincingly defeat Wojtaszek in the Wijk aan Zee tournament in 2021.  In fact, the move is a logical one as Black fights for the control of the dark squares by attacking the knight on f3 that controls both e5 and d4. It also has the benefit of not being explored as deeply as the more theoretical alternatives, which allows Black to obtain a fresh position without the need for massive memorisation. }
8. d5
{ This is the only critical option, as the alternatives give Black easy play. }
8... a5
{ A typical move on the queenside for Black. He increases his control over the squares b4 and c5, thus slowing down White's expansion by b4 and c5. The pawn on a5 also ensures a safe spot on c5 for the knight. }
9. Ne1
{ This is an ambitious move, aiming for the ideal @@StartBracket@@for White@@EndBracket@@ exchange of the light-squared bishops @@StartBracket@@White's is a limited one, Black's is a good one@@EndBracket@@. Furthermore, the knight from e1 will come to d3 to support the c5-push. }
9... Bd7 { Black avoids the unfavourable exchange. } 10. Nd3 Na6
{ A typical development for Black, the pawn on a5 and the knight on a6 make it pretty difficult for White to make any progress on the queenside. }
11. Be3 { White insists on c5. } 11... b6
{ Black naturally prevents the c5-push. Now his queenside is safe and he can turn his attention to the kingside by organising the ...f5-push. He can do so by playing ...Ne8 or in case White plays f3 he can go ...Nh5, which has the additional idea of jumping to f4. A sample line is: }
12. f3
{ Strengthening the centre.  After  12.Qd2  Black can choose between  12...Nb4  @@StartBracket@@exchanging the knight on d3 and going ...Nh5 next@@EndBracket@@ and  12...Ng4  , the latter being played in the rapid game Gunina-Vitiugov from the Dvoretsky Memorial in Moscow in 2021. }
12... Nc5
{ An important move. By exchanging the knight on d3 Black weakens White's control over the f4-square. This is clearly seen after the immediate  12...Nh5?!  , which allows  13.g4!  and the knight is forced to go back to f6 as going to f4 simply loses a pawn. }
13. b3
{ White slowly prepares his queenside expansion. He wants to play Rb1, a3 and eventually b4, not allowing Black to fix the queenside by ...a4. }
13... Nh5
{ Now this is possible because Black can take on d3 and jump to f4. Black has excellent play here with ...f5 coming next when his kingside play is coming while White is very slow on the other side of the board. }
