[White "1. The Classical Variations"]
[Black "19. Classical Main Line (7.0-0) with 8.d5. White plays 9.h3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 { White naturally takes over the centre. }
4... d6 { Preventing e5. } 5. Nf3 O-O
{ Black finished the development of the kingside and is now ready to play in the centre. }
6. Be2
{ This is White's most natural development, preparing short castle, and that is why this variation is called the Classical Variation. }
6... e5
{ The central strike that characterises the King's Indian Defence. Its idea is to attack the d4-square and either provoke White to react by pushing d5 or by taking on e5,  or to capture on d4 and open the e-file and the long-diagonal for the fianchettoed bishop. Now White has 4 main options to choose from:  1. He can keep the tension in the centre by castling  7.O-O   2. He can keep the tension in the centre by developing the dark-squared bishop to e3 with  7.Be3  - the Gligoric Variation.  3. He can blockade the centre immediately with  7.d5  - the Petrosian Variation.  4. He can exchange the pawns and then the queens after  7.dxe5  - the Exchange Variation. }
7. O-O { The most natural move for White, getting the king out of the centre. }
7... Bg4
{ This rare move has been known since the 50s, but it was never considered to be good. This conclusion changed when it was successfully used by Caruana to convincingly defeat Wojtaszek in the Wijk aan Zee tournament in 2021.  In fact, the move is a logical one as Black fights for the control of the dark squares by attacking the knight on f3 that controls both e5 and d4. It also has the benefit of not being explored as deeply as the more theoretical alternatives, which allows Black to obtain a fresh position without the need for massive memorisation. }
8. d5
{ This is the only critical option, as the alternatives give Black easy play. }
8... a5
{ A typical move on the queenside for Black. He increases his control over the squares b4 and c5, thus slowing down White's expansion by b4 and c5. The pawn on a5 also ensures a safe spot on c5 for the knight. }
9. h3
{ Normally White doesn't play like this in the KID, weakening the kingside, but in this case it forces the exchange of Black's light-squared bishop. This is a double-edged decision as even though White obtains the pair of bishops he does weaken his kingside and slows down his queenside play.  Note that after  9.Be3  Na6  10.Ne1  Bd7  11.Nd3  b6  we have a transposition...   ... to the line after  9.Ne1  Bd7  10.Nd3  Na6  11.Be3  b6  . @@StartBracket@@seethis line@@EndBracket@@ }
9... Bxf3
{ Black would have liked to keep this bishop @@StartBracket@@his pawns on the dark squares in the centre mean that he needs that piece to control the light squares@@EndBracket@@, but unfortunately keeping it allows  9...Bd7?!  10.c5!  when White starts queenside play immediately @@StartBracket@@the same goes for @@StartFEN@@rn1q1rk1/1pp2pbp/3p1np1/p2Pp3/2P1P1b1/2N2N1P/PP2BPP1/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Bc8?!  10.c5!  @@EndBracket@@.  The further justification is seen after @@StartFEN@@rn1q1rk1/1ppb1pbp/3p1np1/p1PPp3/4P3/2N2N1P/PP2BPP1/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10...dxc5  11.Nxe5  Nxe4  12.Nxe4  Bxe5  13.Bg5!  when Black's position is close to collapsing. Still, the exchange of the light-squared bishop is justified here because of White's weakening of his kingside with h3,  a move he'd rather avoid. }
10. Bxf3 Nbd7
{ Black finishes development. Now he has two main ideas: to prepare and execute the ...f5 push @@StartBracket@@by moving the knight from f6 first@@EndBracket@@ and to exchange the dark-squared bishops. The latter can be done in more than one way: by playing ...Kh8, ...Ng8 and ...Bh6, by playing ...h5, ...Kh7 and ...Bh6, by moving the knight from f6 and going ...Bf6-g5 @@StartBracket@@with or without ...f5@@EndBracket@@.  Note that after the exchange of the dark-squared bishops Black will have the advantage of having the better minor pieces because White's remaining bishop will be severely limited due to White's own pawns placed on the light squares. Additionally, the exchange of the dark-squared bishops will weaken White's dark squares because without the bishop White will have one piece less to control them.  While these positional considerations are valid for a lot of KID positions of a similar type, this particular position is practically unexplored and there is vast room for finding new paths. Let's take a look now at two ways for White - one is to prepare the queenside expansion immediately, while the other is to finish development first before doing so. }
11. Be3
{ This is a developing move that takes control over the c5-square as White wants to achieve the c5-push after preparing b4 first. This is White's typical way of queenside expansion. }
11... Ne8
{ White's bishop on e3 should serve as a hint to Black to start preparing the ...f5-push immediately as the pawn can possibly harass the bishop on e3. An additional idea for Black after ...Ne8 is the possibility for ...Bf6-g5, to exchange the dark-squared bishops. }
12. a3 { White prepares his queenside expansion. } 12... f5
{ Black also follows through with his plan. } 13. b4 Bf6
{ Intending ...Bg5.  Playing  13...f4?  would be bad as after the bishop retreats to d2 Black's kingside play comes to a standstill - he cannot achieve an attack with ...h5 and ...g4 because White has strong control over the g4-square and his own dark-squared bishop is now a prisoner behind the pawn chain that stretches from c7 to f4. However, the move ...f4 is still important as White now cannot stop the exchange of the dark-squared bishops with Qd2. }
14. Bh6 Rf7
{ Now Black threatens ...f4 to trap the bishop on h6, so White is forced to allow Black a pawn centre: }
15. exf5 gxf5 16. Bh5 Re7
{ The only place for the rook, but now Black wants to untangle with ...Kh8, ...Bg7 and then one of the knights coming to f6. The position is unclear and Black's chances are rather good. }
