14. Qc1
{ The point of having the move ...f4 at his disposal is that White cannot play  14.Qd2?  because  14...f4  traps the bishop on e3. }
14... axb4
{ By exchanging the rooks on the a-file Black forces the white queen to move from c1, thus allowing for the exchange of the bishops after ...Bg5. }
15. axb4 Rxa1 16. Qxa1 Bg5
{ Black achieved his strategic goal and now will not have potentially bad pieces, unlike White with his potentially passive light-squared bishop. }
17. Bxg5
{ In case of  17.Qc1  Bxe3  18.Qxe3  Qh4  followed by ...Ndf6 Black has good activity on the kingside while there is nothing for White to attack on the queenside. }
17... Qxg5 18. Qa7 { White goes after the pawn on b7. } 18... b6
{ The simplest move, securing the queenside. Now Black will continue with ...Ndf6 @@StartBracket@@leaving the knight on e8 to cover the c7-pawn@@EndBracket@@ to put pressure on the pawn on e4.  His queen can also penetrate on d2 to harass the knight on c3. If White retreats the queen from a7 then the knight from e8 can be activated via g7 and a further ...fxe4 and ...Nf5.  Black has very good play here. }
