{ Since White wants to start immediate play on the queenside with Rb1 and b4 Black's plan with ...f5 is rather slow. To illustrate, after  11...Ne8?!  12.Rb1  f5  13.b4  White is ready to crash through with c5 even at the expense of a pawn, while Black's kingside play has little to show for.  That is why he switches to the strategic idea of the exchange of the dark-squared bishops and plans to exchange them in one of the two ways: with ...Kh7 and ...Bh6,  or ...Nh7 followed by ...Bf6-g5. }
12. Rb1 Nh7
{ With the intention of ...Bf6-g5.  The alternative is  12...Kh7  , which is also possible. Now White should try to stop Black's plan by playing  13.g4!?  , intending to meet Black's ...Bh6 with g5. So Black should adjust his plan and play  13...hxg4  14.hxg4  Kg8!  with the idea of ...Nh7 and then either ...Ng5 or ...Bf6-g5. This leads to a very complex middlegame. }
13. b4 Bf6
{ It is important not to open the a-file prematurely because in that case, White can seize it after Bb2, Qd3 and Ra1. }
14. Nb5 Bg5
{ Black continues with his plan. Now he has activated his dark-squared bishop so even in case White avoids the exchange he will no longer have passive pieces. }
15. Bb2
{ Avoiding the exchange. If White allows it, then after  15.Be2  Ndf6  @@StartBracket@@hitting the pawn on e4@@EndBracket@@  16.Qd3  Bxc1  17.Rfxc1  axb4  @@StartBracket@@Black opens the a-file now as he will combine the rook's activity with an attack on the pawn on e4@@EndBracket@@  18.axb4  Ng5  @@StartBracket@@attacking the pawn on e4 again@@EndBracket@@  19.Nc3  Ra3!  with good counterplay as Black nicely combines play on both wings. }
15... b6
{ Increasing the control over the c5-square, thus making White's c5-push more difficult to achieve. }
16. Qc2 { White connects the rooks and again targets the c5-square. } 16... Bh6
{ An important prophylactic move that takes the sting out of White's intended push c5. }
17. c5
{ White persists, but Black is now ready to deal with this push.  In case of a slower development like  17.Be2  Black can play  17...h4  followed by ...Bf4 and various ideas on the kingside like ...Ng5,  ...Nf6-h5,  preparation of ...f5 etc. }
17... bxc5 18. bxc5 Nxc5
{ Black takes the pawn and keeps his structure intact. } 19. Bxe5
{ This was White's idea behind 16.Qc2 - the queen keeps an eye on the knight on c5, but now we see the deep idea behind Black's 16th move. }
19... Ng5
{ This is the defence Black prepared by liberating the g5-square. Now White cannot move the bishop from f3 since the pawn on e4 is hanging, which means that he will be forced to allow the wrecking of his kingside after ...Nxf3 as he will have to recapture with gxf3. This weakening of White's kingside gives Black very good chances. }
