[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. The Saemisch Variation"]
[Black "22. Saemisch Variation with 3.f3. White plays 6.Bg5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3
{ This is a popular move-order against the Grunfeld Defence, while against the KID it offers an additional option by keeping the knight on b1. }
3... Bg7 { Black continues with the usual development. } 4. e4 d6 5. Ne2
{ This is the extra option White has. His idea is to play Nec3, thus solving the problem of the knight on g1. By keeping the knight on b1 he also keeps the option to develop it to a3 and then c2. }
5... O-O
{ Black castles and now it's up to White to try to take advantage of the peculiar move-order. }
6. Bg5
{ This is another possibility similar to the regular Saemisch where White develops the bishop to g5. }
6... a6
{ It's important to start with this move as it immediately prepares ...b5, thus taking advantage of the fact that White doesn't control that square since he delayed the development of the knight from b1. Black still keeps the possibility of ...Nc6 the moment White weakens the d4-square. }
7. Qd2
{ Still insisting on independent play. The natural  7.Nbc3  Nc6  transposes to the lines of the Saemisch where White develops the bishop to g5,  analysed after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppppp1p/5np1/8/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  Bg7  4.e4  d6  5.f3  O-O  6.Bg5  Nc6  7.Nge2  a6  8.Qd2  @@StartBracket@@seethis line@@EndBracket@@.   Playing  7.Nec3  weakens the d4-square and allows  7...Nc6!  with the idea of ...e5 and ...Nd4 while now  8.d5  Ne5  followed by ...c6 undermines White's centre. }
7... b5
{ Black takes advantage of the fact that White left the b5-square without attention to undermine White's centre.  The typical Saemisch move  7...Nc6  allows for the interesting  8.Na3!?  with the idea of Nc2. But the move  7...c5!?  is an interesting alternative with the Benko Gambit style idea of  8.d5  b5!  . }
8. Nbc3
{ Eventually White couldn't avoid the development of the queen's knight to c3.  Taking on b5 is good for Black after  8.cxb5?!  axb5  when Black gets the open a-file and the opportunity to harass the white knight with ...b4 in case it develops to c3.   Developing the knight to a3 allows  8.Na3  bxc4  9.Nxc4  d5  forcing White to play with an IQP after  10.exd5  Qxd5  . }
8... bxc4
{ Taking the pawn, though  8...c5!?  is an interesting alternative, sacrificing a pawn for activity after  9.cxb5  axb5  10.Nxb5  Qb6  . }
9. h4 c5
{ Attacking White's centre and following the maxim that an attack on the flank @@StartBracket@@White's h4@@EndBracket@@ is best met by a counterattack in the centre. }
10. O-O-O
{ An aggressive attempt by White to play for an attack. Exchanging queens is harmless after  10.dxc5  dxc5  11.Qxd8  Rxd8  followed by ...Nc6,  as is  10.d5  Nbd7  with ...Ne5 next. }
10... Qa5
{ Activating the queen and intending to follow up with ...Nc6. The position is complex but Black is still a pawn up, he is solid on the kingside and he has an open file on the queenside to use for an attack against White's king. He will continue with ...Nc6 and ...Rb8 next and will seek to create threats, for example by doubling on the b-file. }
