[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. The Saemisch Variation"]
[Black "23. Saemisch Variation with 3.f3. White plays 6.Be3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3
{ This is a popular move-order against the Grunfeld Defence, while against the KID it offers an additional option by keeping the knight on b1. }
3... Bg7 { Black continues with the usual development. } 4. e4 d6 5. Ne2
{ This is the extra option White has. His idea is to play Nec3, thus solving the problem of the knight on g1. By keeping the knight on b1 he also keeps the option to develop it to a3 and then c2. }
5... O-O
{ Black castles and now it's up to White to try to take advantage of the peculiar move-order. }
6. Be3
{ The move  6.Nec3  is not very good as it weakens the d4-square so Black immediately plays  6...Nc6  with the idea of ...e5 and ...Nd4. If White prevents it by  7.d5  Ne5  8.Be2  e6!  undermines White's centre and gives Black great play, as demonstrated in the game Mamedyarov-Carlsen from the World Blitz Championship in Moscow in 2009. }
6... a6
{ Black starts with ...a6 as White doesn't control the b5-square so he intends to attack White's centre by ...b5. }
7. Nec3
{ This is an alternative, but it weakens the d4-square, so Black's next move is understandable. }
7... Nc6 { Intending ...e5 and ...Nd4. } 8. Na3
{ White rushes to cover the d4-square from c2.  Of course,  8.d5  Ne5  followed by ...c6 and possibly even ...b5 nicely undermines White's centre. }
8... e5 { Black follows his plan. } 9. d5 Nd4
{ The knight is dominant on d4 so White must try to get rid of it. } 10. Nc2
{ White cannot take twice on d4,  the typical trick being  10.Bxd4?  exd4  11.Qxd4??  Nxe4  12.Qxe4  Re8  winning the queen and the game. }
10... c5 { Black supports the knight. } 11. dxc6 Nxc2+
{ The simple solution. Black can also sacrifice a pawn after  11...bxc6  12.Nxd4  exd4  13.Bxd4  Re8  , as mentioned in the line after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppppp1p/5np1/8/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  Bg7  4.e4  d6  5.f3  O-O  6.Be3  Nc6  7.Nge2  a6  8.Nc1  @@StartBracket@@seethis line@@EndBracket@@ }
12. Qxc2 bxc6
{ With ...Be6, ...Qe7 and ...Rfd8 coming Black has good play as he controls the centre well. He can try to push ...d5 or ...f5. }
