[White "2. The Saemisch Variation"]
[Black "24. Saemisch Variation with 3.f3. White plays 6.Be3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3
{ This is a popular move-order against the Grunfeld Defence, while against the KID it offers an additional option by keeping the knight on b1. }
3... Bg7 { Black continues with the usual development. } 4. e4 d6 5. Ne2
{ This is the extra option White has. His idea is to play Nec3, thus solving the problem of the knight on g1. By keeping the knight on b1 he also keeps the option to develop it to a3 and then c2. }
5... O-O
{ Black castles and now it's up to White to try to take advantage of the peculiar move-order. }
6. Be3
{ The move  6.Nec3  is not very good as it weakens the d4-square so Black immediately plays  6...Nc6  with the idea of ...e5 and ...Nd4. If White prevents it by  7.d5  Ne5  8.Be2  e6!  undermines White's centre and gives Black great play, as demonstrated in the game Mamedyarov-Carlsen from the World Blitz Championship in Moscow in 2009. }
6... a6
{ Black starts with ...a6 as White doesn't control the b5-square so he intends to attack White's centre by ...b5. }
7. Qd2
{ The moves  7.Nbc3  Nc6  transpose to the usual lines of the Saemisch. } 7...
b5 { Black attacks the centre. } 8. Nbc3
{ The move  8.Na3  allows  8...bxc4  10.Nxc4  d5  with favourable simplifications in the centre as White will have to play with an IQP on d4. }
8... bxc4 { Black takes the pawn. } 9. h4 h5
{ In the similar position inthe line with 6.Bg5 Black played ...c5 here, attacking White's centre, but with a bishop on e3 that is not possible since the bishop controls the c5-square, so Black takes the time to stop White's kingside advance. }
10. Nf4 Nc6
{ Black still implements the same ideas, intending ...e5 and ...Nd4. } 11. Bxc4
{ White attacks the pawn on g6 in view of the pin on the a2-g8 diagonal, so Black doesn't have time for ...e5. }
11... e6 { Closing the sensitive diagonal. Now Black intends ...d5. } 12. O-O-O
{ This is more ambitious than  12.O-O  d5  13.exd5  Na5  followed by ...exd5 with good play for Black in the centre as the immediate threat is ...Nc4. }
12... Rb8
{ Here  12...d5?  would be bad because after  13.exd5  Na5  14.Bd3  exd5  15.g4!  White creates a very dangerous attack against Black's king.  That is why Black keeps the centre flexible and intends ...Nd7-b6 or ...e5. With the rook on b8 the move ...e5 works: }
13. Kb1 e5 { White cannot take on g6 in view of: } 14. Nxg6 Na5
{ And the bishop cannot come to d5 attacking the rook on a8, so White loses material. }
