[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. The Saemisch Variation"]
[Black "25. Saemisch Variation with 3.Nc3. White plays 6.Bg5 "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. f3
{ This move is typical for the Saemisch Variation, named after the German GM Friedrich Saemisch. The idea is quite simple: since one aspect of Black's counterplay in the KID is the attack on the e4-pawn White immediately defends it securely. As an additional bonus the pawn on f3 covers the g4-square so this ensures a safe spot for the dark-squared bishop on e3.  However, there is a price to be paid for all these advantages. A long time ago, when GM Eduard Gufeld, a life-long and very successful KID player, was asked about the disadvantages of the Saemisch Variation he simply replied: 'Just ask the knight on g1!'  And he was right, the pawn on f3 takes away the natural developing square from the knight and the knight finds it difficult to get into the game - even when developed on e2 it blocks the bishop on f1 and needs further redeployment. As we shall see Black uses this problematic knight to create his counterplay. }
5... O-O
{ Black finishes development and is now ready to start play against White's centre. Now White has a choice where to develop his dark-squared bishop, to e3 or to g5.  Note that the move  6.Nge2  has no independent value because after  6...Nc6  White again needs to make the same choice about the development of the bishop, hence transposing to the main lines either after 6.Be3 or 6.Bg5. }
6. Bg5
{ A slightly provocative move. White seeks to provoke ...h6 when the bishop will drop back to its natural square on e3 when White can gain a tempo against the pawn on h6 by attacking it with Qd2.  However, if Black refrains from ...h6 then the bishop may turn out to be somewhat out or play and the pawn on d4 may feel the lack of protection @@StartBracket@@unlike when the bishop is on e3@@EndBracket@@. }
6... Nc6
{ Black's play is the same as in the line after 6.Be3. He intends ...e5 and ...Nd4, so White's next move is forced. }
7. Nge2 a6 { The preparatory move for a possible ...b5. } 8. Qd2
{ Playing  8.d5?!  is not good in view of  8...Ne5  9.Nd4  c5  10.Nc2  Nh5  with ...f5 next and great play for Black. }
8... Na5
{ Black immediately attacks the pawn on c4, thus taking advantage of the clumsy position of the knight on e2. }
9. Nc1
{ The same defence as inthe line with 6.Be3.  The main alternative is  9.Ng3  but after  9...b5  10.Bh6  Bxh6  11.Qxh6  Nc6  we have a transpositon to the line @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/2PPP3/2N2P2/PP4PP/R1BQKBNR w KQ - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Be3  Nc6  7.Nge2  a6  8.Qd2  Na5  9.Ng3  b5  10.Bh6  Bxh6  11.Qxh6  Nc6  @@StartBracket@@seethis line@@EndBracket@@   The move  9.b3  is met by  9...b5  with the same tactic working again,  10.cxb5  axb5  11.Nxb5?  Nxb3  and White loses the exchange because of the pin on the a-file. }
9... c5
{ Without a bishop on e3 Black doesn't need the move ...Nd7 and this move is immediately possible. }
10. d5
{ The most ambitious. Taking on c5 is harmless:  10.dxc5  dxc5  with ...Be6 next with easy play as Black has the better structure in view of the hole on d4 that he ultimately wants to exploit @@StartBracket@@...Nc6-d4 being an idea@@EndBracket@@.   Also allowing Black to take on d4 is good for Black, for example,  10.Nb3  Nxb3  11.axb3  cxd4  12.Qxd4  Be6  with excellent play as ...b5 is coming next, exposing White's queenside pawns on c4 and b3. }
10... Rb8 { Preparing the ...b5 push. } 11. Be2 b5
{ Executing the plan. Now Black's counterplay speeds up. } 12. cxb5 axb5 13.
Bxb5
{ Taking with the knight is worse,  13.Nxb5?!  e6  opens the centre and the game in Black's favour, for example,  14.dxe6  Bxe6  with ideas like ...Nc4 and ...Qb6. }
13... Rxb5
{ A fantastic exchange sacrifice that illustrates Black's dynamic potential. }
14. Nxb5 Nc4
{ Now we see Black's idea: the queen on d2 is under attack and he has threats along the long diagonal @@StartBracket@@...Nxb2 and ...Nxe4@@EndBracket@@ and the e1-a5 diagonal @@StartBracket@@...Qa5 once the white queen leaves it@@EndBracket@@. }
15. Qc2
{ Going to c3 runs into  15.Qc3  Nxb2!  with the idea  16.Qxb2  Nxe4!  and White's position falls apart as everything hangs: the bishop on g5,  the pieces on the long diagonal and the knight on b5 after a possible check on a5. }
15... Qa5+ { The knight on b5 hangs so White's next is forced. } 16. Nc3 Na3
{ Continuing to play on the power of the bishop on the long diagonal. } 17.
bxa3
{ Going back to d2  17.Qd2  Nc4  is at least equal for Black with a repetition.   17.Qd3?  Ba6  is bad for White. }
17... Nxe4
{ Catastrophy happens on c3. Luckily for White he is a rook up so he can survive. }
18. fxe4
{ Defending with  18.Bd2  Nxd2  19.Kxd2  Bf5  20.Qb2  Qa8  when the threats of ...Rb8 and ...c4 give Black tremendous compensation for the rook as White is hopelessly pinned and tied down. }
18... Qxc3+ { Black regains the material. } 19. Qxc3 Bxc3+ 20. Ke2 Bxa1 21.
Bxe7 { Now White starts collecting some pawns, but after... } 21... Re8 22.
Bxd6 Rxe4+ 23. Kf3 Rc4
{ Black has excellent compensation for the pawn in view of his pair of bishops, the activity of his pieces and the passed c-pawn. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. The Saemisch Variation"]
[Black "26. Saemisch Variation with 3.Nc3 White plays 6.Be3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. f3
{ This move is typical for the Saemisch Variation, named after the German GM Friedrich Saemisch. The idea is quite simple: since one aspect of Black's counterplay in the KID is the attack on the e4-pawn White immediately defends it securely. As an additional bonus the pawn on f3 covers the g4-square so this ensures a safe spot for the dark-squared bishop on e3.  However, there is a price to be paid for all these advantages. A long time ago, when GM Eduard Gufeld, a life-long and very successful KID player, was asked about the disadvantages of the Saemisch Variation he simply replied: 'Just ask the knight on g1!'  And he was right, the pawn on f3 takes away the natural developing square from the knight and the knight finds it difficult to get into the game - even when developed on e2 it blocks the bishop on f1 and needs further redeployment. As we shall see Black uses this problematic knight to create his counterplay. }
5... O-O
{ Black finishes development and is now ready to start play against White's centre. Now White has a choice where to develop his dark-squared bishop, to e3 or to g5.  Note that the move  6.Nge2  has no independent value because after  6...Nc6  White again needs to make the same choice about the development of the bishop, hence transposing to the main lines either after 6.Be3 or 6.Bg5. }
6. Be3 { This is the typical Saemisch development. } 6... Nc6
{ This is the Panno Variation. Black puts pressure on the d4-square and wants to play ...e5 and ...Nd4 if allowed.  The development of the knight on c6 also envisions queenside counterplay against the pawn on c4 after ...Na5, especially after White plays Nge2 - the knight on e2 makes the pawn on c4 vulnerable because the bishop on f1 no longer defends it.  The third idea of the move is a preparation of the ...b5 push after ...a6 and ...Rb8. It is curious to note that the Panno Variation was Bobby Fischer's choice when he faced the Saemisch Variation in his rematch with Boris Spassky in 1992 and he scored rather well with it - he won 2, lost 1 and drew 1. }
7. d5
{ Black gladly provokes this advance as he is better developed for the confrontation in the centre. }
7... Ne5 { Now Black wants to undermine White's centre by ...e6 or ...c6. } 8.
f4
{ White continues to harass the knight but all he achieves is to overextend his position. }
8... Neg4 { Getting away with tempo. } 9. Bd2 e6
{ Undermining the centre and intending to open the e-file after ...exd5. } 10.
h3
{ In case of  10.dxe6  Bxe6  Black is ready to continue with ...Re8 when sacrificial ideas based on ...Nxe4 to open the e-file are up in the air. }
10... Nh6
{ The only escape square. The knight is temporarily on the rim, but the rest of Black's pieces compensate for this misplacement. }
11. Bd3
{ The natural  11.Nf3?  is bad in view of  11...exd5  12.cxd5  Re8  with ...Nxe4 and ...f5 next to come. }
11... exd5
{ Opening the e-file. This is simpler than the more imaginative  11...b5!?  12.cxb5  exd5  13.exd5  a6  which also gives Black excellent play. }
12. cxd5 Re8 { With the idea of ...Nxe4 and ...f5 or ...Bf5. } 13. Nge2
{ Closing the e-file. } 13... b5
{ Again this flank idea, intended to harass the knight on c3 and undermine the pawn on e4 after ...b4. }
14. a3
{ Stopping ...b4. Note that White cannot take the pawn on b5 with  14.Bxb5?  as after  14...Nxe4!  with the threat of ...Qh4 Black is much better. }
14... Bd7 { Finishing development and intending ...c6. } 15. O-O c6 16. dxc6
Bxc6
{ Black has excellent play here. The pressure on e4 is giving White headaches as Black intends to intensify it even further by playing ...a5 and ...b4. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. The Saemisch Variation"]
[Black "27. Saemisch Variation with 3.Nc3. White plays 6.Be3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. f3
{ This move is typical for the Saemisch Variation, named after the German GM Friedrich Saemisch. The idea is quite simple: since one aspect of Black's counterplay in the KID is the attack on the e4-pawn White immediately defends it securely. As an additional bonus the pawn on f3 covers the g4-square so this ensures a safe spot for the dark-squared bishop on e3.  However, there is a price to be paid for all these advantages. A long time ago, when GM Eduard Gufeld, a life-long and very successful KID player, was asked about the disadvantages of the Saemisch Variation he simply replied: 'Just ask the knight on g1!'  And he was right, the pawn on f3 takes away the natural developing square from the knight and the knight finds it difficult to get into the game - even when developed on e2 it blocks the bishop on f1 and needs further redeployment. As we shall see Black uses this problematic knight to create his counterplay. }
5... O-O
{ Black finishes development and is now ready to start play against White's centre. Now White has a choice where to develop his dark-squared bishop, to e3 or to g5.  Note that the move  6.Nge2  has no independent value because after  6...Nc6  White again needs to make the same choice about the development of the bishop, hence transposing to the main lines either after 6.Be3 or 6.Bg5. }
6. Be3 { This is the typical Saemisch development. } 6... Nc6
{ This is the Panno Variation. Black puts pressure on the d4-square and wants to play ...e5 and ...Nd4 if allowed.  The development of the knight on c6 also envisions queenside counterplay against the pawn on c4 after ...Na5, especially after White plays Nge2 - the knight on e2 makes the pawn on c4 vulnerable because the bishop on f1 no longer defends it.  The third idea of the move is a preparation of the ...b5 push after ...a6 and ...Rb8. It is curious to note that the Panno Variation was Bobby Fischer's choice when he faced the Saemisch Variation in his rematch with Boris Spassky in 1992 and he scored rather well with it - he won 2, lost 1 and drew 1. }
7. Nge2
{ In view of Black's threat of ...e5 and ...Nd4 this is White's only reasonable move. For example, the careless  7.Qd2?!  is met by  7...e5  8.d5  Nd4  with great play. }
7... a6
{ Black prepares for the possibility to push ...b5 and attack White's vulnerable c4-pawn. }
8. Nc1
{ Is an attempt to find the clumsy knight a better square, but it allows Black to achieve his main idea to plant a knight on d4. }
8... e5 9. d5 Nd4 10. Nb3
{ White cannot tolerate the knight on d4. Trying to exchange it from e2 allows  10.N1e2  c5  12.dxc6  Nxc6  as White is again stuck with an awkward knight on e2 while Black has easy development with ...Be6,  ...Rc8 etc. }
10... Nxb3
{ This is the simplest. A good alternative is the promising pawn sacrifice  10...c5!?  11.dxc6  bxc6  12.Nxd4  exd4  13.Bxd4  Re8  followed by ...d5. }
11. Qxb3 Nd7
{ Liberating the path for the f-pawn and controlling the c5-square. Black has good play here as in case White castles long he can combine the kingside play with queenside play after ...Rb8, ...Bd7 and ...b5. }
