{ Black finishes development and is now ready to start play against White's centre. Now White has a choice where to develop his dark-squared bishop, to e3 or to g5.  Note that the move  6.Nge2  has no independent value because after  6...Nc6  White again needs to make the same choice about the development of the bishop, hence transposing to the main lines either after 6.Be3 or 6.Bg5. }
6. Be3 { This is the typical Saemisch development. } 6... Nc6
{ This is the Panno Variation. Black puts pressure on the d4-square and wants to play ...e5 and ...Nd4 if allowed.  The development of the knight on c6 also envisions queenside counterplay against the pawn on c4 after ...Na5, especially after White plays Nge2 - the knight on e2 makes the pawn on c4 vulnerable because the bishop on f1 no longer defends it.  The third idea of the move is a preparation of the ...b5 push after ...a6 and ...Rb8. It is curious to note that the Panno Variation was Bobby Fischer's choice when he faced the Saemisch Variation in his rematch with Boris Spassky in 1992 and he scored rather well with it - he won 2, lost 1 and drew 1. }
7. Nge2
{ In view of Black's threat of ...e5 and ...Nd4 this is White's only reasonable move. For example, the careless  7.Qd2?!  is met by  7...e5  8.d5  Nd4  with great play. }
7... a6
{ Black prepares for the possibility to push ...b5 and attack White's vulnerable c4-pawn. }
8. Qd2
{ The usual move. White finishes development and prepares Bh6,  0-0-0 or Rd1.  The move  8.h4  is met by  8...h5  and then play will be analogous as White again will likely play Qd2. }
8... Na5
{ A relatively fresh idea compared to the traditional move  8...Rb8  . Black immediately starts counterplay against the pawn on c4 and keeping the rook on a8 for now gives him additional tactical chances based on the fork ...Nb3. }
9. Nf4 { This is the main alternative, leading to ultra-sharp play. } 9... b5
{ Black continues his queenside play against the pawn on c4, still using the rook on a8, thus making it impossible for White to take twice on b5. }
10. h4
{ White also starts his attack, supported by the knight on f4. Black's idea is shown after  10.cxb5?!  axb5  11.Bxb5?  Nb3  winning the exchange thanks to the pin on the a-file. }
10... h5
{ Black should stop White's threat of h5 as then the attack can become dangerous. Now White should decide whether to continue his attack immediately by pushing g4 or to castle long first. }
11. O-O-O { White castles before continuing his kingside play. } 11... Nd7
{ With the idea of ...e5 or ...Nb6, increasing the pressure on the c4-pawn. }
12. g4 { White starts the attack. } 12... e5
{ And Black counterattacks in the centre. } 13. gxh5
{ White sacrifices a piece for the attack.  In case of  13.dxe5  Nxe5  14.gxh5  Naxc4  15.Bxc4  Nxc4  16.Qe2  Nxe3  17.Qxe3  b4  play is also extremely sharp but Black is fine with his pair of bishops and counterplay based on the moves ...b3 @@StartBracket@@trying to open the b-file@@EndBracket@@ and ...Qf6.   Another move is  13.Nfd5  c6  when play is again sharp with White having to decide whether to sacrifice and how. }
13... exf4 { Black takes the piece. } 14. Bxf4 Nb6
{ Black's counterplay continues to be the pawn on c4. } 15. Bg5
{ A subtle move, provoking ...f6 so that the pawn on g6 doesn't have the support of the pawn on f7. }
15... f6 { Chasing away the bishop with tempo. } 16. Bf4 Nbxc4
{ It's better to take with this knight as the one on a5 controls the b3-square and this may give Black counterplay in some lines. }
17. Qg2 b4 { Black is not backing down, he continues to counterattack. } 18.
Nd5 c6 { Forcing the exchange of knights on e3. } 19. Ne3 Nxe3 20. Bxe3 gxh5
{ Black doesn't fear the pin on the g-file because he can defend the bishop with both rooks, from f7 and a7. }
21. Rg1 Rf7 22. Bh6 Raa7
{ Black's moves were forced, defending the bishop on g7. } 23. Qg6 Be6
{ Black threatens ...Bxa2. The position is extremely sharp, White has compensation for the piece but only for equality and he is under pressure to prove it. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. The Saemisch Variation"]
[Black "29. Saemisch Variation with 3.Nc3. White plays 6.Be3 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. f3
{ This move is typical for the Saemisch Variation, named after the German GM Friedrich Saemisch. The idea is quite simple: since one aspect of Black's counterplay in the KID is the attack on the e4-pawn White immediately defends it securely. As an additional bonus the pawn on f3 covers the g4-square so this ensures a safe spot for the dark-squared bishop on e3.  However, there is a price to be paid for all these advantages. A long time ago, when GM Eduard Gufeld, a life-long and very successful KID player, was asked about the disadvantages of the Saemisch Variation he simply replied: 'Just ask the knight on g1!'  And he was right, the pawn on f3 takes away the natural developing square from the knight and the knight finds it difficult to get into the game - even when developed on e2 it blocks the bishop on f1 and needs further redeployment. As we shall see Black uses this problematic knight to create his counterplay. }
5... O-O
{ Black finishes development and is now ready to start play against White's centre. Now White has a choice where to develop his dark-squared bishop, to e3 or to g5.  Note that the move  6.Nge2  has no independent value because after  6...Nc6  White again needs to make the same choice about the development of the bishop, hence transposing to the main lines either after 6.Be3 or 6.Bg5. }
6. Be3 { This is the typical Saemisch development. } 6... Nc6
{ This is the Panno Variation. Black puts pressure on the d4-square and wants to play ...e5 and ...Nd4 if allowed.  The development of the knight on c6 also envisions queenside counterplay against the pawn on c4 after ...Na5, especially after White plays Nge2 - the knight on e2 makes the pawn on c4 vulnerable because the bishop on f1 no longer defends it.  The third idea of the move is a preparation of the ...b5 push after ...a6 and ...Rb8. It is curious to note that the Panno Variation was Bobby Fischer's choice when he faced the Saemisch Variation in his rematch with Boris Spassky in 1992 and he scored rather well with it - he won 2, lost 1 and drew 1. }
7. Nge2
{ In view of Black's threat of ...e5 and ...Nd4 this is White's only reasonable move. For example, the careless  7.Qd2?!  is met by  7...e5  8.d5  Nd4  with great play. }
7... a6
{ Black prepares for the possibility to push ...b5 and attack White's vulnerable c4-pawn. }
8. Qd2
{ The usual move. White finishes development and prepares Bh6,  0-0-0 or Rd1.  The move  8.h4  is met by  8...h5  and then play will be analogous as White again will likely play Qd2. }
8... Na5
{ A relatively fresh idea compared to the traditional move  8...Rb8  . Black immediately starts counterplay against the pawn on c4 and keeping the rook on a8 for now gives him additional tactical chances based on the fork ...Nb3. }
9. Nf4 { This is the main alternative, leading to ultra-sharp play. } 9... b5
{ Black continues his queenside play against the pawn on c4, still using the rook on a8, thus making it impossible for White to take twice on b5. }
10. h4
{ White also starts his attack, supported by the knight on f4. Black's idea is shown after  10.cxb5?!  axb5  11.Bxb5?  Nb3  winning the exchange thanks to the pin on the a-file. }
10... h5
{ Black should stop White's threat of h5 as then the attack can become dangerous. Now White should decide whether to continue his attack immediately by pushing g4 or to castle long first. }
11. g4 { White lunges forward immediately. } 11... Bxg4
{ An excellent defensive sacrifice that kills off White's attack. Black obtains a couple of pawns for the piece and can continue his own play on the queenside. }
12. fxg4 Nxg4
{ The knight on g4 makes sure Black's kingside is safe. Now he has ideas to push ...b4, to take on c4 or to take on e3 and obtain control over the dark squares thanks to his strong fianchettoed bishop on g7. }
13. O-O-O b4
{ Hitting the knight on c3 and introducing the idea of ...b3. With the white rook on d1 taking on c4 allows that rook to come to the g-file after Bxc4 and Rdg1. }
14. Ncd5 c6
{ Black continues to harass the knight. Black has a complicated alternative in 14...e6 here. }
15. Nxh5
{ White tries to open up Black's kingside. Taking the pawn on b4 opens the b-file for Black after  15.Nxb4  Rb8  16.Nc2  c5  when Black has a very dangerous initiative on the queenside using the b-file and the long diagonal with ideas like ...Qb6 and ... Nc6. }
15... cxd5
{ By taking the centralised knight on d5 Black opens the c-file for ideas like ...Rc8 or ...Qc8. }
16. Nxg7 Kxg7
{ Black has the remarkable alternative  16...Rc8!?  that also gives him excellent counterchances, an incredible sample line is  17.Ne6!  Nxc4  18.Bxc4  Qa5  and you can take it from there! }
17. h5 b3 { An important tactical motif. The threat is ...bxa2. } 18. a3 Nxc4
{ Not just taking the pawn on c4 but also opening the c-file. } 19. Bxc4 Qc8
{ Getting the queen into play. } 20. Kb1 Qxc4 21. Rc1 Qb5
{ With unclear play where Black is currently two pawns up. He can defend his king with ...f5 to stabilise the knight on g4 or to run to d7. }
