{ In view of Black's threat of ...e5 and ...Nd4 this is White's only reasonable move. For example, the careless  7.Qd2?!  is met by  7...e5  8.d5  Nd4  with great play. }
7... a6
{ Black prepares for the possibility to push ...b5 and attack White's vulnerable c4-pawn. }
8. Qd2
{ The usual move. White finishes development and prepares Bh6,  0-0-0 or Rd1.  The move  8.h4  is met by  8...h5  and then play will be analogous as White again will likely play Qd2. }
8... Na5
{ A relatively fresh idea compared to the traditional move  8...Rb8  . Black immediately starts counterplay against the pawn on c4 and keeping the rook on a8 for now gives him additional tactical chances based on the fork ...Nb3. }
9. Nc1
{ This is White's best attempt. He safely covers the b3-square.  The naive  9.b3?!  shows the point of having the rook on a8 after  9...b5!  10.cxb5  axb5  11.Nxb5?  Nxb3  Black wins the exchange thanks to the pin on the a-file. }
9... Nd7
{ Preparing the ...c5 push. Black has interesting alternatives in:  A@@EndBracket@@  9...e5!?  10.d5  c5  which leads to typical closed KID positions.   B@@EndBracket@@  9...c5!?  , a pawn sacrifice after  10.dxc5  Be6  . }
10. h4
{ This is an important alternative, White starts kingside operations immediately. }
10... c5
{ Black executes his idea to push ...c5 and create play on the long diagonal.  An interesting alternative is  10...h5!?  11.Bh6  c5  12.d5  Ne5  which also leads to unclear play. }
11. h5
{ After  11.d5?!  b5  Black creates immediate counterplay on the queenside and obtains compensation in an improved @@StartBracket@@thanks to the weakening of the White position after the advance of the h-pawn@@EndBracket@@ Benko Gambit style after  12.cxb5  axb5  13.Bxb5  Ba6  . }
11... cxd4
{ With the exchanges on d4 Black obtains a favourable strategic position with the pawn structure from the Maroczy Bind but with the dark-squared bishops exchanged, something which is Black's dream in the Maroczy. }
12. Bxd4 Bxd4 13. Qxd4 Nf6
{ With the dark-squared bishops gone Black managed to weaken the dark squares in White's camp as there is no bishop to guard them. He also wants to exchange the queens when he will have a better endgame because of those dark-squared weaknesses and White's bad light-squared bishop as all White's pawns are on light squares.  White's only chance is to try to use the advanced h-pawn to create play on the kingside, but with careful play, Black manages to neutralise this. }
14. hxg6 { White opens the h-file. } 14... fxg6
{ The only move, as  14...hxg6??  15.Qe3  with Qh6 to come will see Black mated. }
15. Nb3 { White prepares long castle. } 15... Be6
{ Black finishes development. It is very important for Black to have good control over the d5-square and to capture White's knight with his bishop in case it appears there. }
16. O-O-O Nxb3+ { Liberating the a5-square for the queen. } 17. axb3 Qa5
{ The queen is active on a5, she controls the 5th rank and supports the ...b5 push. }
18. Kb1 Qg5
{ A good move. The queen's presence on the kingside ensures against any problems there. Black had a good alternative in  18...Rab8  , intending ...b5. }
19. Nd5 { Sooner or later White must jump to d5. } 19... Bxd5
{ Black should always take with a bishop as his knight is a better piece to take advantage of his control over the dark squares. }
20. exd5 Nd7
{ With the idea of ...a5 and either ...Nc5 or ...Ne5. Black has comfortable play on the dark squares and this gives him good counterchances. }
