{ Black prepares for the possibility to push ...b5 and attack White's vulnerable c4-pawn. }
8. Qd2
{ The usual move. White finishes development and prepares Bh6,  0-0-0 or Rd1.  The move  8.h4  is met by  8...h5  and then play will be analogous as White again will likely play Qd2. }
8... Na5
{ A relatively fresh idea compared to the traditional move  8...Rb8  . Black immediately starts counterplay against the pawn on c4 and keeping the rook on a8 for now gives him additional tactical chances based on the fork ...Nb3. }
9. Nc1
{ This is White's best attempt. He safely covers the b3-square.  The naive  9.b3?!  shows the point of having the rook on a8 after  9...b5!  10.cxb5  axb5  11.Nxb5?  Nxb3  Black wins the exchange thanks to the pin on the a-file. }
9... Nd7
{ Preparing the ...c5 push. Black has interesting alternatives in:  A@@EndBracket@@  9...e5!?  10.d5  c5  which leads to typical closed KID positions.   B@@EndBracket@@  9...c5!?  , a pawn sacrifice after  10.dxc5  Be6  . }
10. Rb1
{ White removes the rook from the long diagonal and prepares b4 when the pawn on b4 will be defended by the rook.  The immediate  10.b4  Nc6  11.Rb1  e5!  12.d5  Nd4  allows Black to achieve his idea of establishing a knight on d4. If White exchanges it Black will gladly do so and will proceed with the typical thrust ...f5.   The alternatives, except  10.h4  , are easier to deal with, for example:   A@@EndBracket@@  10.Be2  c5  11.dxc5  Ne5!  @@StartBracket@@hitting the pawn on c4@@EndBracket@@  12.b3  dxc5  with good play for Black as he forced White to weaken the long diagonal. If now White takes the pawn then after  13.Bxc5  Qc7  Black intends ...Rd8,  and ...Nac6 when the open d-file and the weakness of the d4-square give him ample compensation @@StartBracket@@if White jumps to d5 the knight can always be chased away with ...e6 after the queen moves@@EndBracket@@.   B@@EndBracket@@ Another option is  10.Bh6  Bxh6  11.Qxh6  b5!  sacrificing a pawn for great activity after  12.cxb5  axb5  13.Bxb5  c6  14.Bd3  e5  when Black will use the weakened dark squares and the b-file @@StartBracket@@for example with ...Qb6@@EndBracket@@ to obtain his compensation. }
10... Rb8
{ Since there are no more tricks based on ...Nb3 @@StartBracket@@as we saw in some of the other lines when the a-file was opened@@EndBracket@@ Black moves the rook on the b-file and stays flexible with his plans.  One idea of the move is to support the ...b5 push in a more direct fashion @@StartBracket@@for example after ...c5,  d5 ...b5 when Black hopes to obtain counterplay in Benko Gambit style@@EndBracket@@.  Black has a good alternative here in the move  10...c5!?  11.dxc5  dxc5  12.Nb3  Nxb3  13.axb3  e6  with a complex position. }
11. b4
{ White expands on the queenside. The other moves are less critical, for example,  11.Be2  c5  12.O-O  cxd4  13.Bxd4  Bxd4  14.Qxd4  Qb6!  when Black obtains an ideal Maroczy Bind endgame with no dark-squared bishops when he can freely play on the dark squares by putting a knight on c5,  playing ...a5 etc.   The exchange of the dark-squared bishops is met by the typical  11.Bh6  Bxh6  12.Qxh6  Nc6!  13.N1e2  e5  14.d5  Nd4  with comfortable equality - again the exchange of the dark-squared bishops works in Black's favour in view of the fact that his pawns are on dark squares, not limiting his remaining bishop. }
11... Nc6 { The only retreat, now Black threatens ...e5 followed by ...Nd4. }
12. N1e2
{ The knight cannot defend the d4-square from b3 because the pawn on b4 is lost. The other moves allow ...e5 followed by ...Nd4,  for example,  12.Be2  e5  13.d5  Nd4  14.O-O  f5  with comfortable play for Black in typical KID fashion when he wants to take on e2 and continue with the standard attack with ...f4,  ...g5,  ...Nf6,  ...g4 etc.   Chasing the knight from c6 with  12.d5  Nce5  13.Nb3  and now either  13...e6  or  13...Nb6  14.Na5  c6  allow Black to undermine White's over-extended centre.   The move  12.h4  is met by  12...h5  when again White is faced with the same choice. }
12... h5
{ A very interesting move that puts White in a strange situation that resembles a zugzwang! White's problem is the knight on e2 that cannot find its proper place and with it stuck on e2 @@StartBracket@@from where it controls d4 and prevents ...e5 and ...Nd4@@EndBracket@@ White cannot develop his kingside.  With his last move, Black takes away the g3-square from the knight as now Ng3 can be met by ...h4. So White is stuck!  Black has an alternative here in the move  12...f5!?  13.exf5  Nb6  14.Ng3  Bxf5  15.Nxf5  gxf5  with an unclear position with good counterchances for Black. }
13. Nc1 { This allows the typical reaction: } 13... e5 14. d5 Nd4
{ And here it's important to explore the consequences of the characteristic pawn sacrifice that Black frequently employs in the Saemisch. }
15. Nb3 c5
{ Practically forcing White to accept the pawn sacrifice as living with a knight on d4 is not very comfortable. }
16. dxc6 bxc6 { This opens the b-file. } 17. Nxd4 exd4 18. Bxd4 Ne5
{ Black has the equally good alternative in  18...Bxd4  19.Qxd4  Ne5  with the idea of ...c5 and ...Be6 which also gives him enough compensation. }
19. Be2 Be6
{ Attacking the pawn on c4 even though Black doesn't threaten to take it in view of the tactic Bxg7 and then Qd4 with check and attack on the piece on c4. }
20. O-O
{ An attempt to attack the knight with  20.f4  is met by  20...Bh6  and the pin on the f4-pawn keeps the knight on its central position. }
20... c5
{ This move controls the d4-square and now Black does threaten to take the pawn on c4. Doing so immediately loses to  20...Nxc4??  21.Bxc4  Bxc4  22.Bxg7  Kxg7  23.Qd4  winning the bishop on c4. }
21. Bxe5
{ A sad necessity for White if he wants to keep the extra pawn.  Taking the pawn on c5 is bad as  21.bxc5?  dxc5  22.Be3  Qxd2  23.Bxd2  Nxc4  gives Black a much better endgame in view of his activity and the passed c-pawn.   21.Be3  Nxc4  is also excellent for Black who regains the pawn and obtains the pair of bishops. }
21... Bxe5
{ Black has excellent compensation here in view of his domination on the dark squares, with the monster bishop on e5 being the crucial piece. He can continue with ...Bd4, ...Qf6 and emphasize his dark-square control. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. The Saemisch Variation"]
[Black "34. Saemisch Variation with 3.Nc3. White plays 6.Be3 #9"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. f3
{ This move is typical for the Saemisch Variation, named after the German GM Friedrich Saemisch. The idea is quite simple: since one aspect of Black's counterplay in the KID is the attack on the e4-pawn White immediately defends it securely. As an additional bonus the pawn on f3 covers the g4-square so this ensures a safe spot for the dark-squared bishop on e3.  However, there is a price to be paid for all these advantages. A long time ago, when GM Eduard Gufeld, a life-long and very successful KID player, was asked about the disadvantages of the Saemisch Variation he simply replied: 'Just ask the knight on g1!'  And he was right, the pawn on f3 takes away the natural developing square from the knight and the knight finds it difficult to get into the game - even when developed on e2 it blocks the bishop on f1 and needs further redeployment. As we shall see Black uses this problematic knight to create his counterplay. }
5... O-O
{ Black finishes development and is now ready to start play against White's centre. Now White has a choice where to develop his dark-squared bishop, to e3 or to g5.  Note that the move  6.Nge2  has no independent value because after  6...Nc6  White again needs to make the same choice about the development of the bishop, hence transposing to the main lines either after 6.Be3 or 6.Bg5. }
6. Be3 { This is the typical Saemisch development. } 6... Nc6
{ This is the Panno Variation. Black puts pressure on the d4-square and wants to play ...e5 and ...Nd4 if allowed.  The development of the knight on c6 also envisions queenside counterplay against the pawn on c4 after ...Na5, especially after White plays Nge2 - the knight on e2 makes the pawn on c4 vulnerable because the bishop on f1 no longer defends it.  The third idea of the move is a preparation of the ...b5 push after ...a6 and ...Rb8. It is curious to note that the Panno Variation was Bobby Fischer's choice when he faced the Saemisch Variation in his rematch with Boris Spassky in 1992 and he scored rather well with it - he won 2, lost 1 and drew 1. }
7. Nge2
{ In view of Black's threat of ...e5 and ...Nd4 this is White's only reasonable move. For example, the careless  7.Qd2?!  is met by  7...e5  8.d5  Nd4  with great play. }
7... a6
{ Black prepares for the possibility to push ...b5 and attack White's vulnerable c4-pawn. }
8. Qd2
{ The usual move. White finishes development and prepares Bh6,  0-0-0 or Rd1.  The move  8.h4  is met by  8...h5  and then play will be analogous as White again will likely play Qd2. }
8... Na5
{ A relatively fresh idea compared to the traditional move  8...Rb8  . Black immediately starts counterplay against the pawn on c4 and keeping the rook on a8 for now gives him additional tactical chances based on the fork ...Nb3. }
9. Nc1
{ This is White's best attempt. He safely covers the b3-square.  The naive  9.b3?!  shows the point of having the rook on a8 after  9...b5!  10.cxb5  axb5  11.Nxb5?  Nxb3  Black wins the exchange thanks to the pin on the a-file. }
9... Nd7
{ Preparing the ...c5 push. Black has interesting alternatives in:  A@@EndBracket@@  9...e5!?  10.d5  c5  which leads to typical closed KID positions.   B@@EndBracket@@  9...c5!?  , a pawn sacrifice after  10.dxc5  Be6  . }
10. Rb1
{ White removes the rook from the long diagonal and prepares b4 when the pawn on b4 will be defended by the rook.  The immediate  10.b4  Nc6  11.Rb1  e5!  12.d5  Nd4  allows Black to achieve his idea of establishing a knight on d4. If White exchanges it Black will gladly do so and will proceed with the typical thrust ...f5.   The alternatives, except  10.h4  , are easier to deal with, for example:   A@@EndBracket@@  10.Be2  c5  11.dxc5  Ne5!  @@StartBracket@@hitting the pawn on c4@@EndBracket@@  12.b3  dxc5  with good play for Black as he forced White to weaken the long diagonal. If now White takes the pawn then after  13.Bxc5  Qc7  Black intends ...Rd8,  and ...Nac6 when the open d-file and the weakness of the d4-square give him ample compensation @@StartBracket@@if White jumps to d5 the knight can always be chased away with ...e6 after the queen moves@@EndBracket@@.   B@@EndBracket@@ Another option is  10.Bh6  Bxh6  11.Qxh6  b5!  sacrificing a pawn for great activity after  12.cxb5  axb5  13.Bxb5  c6  14.Bd3  e5  when Black will use the weakened dark squares and the b-file @@StartBracket@@for example with ...Qb6@@EndBracket@@ to obtain his compensation. }
10... Rb8
{ Since there are no more tricks based on ...Nb3 @@StartBracket@@as we saw in some of the other lines when the a-file was opened@@EndBracket@@ Black moves the rook on the b-file and stays flexible with his plans.  One idea of the move is to support the ...b5 push in a more direct fashion @@StartBracket@@for example after ...c5,  d5 ...b5 when Black hopes to obtain counterplay in Benko Gambit style@@EndBracket@@.  Black has a good alternative here in the move  10...c5!?  11.dxc5  dxc5  12.Nb3  Nxb3  13.axb3  e6  with a complex position. }
11. b4
{ White expands on the queenside. The other moves are less critical, for example,  11.Be2  c5  12.O-O  cxd4  13.Bxd4  Bxd4  14.Qxd4  Qb6!  when Black obtains an ideal Maroczy Bind endgame with no dark-squared bishops when he can freely play on the dark squares by putting a knight on c5,  playing ...a5 etc.   The exchange of the dark-squared bishops is met by the typical  11.Bh6  Bxh6  12.Qxh6  Nc6!  13.N1e2  e5  14.d5  Nd4  with comfortable equality - again the exchange of the dark-squared bishops works in Black's favour in view of the fact that his pawns are on dark squares, not limiting his remaining bishop. }
11... Nc6 { The only retreat, now Black threatens ...e5 followed by ...Nd4. }
12. N1e2
{ The knight cannot defend the d4-square from b3 because the pawn on b4 is lost. The other moves allow ...e5 followed by ...Nd4,  for example,  12.Be2  e5  13.d5  Nd4  14.O-O  f5  with comfortable play for Black in typical KID fashion when he wants to take on e2 and continue with the standard attack with ...f4,  ...g5,  ...Nf6,  ...g4 etc.   Chasing the knight from c6 with  12.d5  Nce5  13.Nb3  and now either  13...e6  or  13...Nb6  14.Na5  c6  allow Black to undermine White's over-extended centre.   The move  12.h4  is met by  12...h5  when again White is faced with the same choice. }
12... h5
{ A very interesting move that puts White in a strange situation that resembles a zugzwang! White's problem is the knight on e2 that cannot find its proper place and with it stuck on e2 @@StartBracket@@from where it controls d4 and prevents ...e5 and ...Nd4@@EndBracket@@ White cannot develop his kingside.  With his last move, Black takes away the g3-square from the knight as now Ng3 can be met by ...h4. So White is stuck!  Black has an alternative here in the move  12...f5!?  13.exf5  Nb6  14.Ng3  Bxf5  15.Nxf5  gxf5  with an unclear position with good counterchances for Black. }
13. a3
{ A useful move that defends the b4-pawn, but one that doesn't help White's development.  A move like  13.h4  is met by  13...e6  and White again needs to decide what to do with his clogged kingside. }
13... e6
{ Another useful waiting move for Black, putting the onus again on White. } 14.
Nc1
{ When the knight leaves control over the d4-square Black executes the ...e5 push. }
14... e5
{ The typical reaction. Black has a good alternative in  14...f5!?  15.exf5  gxf5  with further ideas like ...e5,  ...Qh4 or ...f4. }
15. d5 Nd4 16. Nb3
{ The move  16.N1e2  doesn't change anything as the game transposes after  16...c5  17.dxc6  bxc6  18.Nxd4  exd4  . }
16... c5
{ The characteristic pawn sacrifice that we also sawafter White's 13.Nc1. } 17.
dxc6 bxc6 18. Nxd4 exd4 19. Bxd4
{ The difference withthe line after 13.Nc1 is that here White has the extra tempo a3, which helps him defend the pawn on b4. }
19... Ne5
{ With the pawn on b4 protected Black concentrates on the pawn on c4 - he wants to play ...Be6, just like inthe analogous line after 13.Nc1. }
20. Be2 Be6 { Targeting the pawn on c4. } 21. O-O c5
{ Again this important move that takes away the d4-square from the white pieces.  Note that again taking on c4 immediately loses a piece to  21...Nxc4??  22.Bxc4  Bxc4  23.Bxg7  Kxg7  24.Qd4  winning the bishop on c4. }
22. Bxe5 { The only way for White if he is to keep the extra pawn. } 22... Bxe5
{ Black has excellent compensation here. It is all about the dark squares and Black is the absolute master here. He has ideas like ...Bd4 and ...Qf6 or ...cxb4 and ...Qb6. }
