17... Nd7 { Preparing the ...b5 break. } 18. Kf2
{ 18.Bg2  b5  is good for Black, for example  19.O-O  Nb6  20.c5  Nc4  . With the king move, White defends the bishop on e3 and is preparing for the ...b5-push. }
18... b5 { Black continues with his plan. } 19. cxb5 axb5
{ Now Black intends ...Nb6-c4. Play is very complex and a sample line is: } 20.
d5
{ Now we see White's plan of keeping the bishop on f1 - after the knight on c6 moves he intends to play Nd4 and take the pawn on b5. }
20... exd5
{ Black opens the play, which is natural since White has a king in the centre. }
21. exd5 Ne7
{ The e5-square is reserved for the knight on d7. The knight on e7 keeps an eye on the d5-pawn and can come to f5. }
22. Nd4 Ne5 { Both sides continue with their plans. } 23. Bxb5 Rxb5
{ A powerful exchange sacrifice. } 24. Ncxb5
{ The other capture  24.Ndxb5?!  allows  24...Bg4!  with the idea  25.fxg4?!  Nxg4  26.Kf3  Nxe3  27.Kxe3  Bxc3  28.Nxc3  Nxd5  when we see how handy the queen on the e8 is - the discovered check ...Nxd5 regains all sacrificed material after the further ...Nxc3-Nxd1. }
24... Bb7 { Attacking the pawn on d5. } 25. Nc3 c5
{ The position is a mess but Black has excellent counterplay in the centre and ultimately against White's king. }
26. bxc5 dxc5 27. Ndb5 c4
{ Black's threats become much more concrete with ...Nd3 and ...Nxd5 being the main ones. }
