[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. The Four Pawns Attack"]
[Black "36. The Four Pawns Attack with 7.fxe5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. f4
{ In the beginning of the KID the Four Pawns Attack was considered the refutation of this defence. White's strategy is very direct, he takes up maximum space and wants to strangulate Black. Nowadays the line is not considered a critical one as Black has more than one good way to deal with it. }
5... O-O { Black castles as usual. } 6. Nf3
{ White's setup is quite aggressive. He wants to use his central superiority to create an attack either in the centre @@StartBracket@@by pushing e5@@EndBracket@@ or on the kingside. }
6... e5
{ The shocking effect of this move never ceases to amaze me. White controls the e5-square 3 times and yet it is exactly there that Black strikes!  This move also changes the character of the game, as now White has a choice - either to take a pawn and allow Black compensation in view of a pleasant initiative or to allow his centre to be attacked. Now White needs to decide how to take on e5. }
7. fxe5 dxe5 8. d5
{ White wants to keep his centre intact. Taking on e5 is bad:  A@@EndBracket@@  8.Nxe5?  c5  destroys White's centre.   B@@EndBracket@@  8.dxe5?  Qxd1  9.Kxd1  Ng4  is much better for Black who will regain the pawn on e5 and will have the better structure in the endgame. }
8... c6 { Black undermines White's centre. } 9. Bd3
{ In case of  9.Be2  b5  we will have a similar development. } 9... b5
{ Black aggressively attacks White's centre from the queenside. } 10. O-O
{ Taking any pawn is bad, for example:  A@@EndBracket@@  10.cxb5?!  cxd5  and White's centre is in tatters.   B@@EndBracket@@ After  10.dxc6?!  bxc4  11.Bxc4  Qxd1  12.Nxd1  Nxc6  Black is better in the endgame because of the weakness of White's pawn on e4. }
10... bxc4 { Black eliminates one defender of the pawn on d5. } 11. Bxc4 Qd6
{ This is a bit more ambitious than the straight-forward alternative  11...cxd5  12.Nxd5  Ba6  , which also gives Black comfortable equality. Now the threat is ...Qc5,  winning the bishop on c4. }
12. Kh1 { Getting the king away from the sensitive g1-a7 diagonal. } 12... Ba6
{ Black finishes development with tempo, attacking the bishop on c4. } 13. Bxa6
Nxa6 14. Bg5
{ White fights for control over the d5-square, the only way to keep his centre. He attacks the knight on f6 that puts pressure on the pawn on d5.  In case of  14.dxc6  Qxc6  15.Nxe5  Qe6  with ...Nc5 next, Black's activity and pressure on e4 compensate for the pawn. }
14... cxd5
{ With this exchange Black forces White to play with an isolated pawn, the only choice is whether it will be on e4 or d5. }
15. exd5
{ In case of  15.Bxf6  Qxf6  16.Nxd5  Qd6  Black wants to continue playing against White's centre by ...Nc7. Long term he has the advantage of the better pawn structure because of the white pawn on e4 that will need constant attention. In addition to this Black has the option of pushing ...f5 and obtaining a passed pawn on the e-file. }
15... h6
{ An equally good alternative is  15...Nc5  16.Nd2  Ncd7  , connecting the knights. In this pawn structure, Black wants to control the passed d-pawn and advance his own pawn pair consisting of the e- and f-pawns. }
16. Bxf6 { White exchanges the bishop and wants to control the e4-square. }
16... Qxf6
{ Taking with the bishop allows Ne4, hitting both the queen and the bishop, which makes Black's position somewhat loose. }
17. Nd4
{ The knight comes to c6.  Playing  17.Ne4  is harmless after  17...Qb6  , hitting the pawn on b2 and threatening ...f5. }
17... Qb6 { Hitting both the knight on d4 and the pawn on b2. } 18. Nc6 Nb8
{ It's important to challenge the knight on c6 to gain a tempo and to have pieces around the passed d-pawn. The knight on b8 is en-route to d7 from where it will blockade the passed d-pawn.  As an illustration, taking on b2 after  18...Qxb2?!  19.Qc1!  Qxc1  20.Raxc1  gives White excellent compensation because of the dominating knight on c6 and the passed d-pawn. }
19. Qb3 Kh7
{ Moving the king away from the a2-g8 diagonal and preparing ...f5.  Taking on c6 is not very good in view of  19...Nxc6?!  20.Qxb6  axb6  21.dxc6  when White has a dangerous passed pawn on c6. }
20. Rac1 Nd7
{ Establishing a solid blockade of the passed d-pawn. Now that it doesn't represent danger Black is ready to advance his own pawns with ...f5, ...e4 etc with good play. }
