[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. The Four Pawns Attack"]
[Black "37. The Four Pawns Attack with 7.dxe5. White plays 8.Nxe5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. f4
{ In the beginning of the KID the Four Pawns Attack was considered the refutation of this defence. White's strategy is very direct, he takes up maximum space and wants to strangulate Black. Nowadays the line is not considered a critical one as Black has more than one good way to deal with it. }
5... O-O { Black castles as usual. } 6. Nf3
{ White's setup is quite aggressive. He wants to use his central superiority to create an attack either in the centre @@StartBracket@@by pushing e5@@EndBracket@@ or on the kingside. }
6... e5
{ The shocking effect of this move never ceases to amaze me. White controls the e5-square 3 times and yet it is exactly there that Black strikes!  This move also changes the character of the game, as now White has a choice - either to take a pawn and allow Black compensation in view of a pleasant initiative or to allow his centre to be attacked. Now White needs to decide how to take on e5. }
7. dxe5 dxe5 8. Nxe5
{ This is an alternative to the exchange of queens, allowing Black to take on d1, but this robs White of the right to castle. }
8... Qxd1+ 9. Kxd1 Re8
{ By putting the rook on the e-file Black pins the knight on e5 because of the pressure on the e4-pawn. Now he wants to attack it by ...Nbd7 and when the knight on e5 is removed to attack the pawn on e4. }
10. Bd2 { White develops his queenside as he cannot prevent Black's ...Nbd7. }
10... Nbd7
{ Now White is forced to exchange on d7. Black has a good alternative in  10...Na6  with the idea of ...Nac5 and/or ...Nd7. }
11. Nxd7 Bxd7
{ Black finished development and now has concrete play in the centre and against the white pawn on the e-file. }
12. Bd3
{ Defending the pawn on e4. Pushing it is worse, after  12.e5?!  Ng4  13.Kc1  Rad8  Black has a lot of threats, for example, ...Nf2,  ...Bf5 and ...Nd3,  taking advantage of the weakened light squares. }
12... Rad8 { Mobilising the last piece. } 13. Kc2
{ Defending the bishop on d3. Note that doing the same from e2 loses to  13.Ke2??  Bg4  14.Ke3  Bf8  when all of a sudden White's king is in a mating net! }
13... Ng4 { Threatening ...Nf2. } 14. Raf1
{ Covering the f2-square. The other rook must stay on h1 to defend the pawn on h2. }
14... Bxc3
{ With this exchange Black eliminates the knight that defends the pawn on e4 and forces White to recapture with king. }
15. Kxc3 { Of course,  15.Bxc3?  Ne3  wins the exchange. } 15... Bc6
{ White has problems with the pawn on e4 and on the long diagonal. } 16. h3 Nf6
{ Adding one more piece to the attack. } 17. e5
{ The only way to save the pawn. } 17... Rxd3+
{ An attempt to keep more life in the position.  Black has simple equality after  17...Ne4  18.Bxe4  Bxe4  with no problems in a position with opposite-coloured bishops where his bishop is the more active one. }
18. Kxd3 Ne4
{ Threatening ...Rd8, winning the bishop on d2, and ...Ng3, regaining the exchange. }
19. Be1 { Defending against both threats, but allowing: } 19... Nc5+ 20. Ke3
{ Or  20.Kd4  Ne6  with ...Bxg2 next. } 20... Bxg2
{ Black regains both the pawn and the exchange and can try to play for more thanks to his better structure - he has 2 pawn islands compared to White's 3 and the e5 and f4 pawns can be attacked by ...f6 or ...Ne6 and ...f5, fixing the pawn on f4. }
