[White "3. The Four Pawns Attack"]
[Black "38. The Four Pawns Attack with 7.dxe5. White plays 8.Qxd8 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. f4
{ In the beginning of the KID the Four Pawns Attack was considered the refutation of this defence. White's strategy is very direct, he takes up maximum space and wants to strangulate Black. Nowadays the line is not considered a critical one as Black has more than one good way to deal with it. }
5... O-O { Black castles as usual. } 6. Nf3
{ White's setup is quite aggressive. He wants to use his central superiority to create an attack either in the centre @@StartBracket@@by pushing e5@@EndBracket@@ or on the kingside. }
6... e5
{ The shocking effect of this move never ceases to amaze me. White controls the e5-square 3 times and yet it is exactly there that Black strikes!  This move also changes the character of the game, as now White has a choice - either to take a pawn and allow Black compensation in view of a pleasant initiative or to allow his centre to be attacked. Now White needs to decide how to take on e5. }
7. dxe5 dxe5 8. Qxd8 Rxd8 9. Nxe5
{ This is an alternative, but Black has no problems after: } 9... b6
{ With the idea of ...Bb7, attacking the pawn on e4. } 10. Be2
{ Intending Bf3,  to defend the e4-pawn.  The premature  10.Nd5?!  allows  10...Nxe4!  11.Nxc7  Na6!  12.Nxa8  Nb4  when Black's initiative @@StartBracket@@the threat is ...Nc2@@EndBracket@@ and the stranded knight on a8 will ensure he regains the material. }
10... Bb7 { Continuing the plan. } 11. Bf3 Nbd7
{ Challenging the knight on e5 and forcing its exchange. } 12. Nxd7 Nxd7
{ Threatening ...Nc5 when a lot of new threats will appear: ...Nd3, the capture on c3 followed by the capture on e4. White is under pressure here to deal with these ideas, for example, the natural... }
13. O-O { ... is bad in view of: } 13... Bd4+
{ First forcing the king further away from the centre. } 14. Kh1 Bxc3
{ Now wrecking White's queenside. } 15. bxc3 Nc5
{ And Black is clearly better here as White has way too many weaknesses to take care of: the pawns on e4, c3 and c4 and the d3-square cannot all be defended. }
