[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. The Four Pawns Attack"]
[Black "39. The Four Pawns Attack with 7.dxe5. White plays 8.Qxd8 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. f4
{ In the beginning of the KID the Four Pawns Attack was considered the refutation of this defence. White's strategy is very direct, he takes up maximum space and wants to strangulate Black. Nowadays the line is not considered a critical one as Black has more than one good way to deal with it. }
5... O-O { Black castles as usual. } 6. Nf3
{ White's setup is quite aggressive. He wants to use his central superiority to create an attack either in the centre @@StartBracket@@by pushing e5@@EndBracket@@ or on the kingside. }
6... e5
{ The shocking effect of this move never ceases to amaze me. White controls the e5-square 3 times and yet it is exactly there that Black strikes!  This move also changes the character of the game, as now White has a choice - either to take a pawn and allow Black compensation in view of a pleasant initiative or to allow his centre to be attacked. Now White needs to decide how to take on e5. }
7. dxe5 dxe5 8. Qxd8 Rxd8 9. fxe5
{ This wrecks White's central pawns, but it gains a tempo. } 9... Nfd7
{ Attacking the pawn on e5. From d7 the knight can further go to c5 or f8.  However, the alternative  9...Ng4  is also playable after  10.Nd5  Rd7  followed by ...c6,  getting rid of the knight on d5. }
10. Bf4
{ White clings onto the pawn.  The move  10.Nd5  is met by  10...Na6  with ...c6 to come.   Giving the pawn back by  10.e6  fxe6  11.Bf4  Na6  gives Black a comfortable position, for example,  12.e5  Ndc5  13.Be2  b6  with ...Bb7 next. }
10... Re8
{ Black's play is very simple, he concentrates on White's pawns on the e-file, the one on e5 in particular. }
11. O-O-O Na6
{ Taking the pawn on e5 is premature because White penetrates to the 8th rank after  11...Nxe5??  12.Nxe5  Bxe5  13.Bxe5  Rxe5  14.Rd8  winning the bishop on c8. }
12. Be2 { White finishes development and defends the pawn on e5 indirectly. }
12... h5
{ A great prophylactic move we can only understand if we understand White's last move. The point of White's 12th move was that after  12...Nxe5?  13.Nxe5  Bxe5  14.Bxe5  Rxe5  15.Rd8  Kg7  16.Bg4!  White wins the bishop on c8. Now we understand the importance of the g4-square, hence Black's 12th move. }
13. h4
{ Another prophylactic move by White, again aimed against the capture on e5. }
13... c6
{ A useful move, taking control over the d5 and b5-squares. Let's see what happens if Black takes on e5 instead:  This time White doesn't win, but he keeps the initiative after  13...Nxe5  14.Nxe5  Bxe5  15.Bxe5  Rxe5  16.Rd8  Kg7  17.g4!  This is White's idea: He fixed the h5-pawn with his 13th move and now uses the time Black needs to untangle with ...b6 and ...Bb7 to create a weakness on h5 by playing gxh5. White is somewhat better in that endgame. }
14. Rd2 { Intending to double on the d-file. } 14... Ndc5
{ Black wants to develop his bishop on g4. } 15. Rhd1 Bg4
{ Both sides finished development. Black's plan remains the same, he concentrates his play against White's doubled e-pawns.  One idea he has now is to regain the pawn by taking on f3 and then on e5, though he is not forced to do it - White's extra pawn has no importance in this position as he cannot create a passed pawn and in fact, the extra pawn is only a weakness in White's position that he is forced to defend because if he loses that extra pawn without anything in return he will be worse in view of the weakness of the other e-pawn. }
16. Kb1
{ In case of  16.Be3  Black can consider  16...Bxf3  17.gxf3  Bxe5  followed by ...Ne6 with excellent control over the f4 and d4-squares and great play on the dark squares. }
16... Ne6 17. Bh2 { Keeping the pawn on e5 defended. } 17... Bh6
{ Black activates his pieces along the dark squares. } 18. Rd6 Nf4
{ Black can repeat moves if he wishes with  18...Bf8  19.R6d2  Bh6  , but no reason why not to keep on playing. }
19. Bf1 Nc5
{ Black has excellent compensation here. As before, White's extra pawn is only a weakness to defend and all Black's pieces are actively placed.  Now he wants to stabilise the knight on c5 by playing ...a5 and then he can continue to manoeuvre against the doubled e-pawns, perhaps at some point taking on f3 and e5 and continuing play on the dark squares, for example after ...Nce6, ...Bg7 and then ...Bxf3 and ...Bxe5 with domination on the dark squares. }
