[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. The Averbakh Variation"]
[Black "40. Averbakh Variation with 6.Be3 8.h4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Be2 O-O 6. Be3
{ This system is one of the most popular against the KID nowadays. Its idea is similar to the Makagonov System - White wants to advance on the kingside with g4, h4 etc. thus either suffocating Black's counterplay there or creating an attack on the kingside himself. The difference with the Makagonov is that here White controls the g4-square with the bishop on e2, while there White plays h3. }
6... e5 { Black strikes in the centre with the usual move. } 7. d5
{ White closes the centre and will continue with g4 and h4.  Note that the move  7.Nf3  leads to the Gligoric Variation. }
7... Na6
{ Black develops the knight on a6 in order not to block the bishop on c8 and intends to put it on c5 to attack the pawn on e4. }
8. h4 { This is an alternative way to advance on the kingside. } 8... Nc5
{ Black attacks the pawn on e4. } 9. Qc2
{ If White defends the pawn with a bishop then after  9.Bf3  h5  Black stops White's kingside expansion. If now White expands on the other side of the board then Black can take advantage of that expansion after  10.b4  Ncd7  11.Nh3  a5!  12.a3  Nb6  attacking the pawn on c4 and threatening to take on h3 after which White's rook will be misplaced on h3 and Black can take over the a-file after playing ...Qd7,  ...axb4,  exchange on a1 and come to a8 with the other rook. }
9... c6
{ Opening the a5-d8 diagonal for the queen. Black wants to play ...Qa5 to activate the queen and indirectly attack the pawn on e4 in view of the pin on the knight on c3. }
10. Bxc5
{ This surprising exchange is White's best bet.  In case of  10.h5  Qa5  @@StartBracket@@now the pawn on e4 is hanging@@EndBracket@@  11.h6  Bh8  12.f3  Nh5  with threats like ...Ng3 or ...f5 Black obtains good play.   Note that  10.b4?  is a big mistake due to the tactical refutation  10...Ncxe4!  11.Nxe4  Nxe4  12.Qxe4  Bf5  13.Qf3  e4  winning the rook on a1. }
10... dxc5 11. h5 Re8
{ Liberating the f8-square for the bishop in case White plays h6. The middlegame is quite complex where Black will aim to use the unopposed dark-squared bishop by opening the game.  One idea is to capture on d5 and exchange knights there and then depending on which way White recaptures @@StartBracket@@exd5 or cxd5@@EndBracket@@ to advance the majority he obtains @@StartBracket@@...e4 in case of exd5 and ...c4 in case of cxd5@@EndBracket@@. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. The Averbakh Variation"]
[Black "41. Averbakh Variation with 6.Be3 8.g4. White plays 9.Bf3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Be2 O-O 6. Be3
{ This system is one of the most popular against the KID nowadays. Its idea is similar to the Makagonov System - White wants to advance on the kingside with g4, h4 etc. thus either suffocating Black's counterplay there or creating an attack on the kingside himself. The difference with the Makagonov is that here White controls the g4-square with the bishop on e2, while there White plays h3. }
6... e5 { Black strikes in the centre with the usual move. } 7. d5
{ White closes the centre and will continue with g4 and h4.  Note that the move  7.Nf3  leads to the Gligoric Variation. }
7... Na6
{ Black develops the knight on a6 in order not to block the bishop on c8 and intends to put it on c5 to attack the pawn on e4. }
8. g4
{ White continues with his plan.  The move  8.Nf3?!  is not in line with the idea of the line and after  8...Ng4  9.Bg5  f6  10.Bh4  g5  11.Bg3  Nh6  with ...f5 next Black has great play. }
8... Nc5
{ Attacking the pawn on e4. Now White can defend it in two ways, with a pawn or with a bishop. }
9. Bf3 c6
{ Black starts immediate counterplay in the centre. This is a typical ploy in the KID, that whenever Black is unable to commence activity on the kingside because of White's expansion there he should start activity on the queenside instead. }
10. g5
{ White wants to dislodge the knight from f6 and prevent the sacrifice on e4 that is possible after the immediate  10.b4  . }
10... Nfd7 { Connecting the knights. The pawn sacrifice is only temporary: }
11. dxc6
{ If White doesn't take the pawn Black will take on d5 and play ...a5 to stabilise the knight on c5.  In case of  11.b4  Na6  12.a3  cxd5  13.cxd5  f5  play is unclear but Black has good chances because of White's long-term problem with his king safety - the king won't find safe shelter anywhere. }
11... bxc6 12. Qxd6 Ne6
{ Black's threats of ...Nd4 or ...Nxg5 ensure that he regains the material with excellent play. }
