[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. The Averbakh Variation"]
[Black "42. Averbakh Variation with 6.Be3 8.g4. White plays 9.Bf3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Be2 O-O 6. Be3
{ This system is one of the most popular against the KID nowadays. Its idea is similar to the Makagonov System - White wants to advance on the kingside with g4, h4 etc. thus either suffocating Black's counterplay there or creating an attack on the kingside himself. The difference with the Makagonov is that here White controls the g4-square with the bishop on e2, while there White plays h3. }
6... e5 { Black strikes in the centre with the usual move. } 7. d5
{ White closes the centre and will continue with g4 and h4.  Note that the move  7.Nf3  leads to the Gligoric Variation. }
7... Na6
{ Black develops the knight on a6 in order not to block the bishop on c8 and intends to put it on c5 to attack the pawn on e4. }
8. g4
{ White continues with his plan.  The move  8.Nf3?!  is not in line with the idea of the line and after  8...Ng4  9.Bg5  f6  10.Bh4  g5  11.Bg3  Nh6  with ...f5 next Black has great play. }
8... Nc5
{ Attacking the pawn on e4. Now White can defend it in two ways, with a pawn or with a bishop. }
9. Bf3 c6
{ Black starts immediate counterplay in the centre. This is a typical ploy in the KID, that whenever Black is unable to commence activity on the kingside because of White's expansion there he should start activity on the queenside instead. }
10. b4 cxd5 { With the threat of ...d4, so White must recapture. } 11. cxd5
Ncxe4
{ A very sharp sacrifice that is motivated by the fact that the white king is still in the centre and White's lag in development in addition to his problems on the long diagonal.  As an alternative, retreating to d7 is also fine for Black. }
12. Nxe4 Nxe4 13. Bxe4 f5 { Opening the game further. } 14. gxf5 gxf5 15. Bc2
{ The bishop remains on the b1-h7 diagonal as White wants to use it to create threats against Black's king after Black plays ...f4.  Going to g2 is bad:  15.Bg2?  f4  16.Bd2  e4  shows the power of the pawns as they march forward to open up White's king position after ...e3 when Black has a practically winning attack. }
15... f4 { Continuing the advance with tempo. } 16. Qh5
{ If White retreats  16.Bd2?  e4!  again with the idea of ...e3 Black has a very strong attack. }
16... e4
{ Temporarily closing the b1-h7 diagonal to attack the rook on a1. Now with the rook on a1 and the bishop on e3 hanging Black is assured that he will regain the material. }
17. Bxe4 h6
{ Black has the crazy alternative  17...Rf7!?  18.Rc1  fxe3  19.Nf3  exf2  20.Kxf2  Kf8  when neither king is safe and chaos prevails on the board. }
18. Qg6 Qf6
{ Black covers the g6-square so after a check on h7 his king will be safe on f7. }
19. Qh7+ Kf7 20. Rc1 fxe3 { Getting the piece back. } 21. fxe3 Bd7
{ Black finished development in this very sharp position where he has very good chances thanks to his pair of bishops and the open position of White's king.  All endgames are also good for Black as in an open position his bishops will give him more than enough compensation for the pawn. }
