[White "4. The Averbakh Variation"]
[Black "43. Averbakh Variation with 6.Be3 8.g4. White plays 9.f3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Be2 O-O 6. Be3
{ This system is one of the most popular against the KID nowadays. Its idea is similar to the Makagonov System - White wants to advance on the kingside with g4, h4 etc. thus either suffocating Black's counterplay there or creating an attack on the kingside himself. The difference with the Makagonov is that here White controls the g4-square with the bishop on e2, while there White plays h3. }
6... e5 { Black strikes in the centre with the usual move. } 7. d5
{ White closes the centre and will continue with g4 and h4.  Note that the move  7.Nf3  leads to the Gligoric Variation. }
7... Na6
{ Black develops the knight on a6 in order not to block the bishop on c8 and intends to put it on c5 to attack the pawn on e4. }
8. g4
{ White continues with his plan.  The move  8.Nf3?!  is not in line with the idea of the line and after  8...Ng4  9.Bg5  f6  10.Bh4  g5  11.Bg3  Nh6  with ...f5 next Black has great play. }
8... Nc5
{ Attacking the pawn on e4. Now White can defend it in two ways, with a pawn or with a bishop. }
9. f3 h5
{ Black undermines White's expanded kingside, using the fact that with his last move White closed the d1-h5 diagonal so there is no pressure on the h5-pawn. }
10. h4
{ This is a sharp pawn sacrifice that aims to open files on the kingside. }
10... hxg4
{ Black takes the pawn. The ensuing positions are sharp, but they put pressure on White to prove the compensation. }
11. b4
{ White cannot take on g4 because his pawn on e4 is hanging so he first kicks away the knight on c5. }
11... gxf3 { Winning the pawn. } 12. Bxf3
{ The forced recapture, defending the pawn on e4. } 12... Ncd7
{ The natural retreat.  Black has the aggressive alternative  12...Ncxe4!?  13.Nxe4  Nxe4  14.Bxe4  f5  where he obtains a mass of pawns for the sacrificed piece leading to a murky position. }
13. h5 { White continues with his plan to open the files on the kingside. }
13... Nh7
{ A good defensive move with the idea ...g5, which would close the kingside and make it more difficult for White to create play on the kingside. }
14. hxg6
{ Opening the h-file.  In case of  14.Qd2  g5  15.O-O-O  a5  16.b5  @@StartBracket@@trying to keep the queenside closed@@EndBracket@@  16...Nb6  17.Qe2  Bh6  Black stabilised his kingside and White's compensation isn't very obvious. In the future Black can consider pushing ...f5 to open the game and to try to convert the extra pawn. }
14... fxg6 15. Qd2 Rf4
{ A very important motif for Black in all the lines of this variation. He is more than happy to sacrifice an exchange for White's dark-squared bishop in order to dominate the dark squares. As a general rule of thumb, whenever White accepts the sacrifice Black obtains wonderful compensation thanks to his unopposed dark-squared bishop, his control over the long diagonal and access to the e5-square.  The position is sharp but being a pawn up and with ideas like ...Rh4 @@StartBracket@@to exchange White's active rook in case White doesn't take on f4@@EndBracket@@, ...a5 @@StartBracket@@to try to open the queenside@@EndBracket@@ and ...Nb6 @@StartBracket@@targeting the pawn on c4@@EndBracket@@ Black has quite a few things to look forward to. }
