[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. The Averbakh Variation"]
[Black "44. Averbakh Variation with 6.Be3 8.g4. White plays 9.f3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Be2 O-O 6. Be3
{ This system is one of the most popular against the KID nowadays. Its idea is similar to the Makagonov System - White wants to advance on the kingside with g4, h4 etc. thus either suffocating Black's counterplay there or creating an attack on the kingside himself. The difference with the Makagonov is that here White controls the g4-square with the bishop on e2, while there White plays h3. }
6... e5 { Black strikes in the centre with the usual move. } 7. d5
{ White closes the centre and will continue with g4 and h4.  Note that the move  7.Nf3  leads to the Gligoric Variation. }
7... Na6
{ Black develops the knight on a6 in order not to block the bishop on c8 and intends to put it on c5 to attack the pawn on e4. }
8. g4
{ White continues with his plan.  The move  8.Nf3?!  is not in line with the idea of the line and after  8...Ng4  9.Bg5  f6  10.Bh4  g5  11.Bg3  Nh6  with ...f5 next Black has great play. }
8... Nc5
{ Attacking the pawn on e4. Now White can defend it in two ways, with a pawn or with a bishop. }
9. f3 h5
{ Black undermines White's expanded kingside, using the fact that with his last move White closed the d1-h5 diagonal so there is no pressure on the h5-pawn. }
10. g5 { The most natural and main move. } 10... Nh7
{ Getting away with tempo. } 11. h4 f6
{ Black continues to put pressure on the pawn on g5 and manages to open the f-file. After the exchange of pawns the pawn on h4 will also become vulnerable. Now White has a choice, to exchange on f6 or to allow Black to take on g5. }
12. Qd2 fxg5 { Black opens the f-file. } 13. hxg5 Rf4
{ The usual motif for Black in this line. He uses the f4-square for his rook and is happy to sacrifice the exchange so that he obtains absolute control over the dark squares. The rook on f4 also closes the c1-h6 diagonal so Black now wants to collect the pawn on g5. }
14. Bxf4
{ Taking material is critical. If White ignores the rook Black will take on g5 with his knight, for example,  14.b4  Na6  15.Rb1  Nxg5  with sharp play where Black wants to retreat the knight to f7 and then possibly play ...Rh4. }
14... exf4 15. Qxf4 Nxg5
{ A picturesque position demonstrating the strength of Black's compensation on the dark squares. Black has easy play as he wants to proceed with ...Be5 and ...Qf6 obtaining total control over the dark squares on both sides of the board. }
16. Qe3 { White attempts to break the grip on the dark squares by pushing f4. }
16... Be5
{ If allowed Black will play ...Qf6 next and White will be boxed in so his next is understandable. }
17. f4
{ After  17.O-O-O  Qf6  followed by ...Bd7 Black is dominating. He will try to soften White's queenside with ...a5-a4-a3 and force further weakening of White's position. }
17... Bxc3+
{ Black is forced to give up his dominating bishop but he obtains a strong centralised knight in return. }
18. bxc3
{ White is also forced to wreck his structure because after  18.Qxc3?!  Ngxe4  19.Qe3  Bf5  followed by ...Qd7 or ...Qf6 and ...Re8 Black has a very menacing position. }
18... Ngxe4 19. Nf3 Qf6 { Attacking the pawn on c3. } 20. Nd4 Bd7
{ Finishing development and letting the rook out. Black has excellent compensation here because his knights are very strong as they cannot be dislodged and White has pawn weaknesses @@StartBracket@@f4, c4, c3@@EndBracket@@ in addition to the problem of his king's safety.  Black can combine his play in the centre with the advance of the passed h-pawn where ...h4 and ...Ng3 is the main idea. }
