[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. The Averbakh Variation"]
[Black "45. Averbakh Variation with 6.Be3 8.g4. White plays 9.f3 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Be2 O-O 6. Be3
{ This system is one of the most popular against the KID nowadays. Its idea is similar to the Makagonov System - White wants to advance on the kingside with g4, h4 etc. thus either suffocating Black's counterplay there or creating an attack on the kingside himself. The difference with the Makagonov is that here White controls the g4-square with the bishop on e2, while there White plays h3. }
6... e5 { Black strikes in the centre with the usual move. } 7. d5
{ White closes the centre and will continue with g4 and h4.  Note that the move  7.Nf3  leads to the Gligoric Variation. }
7... Na6
{ Black develops the knight on a6 in order not to block the bishop on c8 and intends to put it on c5 to attack the pawn on e4. }
8. g4
{ White continues with his plan.  The move  8.Nf3?!  is not in line with the idea of the line and after  8...Ng4  9.Bg5  f6  10.Bh4  g5  11.Bg3  Nh6  with ...f5 next Black has great play. }
8... Nc5
{ Attacking the pawn on e4. Now White can defend it in two ways, with a pawn or with a bishop. }
9. f3 h5
{ Black undermines White's expanded kingside, using the fact that with his last move White closed the d1-h5 diagonal so there is no pressure on the h5-pawn. }
10. g5 { The most natural and main move. } 10... Nh7
{ Getting away with tempo. } 11. h4 f6
{ Black continues to put pressure on the pawn on g5 and manages to open the f-file. After the exchange of pawns the pawn on h4 will also become vulnerable. Now White has a choice, to exchange on f6 or to allow Black to take on g5. }
12. gxf6 Bxf6 { Black attacks the pawn on h4 so White's next move is forced. }
13. Bf2 { The only way to defend the pawn on h4. } 13... Be7
{ With this move Black opens the f-file and allows for ...Rf4, the typical move for Black in this line. }
14. Kd2
{ White doesn't have time for long castle as  14.Qd2  Rf4  15.O-O-O  Bxh4  wins a pawn so he liberates the e1-square for the queen in order to be able to defend the pawn on h4 three times. }
14... c6
{ Since White committed his king Black immediately opens the game on the queenside. }
15. Kc2 cxd5
{ While he still keeps the idea of ...Rf4 and attacking the pawn on f4 Black sharpens the game to the maximum by opening the game on the queenside. }
16. cxd5
{ In case of  16.Qxd5  Be6  17.Qd2  Rc8  Black has excellent play as he can open the game ever further with the pawn sacrifice ...b5. Note that if the knight on c3 leaves its place, Black has ...Nxe4 because of the pin on the f-file.   If White takes the knight  16.Bxc5  dxc5  17.exd5  then again the pawn sacrifice  17...b5!  18.Nxb5  Rb8  is very strong as it gives Black the open b-file, which means that White's king will never find peace. }
16... Bd7
{ Black finishes development and liberates the c8-square for the rook. } 17.
Rc1 { White prepares artificial castling. } 17... b5
{ Black doesn't lose time and attacks immediately. } 18. Bxc5
{ The tactical justification of Black's move is that White cannot take the pawn:  18.Nxb5?  Nxe4  and  18.Bxb5?  Nxe4  are both very good for Black. }
18... Rc8
{ A beatiful tactical idea. Thanks to the pin on the c-file Black regains the piece. }
19. Bf2
{ After  19.Ba3  Qa5  Black follows up with ...b4 and regains the piece. }
19... b4
{ Black regains the piece and opens the files against White's king on the queenside. }
20. Kb1 bxc3 21. b3 { Trying to keep it closed. } 21... Qa5
{ Black has excellent play here. His plan is to play ...Bd8-b6 and then advance his a-pawn to a4 in order to attack White's king. }
