[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. The Averbakh Variation"]
[Black "46. Averbakh Variation with 6.Bg5. White plays 8.Nf3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Be2 O-O 6. Bg5
{ This development of the bishops on e2 and g5 is characteristic for the Averbakh Variation. The idea to put the bishop on g5 is to stop Black's typical central push ...e5. }
6... c5
{ To illustrate White's idea, pushing ...e5 loses after  6...e5??  7.dxe5  dxe5  8.Qxd8  Rxd8  9.Nd5  and Black loses material because of the pin on the h4-d8 diagonal and the weakness of the pawn on c7.  Pushing the c-pawn however aims to take immediate advantage of the lack of protection of the d4-square and the weakening of the long diagonal, the b2-pawn in particular, as White's dark-squared bishop left the c1-square. }
7. d5
{ The only critical try. Taking on c5 allows the simple  7.dxc5  dxc5  when Black is very comfortable, for example,  8.Qxd8  Rxd8  9.e5  Nfd7  with ...f6 next when all Black's pieces come easily into play after Black recaptures ...Nxf6 with ...Nc6,  ...Bf5 etc.   Playing  7.Nf3  is also timid, Black can play  7...cxd4  8.Nxd4  Qa5  with good counterplay as his pieces come out naturally with ...Nc6,  ...Be6 and ...Rfc8. }
7... e6
{ Undermining White's centre and intending to open the e-file after ...exd5. }
8. Nf3 { This is the natural alternative, but after... } 8... exd5
{ Black is doing great whichever way White recaptures. } 9. cxd5
{ Or  9.exd5  h6!  10.Be3  Bf5  with ...Ne4 next with comfortable play. } 9...
h6
{ It is important to chase away the bishop to give the pinned knight freedom of movement. }
10. Be3
{ Going to h4 allows Black to obtain the pair of bishops after  10.Bh4  g5  11.Bg3  Nh5  . }
10... b5
{ The simplest and most direct move that immediately solves all problems. Black starts action on the queenside in this Modern Benoni structure and the fact that he can do so makes it a great version for him. The justification of the move lies in the line: }
11. Bxb5
{ Or  11.Nxb5  Nxe4  , which is excellent for Black, who exchanged his b-pawn for White's central e-pawn. }
11... Nxe4 { A typical tactical motif in the Benoni. } 12. Nxe4 Qa5+
{ Black regains the piece. } 13. Qd2
{ Covering with the knight is met by  13.Nc3  Bxc3  followed by ...Qxb5. }
13... Qxb5 14. Nxd6 Qxb2
{ With easy equality for Black who has active play thanks to the powerful fianchettoed bishop. }
