[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. The Averbakh Variation"]
[Black "47. Averbakh Variation with 6.Bg5. White plays 8.Qd2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Be2 O-O 6. Bg5
{ This development of the bishops on e2 and g5 is characteristic for the Averbakh Variation. The idea to put the bishop on g5 is to stop Black's typical central push ...e5. }
6... c5
{ To illustrate White's idea, pushing ...e5 loses after  6...e5??  7.dxe5  dxe5  8.Qxd8  Rxd8  9.Nd5  and Black loses material because of the pin on the h4-d8 diagonal and the weakness of the pawn on c7.  Pushing the c-pawn however aims to take immediate advantage of the lack of protection of the d4-square and the weakening of the long diagonal, the b2-pawn in particular, as White's dark-squared bishop left the c1-square. }
7. d5
{ The only critical try. Taking on c5 allows the simple  7.dxc5  dxc5  when Black is very comfortable, for example,  8.Qxd8  Rxd8  9.e5  Nfd7  with ...f6 next when all Black's pieces come easily into play after Black recaptures ...Nxf6 with ...Nc6,  ...Bf5 etc.   Playing  7.Nf3  is also timid, Black can play  7...cxd4  8.Nxd4  Qa5  with good counterplay as his pieces come out naturally with ...Nc6,  ...Be6 and ...Rfc8. }
7... e6
{ Undermining White's centre and intending to open the e-file after ...exd5. }
8. Qd2
{ This is the main move and the reason why for many years Black's last move was considered imprecise because White stops ...h6. However, modern theory and practice have shown that Black can play ...h6 at a later stage with a powerful effect. }
8... exd5 { Black follows his plan and opens the e-file. } 9. exd5
{ Taking with the other pawn is worse as it gives White a problematic Modern Benoni position. After  9.cxd5?!  Re8  White's problem is the knight on g1. He cannot easily develop it as  10.Nf3  h6!  pinpoints the weakness of the pawn on e4. After  11.Bxh6  Nxe4  Black has excellent play as he exchanged his h-pawn for White's central e-pawn.  In the symmetrical position after exd5 Black's main idea is to play ...Bf5 followed by ...Ne4,  which frees his position in general and the bishop on g7 in particular. In order to do that he first needs to get rid of the pin on the h4-d8 diagonal, hence his next move. }
9... Qb6
{ The key move that rehabilitated the line for Black. For a very long time, it was considered that White's space advantage coupled with the pin on the h4-d8 diagonal give White a stable edge, but with the queen move Black introduces strong dynamism in the position.  There are two ideas to this move: the first one is to allow for ...Bf5 and ...Ne4 @@StartBracket@@the knight is free to jump now that there is no pin@@EndBracket@@ and the second one is to put pressure on the b2-pawn. }
10. O-O-O
{ This is a sharp alternative, but the white king is not entirely safe on the queenside. Even more so, Black has a fantastic positional piece sacrifice at his disposal after: }
10... Re8
{ Black waits for Nf3 in order to play ...Bf5 and ...Ne4,  which is Black's main development idea in this structure.  Playing  10...Bf5?!  immediately is not very good as White can meet it with  11.f3! }
11. Bd3 { Preventing Black's plan. } 11... Na6
{ The knight is heading for b4 and it cannot be stopped. } 12. a3 Nb4
{ A fantastic positional sacrifice based on the long-term attack on the queenside and White's lag in development. }
13. axb4
{ White must accept the sacrifice as  13.Bb1  Qa6  exposes the pawn on c4. }
13... cxb4
{ Attacking the knight on c3 and now in order to keep it White must relinquish the bishop pair. }
14. Bxf6
{ White's problems are seen after  14.Nb1?  Ne4!  when all of a sudden White's position collapses in view of the numerous threats. After  15.Bxe4  Rxe4  16.b3  Bf5  with ideas like the simple ...Rae8 or the sacrifice ...Rxc4 followed by ...b3-b2 Black is winning.  By taking the knight on f6 White wants to place his knight on e4. }
14... Bxf6 15. Ne4 Bg7
{ Black has excellent compensation here. He has easy play on the queenside and can calmly get his pieces to play. He wants to play ...Bf5, ...Qa5, ...Rac8 or double on the e-file, push ...b5 to open the c-file while White is under pressure on the whole board. }
