[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. The Makagonov System"]
[Black "49. Makagonov System with 6.Bg5. White plays 8.d5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. h3
{ This little move is the start of the Makagonov Variation, one of the most critical tries against the KID today. The 'little' move is quite venomous: White covers the g4-square like in the Saemisch Variation, only that he doesn't take away the f3-square from his knight. Additionally, by leaving the pawn on f2 his bishop on e3 will be more stable.  The move h3 also supports the g4-advance, aimed either at limiting Black's kingside counterplay by exerting more control over the f5-square or with the idea to start an attack on the kingside, by opening the g-file by gxf5 or by advancing g4-g5 and h4-h5.  Note that White can also start with  5.Nf3  O-O  6.h3  , but that just transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/2PPP3/2N5/PP3PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.h3  O-O  6.Nf3  @@StartBracket@@seethis line@@EndBracket@@. }
5... O-O
{ Black completes his kingside development. Now White has a choice to make - whether to develop the dark-squared bishop @@StartBracket@@to g5 or e3@@EndBracket@@ or to develop the knight to f3, keeping both possibilities for the dark-squared bishop @@StartBracket@@g5 or e3@@EndBracket@@ available.  Against all of these Black needs to decide in which direction he would like the game to proceed. He has three options: to go for the typical KID positions after executing ...e5, to aim for Modern Benoni positions with ...c5 or to give the game an original character with some alternative ideas. In this repertoire, we will go for the third option. }
6. Bg5
{ By putting the bishop on g5 White wishes to provoke ...h6 and only then to drop back to e3. He will regain the tempo later with Qd2, hitting the pawn on h6 and will claim to have managed to weaken Black's kingside. The bishop on g5 also prevents Black's immediate ...e5, similar to the Averbakh Variation. }
6... a6
{ In this version the move  6...Nc6?!  doesn't work and it's important to understand why. After  7.Nf3  Black needs to chase away the bishop from g5 if he is to push ...e5 because the immediate  7...e5?  loses to  8.dxe5  dxe5  9.Qxd8  Nxd8  10.Bxf6  Bxf6  11.Nd5  winning a pawn thanks to the attack on the bishop on f6 and the pawn on c7.   Hence, Black needs to chase away the bishop and after @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/2np1np1/6B1/2PPP3/2N2N1P/PP3PP1/R2QKB1R b KQ - 4 7@@EndFEN@@  7...h6  8.Be3  he is a tempo up compared to the line @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/2PPP3/2N4P/PP3PP1/R1BQKBNR w KQ - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Be3  Nc6  7.Nf3  @@StartBracket@@seethis line@@EndBracket@@. But here we have the rare case where this extra tempo turns out to be a negative tempo that hurts Black's position:  After @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp1ppb1/2np1npp/8/2PPP3/2N1BN1P/PP3PP1/R2QKB1R b KQ - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8...e5  9.d5  Nd4  10.Nxd4  exd4  @@StartBracket@@so far everything is the same as inthis line with 6.Be3 Nc6@@EndBracket@@  11.Qxd4!  Ng4  and now White has the stunning queen sacrifice  12.hxg4!!  Bxd4  13.Bxd4  and thanks to the weakness of the h6-pawn @@StartBracket@@here we see why the extra tempo is a negative one as the pawn is under attack@@EndBracket@@ the threat of Rxh6 is difficult to parry, which coupled with the powerful bishop and the impregnable pawn structure gives White a solid advantage. This assessment was confirmed in the game Predke-Yakubboev from the Grand Swiss event in Riga 2021.  Now that we've seen why the idea with ...Nc6 and ...e5 doesn't work, we understand why Black employs a different plan: with the move of the a-pawn Black prepares a flank attack on White's centre in Benko Gambit style by intending ...c5 and when White pushes d5 he will follow up with ...b5. }
7. Nf3
{ White develops normally. Against all other moves Black continues with ...c5 and after d5 he continues with ...b5,  for example  7.Qd2  c5  8.d5  b5  9.cxb5  Qa5  with typical Benko Gambit style play on the queenside after ...Nbd7,  ...Bxa6 @@StartBracket@@if White takes bxa6@@EndBracket@@, ...Rfb8 etc.   Note that if White insists on preventing Black's idea of ...c5 followed by ...b5 and plays  7.a4?!  this weakens the b4-square and Black can safely transpose to the usual KID positions after  7...a5  followed by ...Na6 and ...e5 when White's hole on b4 makes it impossible for him to create play on the queenside and it gives Black's knights wonderful squares on c5 and b4. }
7... c5
{ Black continues with his plan. White has principally 3 choices here: to capture on c5, to push d5 or to let Black take on d4. }
8. d5
{ This allows Black's main idea of initiating queenside play after ...b5. }
8... b5 { Black executes his main idea. } 9. Bd3
{ White is better advised not to touch the pawn on  b5  as  9.cxb5?!  axb5  10.Bxb5?  Nxe4!  is a tactical trick that wrecks White's position, the point being that  11.Nxe4  Qa5  12.Nc3  Bxc3  13.bxc3  Qxb5  regains the piece with a winning position for Black. }
9... h6
{ Black wants to get rid of the pin on the h4-d8 diagonal before undermining White's centre with ...e6. }
10. Be3
{ If White insists on keeping the bishop on the h4-d8 diagonal after  10.Bh4  then Black is flexible enough to change his plan and instead of undermining the centre with ...e6 he can start play on the queenside after  10...Nbd7  11.O-O  Rb8  with the idea of ...bxc4. }
10... e6 { Black undermines White's centre. } 11. Qd2
{ White wants to gain tempo against Black's pawn on h6.  In case of  11.O-O  exd5  12.Nxd5  Nbd7  Black has comfortable play similar to the one after 11.Qd2. }
11... exd5 { Forcing White to decide which structure he prefers. } 12. Nxd5
{ In case of  12.cxd5  b4  13.Ne2  Kh7  Black has a good game as his queenside majority is quite advanced. He will continue with ...a5 and ...Ba6 to exchange his light-squared bishop and will seek the further advance of his queenside pawns.   After  12.exd5  bxc4  13.Bxc4  Kh7  with ...Bf5 and ...Nbd7 coming Black has smooth development and easy play along the b- and e-files and can target the d5-pawn after ...Nb6. }
12... Nbd7
{ Black is in no rush to take on d5 as he can do that on the next move, so he develops the knight from b8 first. Now he also threatens to take on c4 and then if White recaptures with the bishop the pawn on e4 falls @@StartBracket@@the immediate  12...bxc4  is met by the zwischenschach  13.Nxf6  , thus defending the pawn on e4 - with a black knight on d7 Black can recapture on f6 with a knight and continue attacking the pawn on e4@@EndBracket@@.  The tactical justification of the move is seen after White takes the pawn on h6: }
13. Bxh6 bxc4
{ The bishop on d3 cannot control both e4 and c4 at the same time. } 14. Bxg7
Kxg7 15. Bxc4 Nxe4 { Black regains the pawn and after... } 16. Qc2 Nef6
{ Black has very good play as his pieces come into play after ...Re8, ...Bb7 when he will seek to get rid of the blockade on d5 and advance his central pawns. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. The Makagonov System"]
[Black "50. Makagonov System with 6.Bg5. White plays 8.Be2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. h3
{ This little move is the start of the Makagonov Variation, one of the most critical tries against the KID today. The 'little' move is quite venomous: White covers the g4-square like in the Saemisch Variation, only that he doesn't take away the f3-square from his knight. Additionally, by leaving the pawn on f2 his bishop on e3 will be more stable.  The move h3 also supports the g4-advance, aimed either at limiting Black's kingside counterplay by exerting more control over the f5-square or with the idea to start an attack on the kingside, by opening the g-file by gxf5 or by advancing g4-g5 and h4-h5.  Note that White can also start with  5.Nf3  O-O  6.h3  , but that just transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/2PPP3/2N5/PP3PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.h3  O-O  6.Nf3  @@StartBracket@@seethis line@@EndBracket@@. }
5... O-O
{ Black completes his kingside development. Now White has a choice to make - whether to develop the dark-squared bishop @@StartBracket@@to g5 or e3@@EndBracket@@ or to develop the knight to f3, keeping both possibilities for the dark-squared bishop @@StartBracket@@g5 or e3@@EndBracket@@ available.  Against all of these Black needs to decide in which direction he would like the game to proceed. He has three options: to go for the typical KID positions after executing ...e5, to aim for Modern Benoni positions with ...c5 or to give the game an original character with some alternative ideas. In this repertoire, we will go for the third option. }
6. Bg5
{ By putting the bishop on g5 White wishes to provoke ...h6 and only then to drop back to e3. He will regain the tempo later with Qd2, hitting the pawn on h6 and will claim to have managed to weaken Black's kingside. The bishop on g5 also prevents Black's immediate ...e5, similar to the Averbakh Variation. }
6... a6
{ In this version the move  6...Nc6?!  doesn't work and it's important to understand why. After  7.Nf3  Black needs to chase away the bishop from g5 if he is to push ...e5 because the immediate  7...e5?  loses to  8.dxe5  dxe5  9.Qxd8  Nxd8  10.Bxf6  Bxf6  11.Nd5  winning a pawn thanks to the attack on the bishop on f6 and the pawn on c7.   Hence, Black needs to chase away the bishop and after @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/2np1np1/6B1/2PPP3/2N2N1P/PP3PP1/R2QKB1R b KQ - 4 7@@EndFEN@@  7...h6  8.Be3  he is a tempo up compared to the line @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/2PPP3/2N4P/PP3PP1/R1BQKBNR w KQ - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Be3  Nc6  7.Nf3  @@StartBracket@@seethis line@@EndBracket@@. But here we have the rare case where this extra tempo turns out to be a negative tempo that hurts Black's position:  After @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp1ppb1/2np1npp/8/2PPP3/2N1BN1P/PP3PP1/R2QKB1R b KQ - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8...e5  9.d5  Nd4  10.Nxd4  exd4  @@StartBracket@@so far everything is the same as inthis line with 6.Be3 Nc6@@EndBracket@@  11.Qxd4!  Ng4  and now White has the stunning queen sacrifice  12.hxg4!!  Bxd4  13.Bxd4  and thanks to the weakness of the h6-pawn @@StartBracket@@here we see why the extra tempo is a negative one as the pawn is under attack@@EndBracket@@ the threat of Rxh6 is difficult to parry, which coupled with the powerful bishop and the impregnable pawn structure gives White a solid advantage. This assessment was confirmed in the game Predke-Yakubboev from the Grand Swiss event in Riga 2021.  Now that we've seen why the idea with ...Nc6 and ...e5 doesn't work, we understand why Black employs a different plan: with the move of the a-pawn Black prepares a flank attack on White's centre in Benko Gambit style by intending ...c5 and when White pushes d5 he will follow up with ...b5. }
7. Nf3
{ White develops normally. Against all other moves Black continues with ...c5 and after d5 he continues with ...b5,  for example  7.Qd2  c5  8.d5  b5  9.cxb5  Qa5  with typical Benko Gambit style play on the queenside after ...Nbd7,  ...Bxa6 @@StartBracket@@if White takes bxa6@@EndBracket@@, ...Rfb8 etc.   Note that if White insists on preventing Black's idea of ...c5 followed by ...b5 and plays  7.a4?!  this weakens the b4-square and Black can safely transpose to the usual KID positions after  7...a5  followed by ...Na6 and ...e5 when White's hole on b4 makes it impossible for him to create play on the queenside and it gives Black's knights wonderful squares on c5 and b4. }
7... c5
{ Black continues with his plan. White has principally 3 choices here: to capture on c5, to push d5 or to let Black take on d4. }
8. Be2 { White allows the exchange on d4. } 8... cxd4
{ Black takes on d4 and now the structure is the one from the Maroczy Bind in the Sicilian Defence but one that is favourable for Black because of two factors:  First, the pawn on h3 is one White would want to have on h2 in these structures because after the desirable f3 @@StartBracket@@to strengthen the pawn on e4@@EndBracket@@ White creates dark-square weaknesses on g3 and f4  Second, the bishop on g5 is out of place, it would rather be on e3 to keep control over the important d4-square - this means that White will likely lose tempo to play Be3. }
9. Nxd4 Nc6
{ Black develops normally. His ideal is to exchange the dark-squared bishops and queens and obtain control over the dark squares for example by playing ...e5 and ...Nd4.  Then the difference in the usefulness of the light-squared bishops will be apparent - Black will be able to play ...Bxd5, eliminating the white knight from the dominating d5-square, while White won't be able to touch the knight on d4 because it will be on a dark square. }
10. O-O
{ White continues development. The natural  10.Be3  is met by  10...Nxd4  11.Bxd4  Bh6!  threatening ...e5 when Black manages to achieve his aim to exchange the dark-squared bishops as the bishop on d4 will have to drop back to e3.  For example,  12.Qd3  e5  13.Be3  Bxe3  14.Qxe3  Be6  with an excellent position for Black who has the better long-term prospects thanks to the weakness of the d4 and f4 squares.   In case of @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/1p2pp1p/p2p1npb/8/2PBP3/2N4P/PP2BPP1/R2QK2R w KQ - 1 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Bxf6  exf6  followed by ...f5 Black opens the game for his pair of bishops, which gives him ample play. }
10... Nxd4
{ Black forces the white queen to d4 from where she will need to move again, thus gaining tempo for development. }
11. Qxd4 Be6
{ Developing the bishop and threatening ...Nd5, thus forcing the white queen to move from the central position. }
12. Qe3 Rc8
{ Black continues to develop with tempo, attacking the pawn on c4. } 13. Nd5
{ In case of  13.b3  Qa5  with ...b5 next, Black has excellent play on the queenside. }
13... Bxd5
{ The most direct, Black doesn't lose time and executes the ...b5 push. He can also prepare with  13...Re8  for example, which is a good alternative. }
14. exd5 { Taking  14.cxd5  allows  14...Rc2  . } 14... b5
{ Black has excellent play here with his compact position and activity on the queenside. He wants to take on c4, continue with ...Qa5 and open the long diagonal for his bishop. }
