1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. h3
{ This little move is the start of the Makagonov Variation, one of the most critical tries against the KID today. The 'little' move is quite venomous: White covers the g4-square like in the Saemisch Variation, only that he doesn't take away the f3-square from his knight. Additionally, by leaving the pawn on f2 his bishop on e3 will be more stable.  The move h3 also supports the g4-advance, aimed either at limiting Black's kingside counterplay by exerting more control over the f5-square or with the idea to start an attack on the kingside, by opening the g-file by gxf5 or by advancing g4-g5 and h4-h5.  Note that White can also start with  5.Nf3  O-O  6.h3  , but that just transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/2PPP3/2N5/PP3PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.h3  O-O  6.Nf3  @@StartBracket@@seethis line@@EndBracket@@. }
