6. Bg5
{ By putting the bishop on g5 White wishes to provoke ...h6 and only then to drop back to e3. He will regain the tempo later with Qd2, hitting the pawn on h6 and will claim to have managed to weaken Black's kingside. The bishop on g5 also prevents Black's immediate ...e5, similar to the Averbakh Variation. }
6... a6
{ In this version the move  6...Nc6?!  doesn't work and it's important to understand why. After  7.Nf3  Black needs to chase away the bishop from g5 if he is to push ...e5 because the immediate  7...e5?  loses to  8.dxe5  dxe5  9.Qxd8  Nxd8  10.Bxf6  Bxf6  11.Nd5  winning a pawn thanks to the attack on the bishop on f6 and the pawn on c7.   Hence, Black needs to chase away the bishop and after @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/2np1np1/6B1/2PPP3/2N2N1P/PP3PP1/R2QKB1R b KQ - 4 7@@EndFEN@@  7...h6  8.Be3  he is a tempo up compared to the line @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/2PPP3/2N4P/PP3PP1/R1BQKBNR w KQ - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Be3  Nc6  7.Nf3  @@StartBracket@@seethis line@@EndBracket@@. But here we have the rare case where this extra tempo turns out to be a negative tempo that hurts Black's position:  After @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp1ppb1/2np1npp/8/2PPP3/2N1BN1P/PP3PP1/R2QKB1R b KQ - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8...e5  9.d5  Nd4  10.Nxd4  exd4  @@StartBracket@@so far everything is the same as inthis line with 6.Be3 Nc6@@EndBracket@@  11.Qxd4!  Ng4  and now White has the stunning queen sacrifice  12.hxg4!!  Bxd4  13.Bxd4  and thanks to the weakness of the h6-pawn @@StartBracket@@here we see why the extra tempo is a negative one as the pawn is under attack@@EndBracket@@ the threat of Rxh6 is difficult to parry, which coupled with the powerful bishop and the impregnable pawn structure gives White a solid advantage. This assessment was confirmed in the game Predke-Yakubboev from the Grand Swiss event in Riga 2021.  Now that we've seen why the idea with ...Nc6 and ...e5 doesn't work, we understand why Black employs a different plan: with the move of the a-pawn Black prepares a flank attack on White's centre in Benko Gambit style by intending ...c5 and when White pushes d5 he will follow up with ...b5. }
7. Nf3
{ White develops normally. Against all other moves Black continues with ...c5 and after d5 he continues with ...b5,  for example  7.Qd2  c5  8.d5  b5  9.cxb5  Qa5  with typical Benko Gambit style play on the queenside after ...Nbd7,  ...Bxa6 @@StartBracket@@if White takes bxa6@@EndBracket@@, ...Rfb8 etc.   Note that if White insists on preventing Black's idea of ...c5 followed by ...b5 and plays  7.a4?!  this weakens the b4-square and Black can safely transpose to the usual KID positions after  7...a5  followed by ...Na6 and ...e5 when White's hole on b4 makes it impossible for him to create play on the queenside and it gives Black's knights wonderful squares on c5 and b4. }
7... c5
{ Black continues with his plan. White has principally 3 choices here: to capture on c5, to push d5 or to let Black take on d4. }
8. dxc5
{ This move was Aronian's choice against Radjabov in the Candidates tournament in London 2013. }
8... dxc5
{ This is simpler and better than Radjabov's  8...Qa5  because the endgame is pleasant for Black while the middlegame less so, as the afore-mentioned game Aronian-Radjabov showed. }
9. Qxd8
{ In case of  9.Be2  Qxd1  10.Rxd1  Nc6  Black has a comfortable endgame mostly because of his easy development and better pawn structure - White has a hole on d4 that Black can try to use by placing a piece there. }
9... Rxd8 10. e5
{ Otherwise Black develops with ...Nc6-d4, using the hole on d4. } 10... Nfd7
{ Black attacks the advanced pawn on e5. } 11. O-O-O
{ White develops and pins the knight on d7,  thus indirectly defending the pawn on e5.  In case of  11.Bxe7  Re8  Black regains the pawn by taking on e5 next.   11.Nd5  is met by  11...Nc6  , developing and hitting one more time the pawn on e5. }
11... Nc6
{ A natural, multi-purpose, developing move - the knight defends the rook on d8, so that the knight on d7 can move, it defends the pawn on e7 and it attacks the pawn on e5. }
12. Be2 { White finishes development. } 12... Ndxe5
{ This is the simplest. If Black wants to keep more tension in the position he has the good alternative  12...Ra7!?  , a mysterious rook move with the idea to defend the 7th rank after a subsequent ...b6. Then Black can consolidate with ...Kf8 or ...Re8 to cover the pawn on e7 and concentrate on the attack on the pawn on e5.   Another idea is  12...h6  13.Bf4  g5  14.Bg3  Nb6  again with a complex endgame ahead. }
13. Rxd8+ Nxd8 { Black's moves are forced. } 14. Nxe5 Bxe5 15. Bxe7 Bf5
{ Black finishes development and intends ...Ne6 next. } 16. Bxc5
{ It's critical to see what happens if White takes the pawn as otherwise Black plays ...Ne6 with easy play. }
16... Ne6 { Black improves the position of his knight with tempo. } 17. Be3 Nf4
{ Black has excellent activity for the pawn. He will either regain it or White will be forced to give up one of his bishops for the knight, giving Black the pair of bishops as compensation for the pawn. For example after... }
18. Bf1 Re8
{ ... followed by ...Nd3 Black will obtain the pair of bishops and will threaten the pawn on c4 after White takes the knight and he recaptures with ...Bxd3. }
