[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. h3
{ This little move is the start of the Makagonov Variation, one of the most critical tries against the KID today. The 'little' move is quite venomous: White covers the g4-square like in the Saemisch Variation, only that he doesn't take away the f3-square from his knight. Additionally, by leaving the pawn on f2 his bishop on e3 will be more stable.  The move h3 also supports the g4-advance, aimed either at limiting Black's kingside counterplay by exerting more control over the f5-square or with the idea to start an attack on the kingside, by opening the g-file by gxf5 or by advancing g4-g5 and h4-h5.  Note that White can also start with  5.Nf3  O-O  6.h3  , but that just transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/2PPP3/2N5/PP3PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.h3  O-O  6.Nf3  @@StartBracket@@seethis line@@EndBracket@@. }
5... O-O
{ Black completes his kingside development. Now White has a choice to make - whether to develop the dark-squared bishop @@StartBracket@@to g5 or e3@@EndBracket@@ or to develop the knight to f3, keeping both possibilities for the dark-squared bishop @@StartBracket@@g5 or e3@@EndBracket@@ available.  Against all of these Black needs to decide in which direction he would like the game to proceed. He has three options: to go for the typical KID positions after executing ...e5, to aim for Modern Benoni positions with ...c5 or to give the game an original character with some alternative ideas. In this repertoire, we will go for the third option. }
6. Be3
{ With this move White keeps flexibility with the knight from g1, in some lines it can come to e2. }
6... Nc6 { Black wants to play ...e5 and after d5 to jump to d4. } 7. Nf3
{ This is a natural move, but it doesn't prevent Black's plan. } 7... e5
{ Attacking White's centre. } 8. d5 Nd4
{ Black executes his principal idea thanks to the tactics based on the strength of his dark-squared bishop and the opening of the e-file. }
9. Nxd4 { White cannot tolerate the centralised knight. } 9... exd4 10. Bxd4
{ In case of  10.Qxd4  Ng4!  11.Qd2  Nxe3  12.Qxe3  f5  Black has excellent compensation for the pawn in view of his control over the dark squares and the upcoming opening of the position.  Keep this idea in mind when revisingthe analogous line after 6.Bg5, which doesn't work for Black @@StartBracket@@and hence the reason for choosing 6...a6 as a preferred choice@@EndBracket@@. }
10... Nxe4 { Thanks to this tactical shot Black regains the pawn. } 11. Nxe4
{ In case of  11.Bxg7  Re8!  threatening discovered check Black captures the bishop on g7 on the next move with an easy game. }
11... Qh4
{ White's loose pieces in the centre are under tremendous pressure and Black easily regains material. }
12. Bxg7
{ A move like  12.g4  doesn't change much after  12...Re8  13.Bg2  Bf5  the pins on the e-file and the 4th rank ensure Black gets the material back. }
12... Qxe4+ { Taking one piece back with check. } 13. Qe2 Qxe2+ 14. Bxe2 Kxg7
{ Regaining the other piece. The endgame is problem-free for Black, who can even claim he has the better bishop as White's is limited by his pawns on light squares @@StartBracket@@c4 and d5@@EndBracket@@.  Black will quickly take control over the e-file and if White is not careful a king march along f6-e5-d4 can become a problem. }
