{ The e5-square is available so Black puts the knight in the centre, at the same time provoking White to overextend. }
8. f4
{ White accepts the challenge. Slower development with  8.Be2  e6  9.Nf3  Nxf3  10.Bxf3  Nd7  is fine for Black as he has ideas to close the centre with ...e5 and obtain a good typical KID position or stay flexible and keep the long diagonal open for the time being and play ...a5,  ...Nc5 first.   Note that in case of  8.g4  c6  9.f4  Ned7  we have a transposition...   ... to the lines after  8.f4  Ned7  9.g4  c6  @@StartBracket@@seethis line@@EndBracket@@. }
8... Ned7
{ The only square available for the knight. Now Black wants to attack White's centre either with the e-pawn @@StartBracket@@playing ...e6 or ...e5@@EndBracket@@ or the c-pawn @@StartBracket@@playing ...c6@@EndBracket@@. }
9. g4
{ In fact, this is a prophylactic move against Black's ...e5, which can now be met by f5. }
9... c6
{ Since now  9...e5?  be met by  10.f5  Black attacks the centre using the c-pawn. }
10. Nf3 cxd5 { Opening the c-file. } 11. cxd5 b6
{ Black prepares the development of his light-squared bishop to b7 or a6. } 12.
Nd4
{ White immediately targets the weakened c6-square. Slower play allows Black to finish development and attack White's centre, for example,  12.Bg2  Nc5  13.Qc2  Bb7  with further ideas like ...Rc8 and ...e6. }
12... Nc5
{ Black attacks the pawn on e4. His counterplay is based on the fact that White's king is still stuck in the centre and that White lags behind in development. }
13. Nc6
{ This is better than  13.Qf3?!  which was played in the game Caruana-Firouzja at the Wijk aan Zee tournament in 2020. Now a big improvement over Firouzja's play is  13...e6!  , immediately undermining White's centre.  A typical idea for Black in this line is seen after  14.dxe6  Nfxe4!  that destroys White's centre thanks to the open long diagonal after  15.Nxe4  Bb7  , which regains the piece and leaves Black with a winning position. }
13... Qe8
{ The queen is not in the way on e8 @@StartBracket@@for example on c7 she can be attacked after Nb5@@EndBracket@@ and can be useful in case the e-file is opened. }
14. Bg2 { White defends the pawn on e4. } 14... Ba6
{ Black keeps the white king in the centre and threatens ...Nd3. } 15. Bxc5
{ Getting rid of the knight, thus preventing ...Nd3, but now Black obtains the pair of bishops with his unopposed dark-squared bishop potentially becoming a very dangerous piece. }
15... bxc5 { Taking towards the centre and opening the b-file. } 16. Qd2 Nd7
{ A multi-purpose move: Black opens the long diagonal for the dark-squared bishop and wants to play ...c4, ...Nc5-d3.  Another idea for Black is the exchange sacrifice ...Rb8, which gets rid of the knight on c6 and joins a rook in the attack along the b-file. The middlegame is very complicated but Black has good chances with these constructive ideas in mind. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. The Makagonov System"]
[Black "55. Makagonov System with 6.Nf3. White plays 8.a3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. h3
{ This little move is the start of the Makagonov Variation, one of the most critical tries against the KID today. The 'little' move is quite venomous: White covers the g4-square like in the Saemisch Variation, only that he doesn't take away the f3-square from his knight. Additionally, by leaving the pawn on f2 his bishop on e3 will be more stable.  The move h3 also supports the g4-advance, aimed either at limiting Black's kingside counterplay by exerting more control over the f5-square or with the idea to start an attack on the kingside, by opening the g-file by gxf5 or by advancing g4-g5 and h4-h5.  Note that White can also start with  5.Nf3  O-O  6.h3  , but that just transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/2PPP3/2N5/PP3PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.h3  O-O  6.Nf3  @@StartBracket@@seethis line@@EndBracket@@. }
5... O-O
{ Black completes his kingside development. Now White has a choice to make - whether to develop the dark-squared bishop @@StartBracket@@to g5 or e3@@EndBracket@@ or to develop the knight to f3, keeping both possibilities for the dark-squared bishop @@StartBracket@@g5 or e3@@EndBracket@@ available.  Against all of these Black needs to decide in which direction he would like the game to proceed. He has three options: to go for the typical KID positions after executing ...e5, to aim for Modern Benoni positions with ...c5 or to give the game an original character with some alternative ideas. In this repertoire, we will go for the third option. }
6. Nf3
{ White develops the knight on its natural square from where it covers the d4-square and controls the e5-square. }
6... Nc6
{ Black fights for the central d4-square and threatens ...e5,  thus forcing White's next move. This move takes the game into less explored territory compared to the more common  6...e5  or  6...c5  . }
7. d5
{ Practically forced. Otherwise Black plays ...e5 and ...Nd4,  for example  7.Be3?!  e5  8.d5  Nd4  is great for Black and it's a transposition to the line @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/2PPP3/2N4P/PP3PP1/R1BQKBNR w KQ - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Be3  Nc6  7.Nf3?!  e5  8.d5  Nd4  @@StartBracket@@seethis line@@EndBracket@@. }
7... Nb4
{ Unlikethe line with 6.Be3 here the knight on f3 controls the e5-square so Black's knight has to go to b4. }
8. a3
{ This is a natural reaction as White doesn't want to tolerate a piece on his own part of the board, but this helps Black re-route the knight to the desired c5-square. }
8... Na6 9. Bd3
{ White uses the fact that the knight no longer controls the d3 and c2 squares and places the bishop on the b1-h7 diagonal. }
9... Nd7
{ Black's play in this line is very flexible. He opens the long diagonal for his bishop and keeps his options open. Now either knight can come to c5 and Black can undermine White's centre from both sides, with ...e6 or ...c6. }
10. O-O Nac5
{ Getting the knight from the rim back into play.  Black has an interesting alternative in  10...Bxc3!?  11.bxc3  Nac5  12.Bc2  e5  , where Black wants to obtain a great KID position without his limited bishop on g7 and with White's wrecked queenside structure.  Therefore White is forced to take en passant, so after  13.dxe6  Nxe6  we have a complex middlegame with chances for both sides - White hopes to use his unopposed dark-squared bishop while Black plays on the strong e5 and c5 squares for his knights and White's wrecked queenside structure. }
11. Bc2
{ Avoiding the exchange, which would give Black the pair of bishops for nothing. }
11... a5 { Black stabilises the knight on c5 by preventing b4. } 12. Be3 e6
{ Black undermines the centre and will seek a good moment to take on d5 and open the e-file. The move also introduces the positional threat of ...Bxc3 followed by ...e5,  when White won't have the option to take en passant.  Taking on c3 immediately is possible, though after  12...Bxc3  13.bxc3  e5  14.dxe6!  Nxe6  15.Nd4  followed by Nb5 White manages to relocate his knight to an active position on b5. This is what Black wants to avoid by playing ...e6 first. }
13. Bg5
{ In case of a neutral move like  13.Re1  Black executes his idea with  13...Bxc3  14.bxc3  e5  with an excellent position.   After  13.Qd2  @@StartBracket@@threatening b4 since now the knight on c3 is defended@@EndBracket@@  13...a4!  @@StartBracket@@preventing b4@@EndBracket@@  14.Rad1  e5  Black again has a promising KID position where he managed to stop White's queenside expansion.   An exchange on e6 is harmless:  13.dxe6  Nxe6  gives Black excellent squares for his knights on e5 and c5. }
13... Bf6
{ It is also possible to play  13...Qe8  , keeping the bishops, but by exchanging them Black is more ambitious positionally because he wants to obtain a closed KID position without the dark-squared bishops after playing ...e5 and closing the centre. }
14. Bxf6
{ After  14.Bh6  Re8  Black still has the idea to take on c3 and push ...e5. }
14... Qxf6
{ With the dark-squared bishops exchanged Black now wants to push ...e5 and obtain the closed centre KID structure with his better light-squared bishop and without his limited dark-squared bishop. }
15. Nb5
{ White uses the absence of the queen from d8 to put the knight on an attacking position and target the pawn on c7. }
15... Na6
{ The knight returns to a6 to defend the pawn on c7. With the pawn on c7 protected now White's pawn on b2 is hanging. }
16. Rb1 { Defending the pawn and threatening b4. } 16... e5
{ Black closes the centre and obtains the favourable structure. } 17. b4
{ In this now typical KID structure both sides have their clear sides for an attack - White on the queenside and Black on the kingside. However, Black has quite a few pieces on the queenside and he can also successfully limit White's activity there, while at the same time pursuing his own play on the kingside. }
17... Qe7
{ A multi-purpose move. Black opens the path for the f-pawn in order to execute ...f5, liberates the f6-square for the activation of the knight from d7 via f6 and h5 to f4 and bolsters his control over the c5-square. }
18. Qd2
{ Taking on a5 is never a worry for Black as that gives him eternal control over the c5-square, which effectively stops White's queenside play. }
18... Nf6
{ With ...Nh5-f4 and ...f5 to come Black has very good counterchances on the kingside while his position on the queenside remains solid. }
