{ A precise move. First, let's see White's indirect defence:  14...exd5  15.cxd5!  Nxe4??  @@StartBracket@@the move 15...c6 is better, with rather unclear play@@EndBracket@@  16.Nxe4  attacks the knight on b4.   Since taking on d5,  while possible, doesn't force exd5,  Black finishes development and keeps his options open. One idea of the development of the bishop is seen after the immediate  14...e5  15.Ndb5  and now Black cannot move the bishop from c8 as  15...Bd7?  @@StartBracket@@it's better to play 15...Rf8 with ...f5 next with a double-edged position@@EndBracket@@ allows  16.Bxc5!  dxc5  17.a3  Na6  18.Nxa4  winning a pawn.   Black has another interesting alternative to the bishop move, for example,  14...a3!?  15.bxa3  Nba6  with ...e5 next when the pawn sacrifice made it difficult for White to create play on the queenside as he cannot use his pawns to break open the play there.   The move  14...c6!?  is also interesting, initiating play in the centre. }
15. dxe6
{ Black was ready for ...e5 so White changes the structure in the centre.  Alternatively  15.Rad1  e5  16.Ndb5  Nba6  with ...f5-f4 next gives Black typical KID play on the kingside. }
15... fxe6
{ Keeping control over the d5-square.  A good alternative is  15...Nxe6  16.Nxe6  Bxe6  17.Rad1  Qf6!?  @@StartBracket@@preventing Nd5 because the pawn on b2 hangs in that case@@EndBracket@@ with a complex middlegame position. }
16. Ndb5
{ The knight cannot be chased away from b5 by ...c6 as that would weaken the d6-pawn.  In case of  16.Bg5  Bf6  17.Bxf6  Qxf6  the exchange of the dark-squared bishops is good for Black who can then continue with ...e5,  placing his pawns on dark squares and intending to use the d4 and f4 squares after ...Ne6. }
16... Bc6
{ Activating the bishop and exerting pressure on the e4-pawn. Black cannot take it for the time being in view of the attack on the knight on b4 after Nxe4, but White must always keep this attack in mind. }
17. Bg5
{ After  17.f3  Qe7  the middlegame is very complex, Black's plan is to play ...Red8 and push ...d5,  opening up the game and eliminating White's space advantage by exchanging the pawns on e4 and c4. }
17... Qd7 { From here the queen can come to the f-file with ...Qf7. } 18. f4
{ White takes up more central space, but Black is very solid. } 18... Rf8
{ Activating the rook on the f-file. A complicated middlegame lies ahead for both sides.  Black's idea here is to remove the knight from b4 to a6, thus attacking the pawn on e4, and to push ...e5 with the idea to exchange White's pawn on f4 and isolate the pawn on e4. In this way he will obtain the excellent blockading square on e5 which will give him good play. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6. The Fianchetto Variation"]
[Black "59. Fianchetto Variation with 7.e4. White plays 8.d5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nf3
{ If White wishes to play the Fianchetto Variation he can also start with  3.g3  , but the game will transpose after  3...Bg7  4.Nf3  O-O  . }
3... Bg7 4. g3 O-O 5. Bg2 d6 { Black plays the usual KID moves. } 6. Nc3
{ White can also start with  6.O-O  c6  7.Nc3  , but this move gives him an additional possibility on the next move. }
6... c6
{ A very flexible move for Black. First of all, he shuts the long diagonal for White's fianchettoed bishop. He also keeps his options open:    He can play ...e5, ...d5 or even ...c5.  He prepares a possible ...b5.  He can develop his knight from b8 to d7 or a6.  The pawn move also opens the a5-d8 diagonal for the queen, giving her access to the b6 and a5 squares. }
7. e4
{ This is an alternative that only recently started to receive attention thanks to the success Black had after  7.O-O  Bf5  .  White is not against transposition to other lines of the Fianchetto Variation, but he does prevent the development of Black's light-squared bishop to f5. }
7... Be6
{ This provocative move was a result of deep preparation! One of America's best young players, GM Jeffery Xiong played this move when facing another prodigy, the German GM Vincent Keymer at the Grand Swiss event in Riga 2021. Since Keymer had played the move 7.e4 before, Xiong could prepare deeply against it and he produced a really great idea that offers Black excellent chances. }
8. d5
{ This is a natural move, but it weakens the dark squares in the centre @@StartBracket@@c5 and e5 in particular@@EndBracket@@ that Black can use to create counterplay. }
8... Bg4
{ Black fights for the dark squares by pinning @@StartBracket@@or just eliminating@@EndBracket@@ the knight on f3 that controls the e5 and d4-squares.  Since Black can take on d5 at any moment, for the time being he keeps the tension because White cannot really take on c6 as  9.dxc6  9...Nxc6  gives Black a huge lead in development. }
9. h3
{ Sooner or later this is forced as the pin is unpleasant for White.  For example, in case of  9.O-O  Nbd7  10.h3  Bxf3  11.Qxf3  cxd5  12.cxd5  Qa5  we have a transposition to the lines after 9.h3. }
9... Bxf3 { Black gladly exchanges the knight on f3. } 10. Qxf3 Nbd7
{ And after the exchange immediately targets the dark squares in the centre. }
11. O-O cxd5
{ Having finished the development of the light pieces with this exchange Black opens the c-file for one of his rooks. }
12. cxd5
{ Taking with the other pawn leaves the pawn on c4 vulnerable after  12.exd5  Rc8  ...   ... while taking with the knight only opens the long diagonal for Black after  12.Nxd5  Nxd5  13.cxd5  Qb6  . }
12... Qa5
{ Black develops the queen and liberates the path for the king's rook to c8. He intends to play ...Rfc8, ...Ne5-c4, ...b5-b4 @@StartBracket@@if allowed@@EndBracket@@ and create play on the queenside. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6. The Fianchetto Variation"]
[Black "60. Fianchetto Variation with 7.e4. White plays 8.Qe2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nf3
{ If White wishes to play the Fianchetto Variation he can also start with  3.g3  , but the game will transpose after  3...Bg7  4.Nf3  O-O  . }
3... Bg7 4. g3 O-O 5. Bg2 d6 { Black plays the usual KID moves. } 6. Nc3
{ White can also start with  6.O-O  c6  7.Nc3  , but this move gives him an additional possibility on the next move. }
6... c6
{ A very flexible move for Black. First of all, he shuts the long diagonal for White's fianchettoed bishop. He also keeps his options open:    He can play ...e5, ...d5 or even ...c5.  He prepares a possible ...b5.  He can develop his knight from b8 to d7 or a6.  The pawn move also opens the a5-d8 diagonal for the queen, giving her access to the b6 and a5 squares. }
7. e4
{ This is an alternative that only recently started to receive attention thanks to the success Black had after  7.O-O  Bf5  .  White is not against transposition to other lines of the Fianchetto Variation, but he does prevent the development of Black's light-squared bishop to f5. }
7... Be6
{ This provocative move was a result of deep preparation! One of America's best young players, GM Jeffery Xiong played this move when facing another prodigy, the German GM Vincent Keymer at the Grand Swiss event in Riga 2021. Since Keymer had played the move 7.e4 before, Xiong could prepare deeply against it and he produced a really great idea that offers Black excellent chances. }
8. Qe2
{ A move like  8.b3  is met by  8...b5  and White hasn't really solved the problem of the c4-pawn. After taking  9.cxb5  cxb5  Black threatens ...b4 and White now needs to take care of the pawn on e4. Note that White cannot take the pawn on b5 as  10.Nxb5?  Qa5  wins the knight on b5. }
8... Bg4
{ Only after forcing the queen to come to e2 does Black play ...Bg4. The idea was to weaken White's control over the d4-square @@StartBracket@@the queen from d1 supported the d4-pawn while she doesn't do so from e2@@EndBracket@@ as he now intends to attack it after ...Nfd7 and ...c5. }
9. h3 { White wants to get rid of the pin. } 9... Bxf3
{ Black eliminates a piece that covers the d4-square. } 10. Bxf3 Nfd7
{ Black continues his dark-square strategy by targeting the pawn on d4. } 11.
Be3 c5
{ After this attack White is now forced to abandon the control over the d4-square. }
12. d5
{ The most ambitious move.  In case of  12.dxc5  dxc5  13.e5  Qc8  with ...Nc6 next, Black has easy play against White's centre, the pawn on e5 and the d4-square in particular. }
12... Ne5
{ Centralising the knight and if allowed Black would take on f3, eliminating White's pair of bishops. }
13. Bg2 Qb6
{ Activating the queen. The idea is to play ...Qb4 to increase the pressure on the c4-pawn. Black has the initiative here as White is forced to defend. }
14. Rd1
{ White removes the rook from the long diagonal.  The automatic  14.O-O?!  Qb4  pinpoints White's problems as he cannot defend the pawn on c4. }
14... Qb4
{ Attacking the pawn on c4 and forcing White to retreat to f1 with the bishop as there is no other way for him to defend that pawn. }
15. Bf1 Ned7
{ An improvement over Xiong's play against Keymer, where he played the rushed  15...b5  . The knight move prepares the push of the b-pawn by first tying White down to the defence of the knight on c3. }
16. Rc1 b5
{ Sacrificing a pawn for a typical Benko Gambit type of play on the queenside. This works much better than in the Benko as White is still lagging behind in the development of his kingside. }
17. cxb5 a6
{ Increasing the pressure on White's position - Black now wants to open the a-file with ...axb5 and he also has the idea to take on c3 and then on e4, winning White's central pawn.  He also has the idea to open up the game on the kingside by playing ...f5. All these ideas give him excellent play on both sides of the board. }
