[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6. The Fianchetto Variation"]
[Black "61. Fianchetto Variation with 7.0-0. White plays 8.b3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nf3
{ If White wishes to play the Fianchetto Variation he can also start with  3.g3  , but the game will transpose after  3...Bg7  4.Nf3  O-O  . }
3... Bg7 4. g3 O-O 5. Bg2 d6 { Black plays the usual KID moves. } 6. Nc3
{ White can also start with  6.O-O  c6  7.Nc3  , but this move gives him an additional possibility on the next move. }
6... c6
{ A very flexible move for Black. First of all, he shuts the long diagonal for White's fianchettoed bishop. He also keeps his options open:    He can play ...e5, ...d5 or even ...c5.  He prepares a possible ...b5.  He can develop his knight from b8 to d7 or a6.  The pawn move also opens the a5-d8 diagonal for the queen, giving her access to the b6 and a5 squares. }
7. O-O
{ This is by far the most common move and is often automatically played. } 7...
Bf5
{ Black develops the bishop and controls the e4-square, thus preventing White's expansion with e4. Now White has a wide choice, but his most ambitious moves revolve around the fight for the e4-square. }
8. b3
{ This is a tame move. White simply wants to fianchetto his dark-squared bishop, but he neglects the e4-square. }
8... Ne4
{ Black takes advantage of the fact that White left the e4-square without control. }
9. Bb2 Nxc3
{ Black eliminates the knight that controlled the e4-square and intends to land on it with his other light piece. }
10. Bxc3 Be4
{ The bishop on e4 is neutralising White's bishop on g2. Black still keeps his options open in the centre as he can play both ...c5 and ...d5. }
11. Re1 Nd7 { Black finishes development and stays flexible. } 12. Bh3
{ This is a common idea for White in this line. He removes the bishop from the long diagonal and now wants to play Nd2 and push e4. Black's reaction is typical and one worth remembering. }
12... Bxf3 { First Black forces White to double his pawns. } 13. exf3 e6
{ Second, he places his pawns on light squares to limit White's unopposed light-squared bishop and increases the scope of his own remaining bishop. }
14. Bf1 d5
{ Third he fixes White's pawn on d4 and erects an impregnable pawn structure on the light squares. White's bishop pair cannot do anything in this closed position as Black will concentrate his play against the pawn on d4. One idea is the knight manoeuvre ...Nb6-c8-d6@@StartBracket@@e7@@EndBracket@@-f5, putting more pressure on d4. }
