7. O-O
{ This is by far the most common move and is often automatically played. } 7...
Bf5
{ Black develops the bishop and controls the e4-square, thus preventing White's expansion with e4. Now White has a wide choice, but his most ambitious moves revolve around the fight for the e4-square. }
8. b3
{ This is a tame move. White simply wants to fianchetto his dark-squared bishop, but he neglects the e4-square. }
8... Ne4
{ Black takes advantage of the fact that White left the e4-square without control. }
9. Bb2 Nxc3
{ Black eliminates the knight that controlled the e4-square and intends to land on it with his other light piece. }
10. Bxc3 Be4
{ The bishop on e4 is neutralising White's bishop on g2. Black still keeps his options open in the centre as he can play both ...c5 and ...d5. }
11. e3 Nd7 { Finishing development. } 12. Qe2 e6
{ This move is a slight improvement over  12...c5  , which was played in the online game Vidit-Caruana from 2020. Black still pursues the ...c5 push but takes one more move to prepare it. }
13. Bh3 { With the familiar idea to play Nd2 and trap the bishop on e4. } 13...
c5
{ A good move, liberating the c6-square for the light-squared bishop and putting pressure on White's centre. }
14. Nd2 Bc6
{ The bishop managed to stay alive and remain on the long diagonal. } 15. Rac1
{ Defending the bishop on c3. } 15... b6
{ Now the bishop can also drop back to b7 if needed. Black has harmonious development and a very solid position.  He can continue to improve his position with ...Qe7 and then put the rooks in the centre. Then he can consider taking on d4 to transform the position and introduce more dynamism. }
