[White "6. The Fianchetto Variation"]
[Black "63. Fianchetto Variation with 7.0-0. White plays 8.Re1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nf3
{ If White wishes to play the Fianchetto Variation he can also start with  3.g3  , but the game will transpose after  3...Bg7  4.Nf3  O-O  . }
3... Bg7 4. g3 O-O 5. Bg2 d6 { Black plays the usual KID moves. } 6. Nc3
{ White can also start with  6.O-O  c6  7.Nc3  , but this move gives him an additional possibility on the next move. }
6... c6
{ A very flexible move for Black. First of all, he shuts the long diagonal for White's fianchettoed bishop. He also keeps his options open:    He can play ...e5, ...d5 or even ...c5.  He prepares a possible ...b5.  He can develop his knight from b8 to d7 or a6.  The pawn move also opens the a5-d8 diagonal for the queen, giving her access to the b6 and a5 squares. }
7. O-O
{ This is by far the most common move and is often automatically played. } 7...
Bf5
{ Black develops the bishop and controls the e4-square, thus preventing White's expansion with e4. Now White has a wide choice, but his most ambitious moves revolve around the fight for the e4-square. }
8. Re1 { A straightforward move, intending e4. } 8... Ne4
{ Black physically stops e4. } 9. Qb3
{ In case of  9.Nd2  Nxc3  10.bxc3  e5  11.e4  Bc8  Black has a good position as he managed to double White's c-pawns. }
9... Nxc3
{ This is much better than Caruana's  9...Qb6?  after which Mamedyarov could have played  10.Nh4!  to underline the loose position of the bishop on f5 and knight on e4.  Once the knight is on e4 Black should seek to exchange it as soon as possible. }
10. bxc3
{ In case of  10.Qxb7?  Ne4  11.Qxa8  Qb6  Black is winning as the queen on a8 won't get out alive.   Taking the knight with the queen is harmless,  10.Qxc3  c5  shows the vulnerability of the queen on the long diagonal. }
10... Bc8
{ White was threatening both e4 and to take on b7,  so Black removes the bishop from f5 as it was going to be attacked anyway and defends the pawn on b7.  This is an improvement over  10...Qc8?!  11.e4  Bg4  12.e5  which gave White the initiative in the game Mamedyarov-Carlsen played at the Tal Memorial in 2013. }
11. e4 c5
{ Black attacks White's centre and intends to develop the knight on its natural square on c6. }
12. e5
{ Taking on c5 first is harmless,  12.dxc5  dxc5  13.e5  Nc6  gives Black easy play. Once he finishes development Black will have the better long-term prospects in view of White's weak doubled pawns on c3 and c4. }
12... Nc6
{ Black continues his development. Taking on e5 is bad as  12...dxe5?  13.Nxe5  gives White a close-to-winning advantage. }
13. Bf4 { White finishes development. } 13... cxd4
{ Black eliminates the tension in the centre. } 14. cxd4 dxe5
{ Preventing a possible exd6 by White. } 15. dxe5 Qb6
{ Black has no problems with the development as now the light-squared bishop can be developed to e6 from where it can attack the isolated pawn on c4. Black has a good game playing against White's weaknesses on the queenside. }
