{ This is by far the most common move and is often automatically played. } 7...
Bf5
{ Black develops the bishop and controls the e4-square, thus preventing White's expansion with e4. Now White has a wide choice, but his most ambitious moves revolve around the fight for the e4-square. }
8. Qb3
{ White immediately takes advantage of the bishop's leaving the defence of the b7-pawn. }
8... Qb6
{ Black welcomes the exchange of queens as that would open the a-file for him. }
9. Re1
{ Intending e4.  The exchange  9.Qxb6  axb6  is very good for Black who will then develop with ...Na6-b4. }
9... Na6
{ Black finishes development. Note that the usual reaction  9...Ne4?  is bad as after  10.Nh4  the bishop on f5 and the knight on e4 are loose - Black doesn't have the tempo-winning exchange ...Nxc3 attacking the queen on d1 because the queen is not there anymore. }
10. e4 Bg4 { The bishop attacks the knight that defends the pawn on d4. } 11.
Be3 { White defends the pawn on d4. } 11... Qxb3
{ With this exchange Black obtains the b4-square for his knight: after axb3 White won't have the move a3 at his disposal. }
12. axb3 Nd7
{ The immediate  12...Nb4  is also possible but Black stays flexible. He can now attack White's centre with ...e5. }
13. h3 Bxf3
{ The bishop couldn't retreat, but this is part of Black's plan. Black exchanges the knight that defends the d4-pawn, thus increasing his control over the dark squares. }
14. Bxf3 e5 { Attacking the pawn and forcing White to move it forward. } 15. d5
{ Taking  15.dxe5?  Nxe5  gives Black great activity with ...Nb4 coming next. }
15... Ndc5
{ Black obtained great squares for his knights on c5 and b4. With ...Nb4 next he will have excellent play threatening various jumps with the knights on d3 or c2. }
