{ Black reacts inthe same way as after 8.Ne1 as White abandoned the control of the e5-square.  With the knight on g5 @@StartBracket@@unlike on e1,  from where it can go to d3@@EndBracket@@, Black has the solid alternative  8...d5  , played in the online game Ding Liren-Carlsen from 2020, which gave him relatively simple equality. }
9. d5 a5
{ A typical move for Black, obtaining better control over the b4- and c5-squares.  Note the difference in Black's reaction compared tothe line 8.Ne1: In the similar position there Black took on d5 but here taking on d5 is worse because after  9...cxd5?!  10.Nxd5  Nxd5  11.Bxd5  Nc6  @@StartBracket@@which was good for Black inthe line 8.Ne1@@EndBracket@@  10.Ne4!  is problematic for Black because White has the threat Nxd6 when Black cannot take ...Qxd6 in view of the tactic Bxf7 winning the queen on d6. }
10. e4 Bc8
{ The bishop goes all the way back to c8 in order to leave the d-file open so that the queen can defend the pawn on d6 in case White takes on c6. }
11. h3
{ The point of Black's last move is seen after  11.dxc6  bxc6  as Black can recapture with the pawn to control the d5-square and keep his d6-pawn protected by the queen. }
11... cxd5 { With this exchange Black opens the c-file. } 12. cxd5 Na6
{ Black completes his development unhindered. He will continue with ...Bd7 @@StartBracket@@threatening ...b5@@EndBracket@@, ...Rc8 and can then play on both sides of the board with his kingside play based on the typical ...f5 push.  This was nicely demonstrated in the game Lenderman-Caruana played in the US Championship in 2021: }
13. Be3 Bd7 { Threatening ...b5. } 14. a4 Rc8 15. Nf3 Rxc3
{ A wonderful exchange sacrifice that allows Black to be in control of the queenside as now one of his knights will never be chased away from the c5-square. }
16. bxc3 Nxe4 { Black took over the initiative and won a good game. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6. The Fianchetto Variation"]
[Black "67. Fianchetto Variation with 7.0-0. White plays 8.Nh4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nf3
{ If White wishes to play the Fianchetto Variation he can also start with  3.g3  , but the game will transpose after  3...Bg7  4.Nf3  O-O  . }
3... Bg7 4. g3 O-O 5. Bg2 d6 { Black plays the usual KID moves. } 6. Nc3
{ White can also start with  6.O-O  c6  7.Nc3  , but this move gives him an additional possibility on the next move. }
6... c6
{ A very flexible move for Black. First of all, he shuts the long diagonal for White's fianchettoed bishop. He also keeps his options open:    He can play ...e5, ...d5 or even ...c5.  He prepares a possible ...b5.  He can develop his knight from b8 to d7 or a6.  The pawn move also opens the a5-d8 diagonal for the queen, giving her access to the b6 and a5 squares. }
7. O-O
{ This is by far the most common move and is often automatically played. } 7...
Bf5
{ Black develops the bishop and controls the e4-square, thus preventing White's expansion with e4. Now White has a wide choice, but his most ambitious moves revolve around the fight for the e4-square. }
8. Nh4
{ The most commonly played move. White attacks the bishop on f5 and intends to play e4. The drawback of the move is obvious - the knight is now on the rim. }
8... Be6 { Black moves away with tempo and provokes White to push d5. } 9. d5
{ The most ambitious.  After  9.b3  d5  10.cxd5  cxd5  followed by ...Nc6 Black has easy play as he has harmonious development and can play along the c-file while White still needs to get his knight on h4 back into the game. }
9... cxd5
{ Black opens the c-file as he intends to use it to create counterplay.  He has the interesting alternative  9...Bd7!?  at his disposal, postponing the capture on d5. }
10. cxd5 Bd7
{ From d7 the bishop supports the ...b5 push though Black should be careful about it as it weakens the c6-square. }
11. Nf3
{ White brings the knight back from the rim. Against other moves Black's play won't differ much from the main line. Generally speaking Black's piece placement in these lines is fairly straightforward:    The knight goes to a6 and likely to c5.  The queen to a5 or b6.  One rook comes to c8.  Then he plays on the queenside using the c5 and b4 squares in combination with a possible pawn advance with ...a5-a4 or ...b5.  
Examples for this set-up can be seen after  11.e4  Na6  12.Be3  Rc8  with ...Nc5 next, or @@StartFEN@@rn1q1rk1/pp1bppbp/3p1np1/3P4/7N/2N3P1/PP2PPBP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 1 11@@EndFEN@@  11.Be3  Na6  12.Bd4  Nc5  . }
11... Na6 { Black follows his plan. } 12. Nd4
{ Centralising the knight. White's ideal set-up here is to place a bishop on e3,  the queen on d2 and put the rooks on the c- and d-files.  If White decides to centralise the bishop instead, then after  12.Be3  Qa5  13.Bd4  Nc5  Black again obtains comfortable development. }
12... Qb6
{ Targeting the knight on d4 and the pawn on b2.  Here the typical  12...Qa5  can be met by  13.Nb3  , but @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pp1bppbp/n2p1np1/3P4/3N4/2N3P1/PP2PPBP/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 4 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Nc5  13.Rb1  a5  is possible. }
13. Nb3 { Getting away from harm's way. } 13... Nc5
{ Attacking the knight on b3.  The alternative is another typical rearrangement of Black's pieces after  13...Rfc8  14.Be3  Qd8  followed by ...Nc5 or ...Nc7 and a possible advance of the queenside pawns. }
14. Be3 Ng4 { Harassing White's bishop. } 15. Nxc5
{ The exchange of the dark-squared bishops is in Black's favour.  After  15.Bd4  Bxd4  16.Qxd4  Rfc8  White is left with a passive bishop on g2 and Black has unhindered control over the dark squares, e5 and c5 in particular. }
15... dxc5 16. Bd2 Ne5
{ Black has a comfortable position. His immediate threats are ...Nc4 and ...Qxb2 while more generally he'd like to advance his queenside majority, for example by ...Rac8 and ...c4. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7. Various Systems on Move 5"]
[Black "68. Various Systems. White plays 5.Nge2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nge2
{ The knight is en route to g3, from where it controls the f5 and e4 squares. From g3 it also aids the h4-h5 advance. }
5... O-O 6. Ng3 e5 { Black reacts in a typical KID fashion. } 7. d5 a5
{ Another typical move after White has closed the centre: Black grabs some space on the queenside and obtains better control over the dark squares on the queenside, b4 and c5 in particular. }
8. Be2 { The bishop from e2 supports the h4-h5 idea. } 8... Na6
{ Black develops the knight on a6 from where it is ready to join the game by jumping to c5. }
9. h4 h5
{ It is important to stop White's idea of h5 because allowing it gives White the options to either open the h-file by taking on g6 or to shut Black's kingside by playing h6. }
10. Bg5
{ The pin on the h4-d8 diagonal introduces the threat of Bxh5, so Black is well-advised to avoid it. }
10... Qe8
{ Removing the queen from the pin and avoiding the dangerous sacrifice on h5. }
11. Qd2 Nc5
{ Activating the knight and putting more pressure on the pawn on e4. } 12. f3
{ This is better than  12.O-O-O  , which was played in the game Carlsen-Radjabov in Shamkir 2014, because the long castle allows  12...Ng4!  obtaining the pair of bishops after  13.Bxg4  Bxg4  which gave Black comfortable play as he went on to prepare the ...f5 push.   The move  12.f3  takes control over the g4-square and avoids the knight jump. }
12... Bd7
{ Black finishes development and supports the further advance of his a-pawn. }
13. O-O-O
{ If White wants to exchange the dark-squared bishops with  13.Bh6  then Black reacts with  13...Nh7  14.Bxg7  Kxg7  when he will play on both sides of the board with ...a4-a3 on the queenside and ...f5 on the kingside. }
13... a4 { Black wants to weaken White's queenside by pushing ...a3. } 14. Kb1
{ A useful move for White, avoiding a possible check after ...Nb3. } 14... a3
{ Black forces the b-pawn to move. With the pawn on a3 the White king will never be safe, thus every opening of the position will be dangerous for him. }
15. b3 Nh7
{ Since he maximised his position on the queenside Black turns his attention to the kingside, preparing the ...f5-push. }
16. Be3 { After  16.Bh6  f5  Black has active play on the kingside. } 16... f5
{ Black starts his kingside play. The immediate threat is ...f4. } 17. Bxc5
{ An attempt to play in the centre.  Retreating with  17.Bf2  Nf6  is comfortable for Black, who already wants to take on e4 and after White recaptures fxe4 he intends to use the weakened g4-square. }
17... dxc5 18. d6 cxd6 { Black's last two moves are forced. } 19. Qxd6 Nf6
{ Getting the knight back into the game and defending the bishop on d7. } 20.
Qxc5 { White won a pawn, but now: } 20... f4
{ Forcing the knight back on the first rank. } 21. Nf1 Rf7
{ With the idea of ...Bf8 Black has excellent compensation because of his control over the dark squares. Once his unopposed dark-squared bishop comes into the game the long-term weakness of the white king will become even more important. }
