[White "7. Various Systems on Move 5"]
[Black "69. Various Systems. White plays 5.Bg5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Bg5
{ A rare move nowadays, but in the past it was frequently played by GM Ivan Sokolov. The idea is to continue with Qd2. }
5... h6 { Black immediately chases away the bishop. } 6. Be3
{ Going to h4 just places the bishop out of play after  6.Bh4  g5  7.Bg3  c5  8.d5  Qa5  with the threat of ...Nxe4 as shown in the game Spassky-Fischer, game 16 of their match played in Belgrade in 1992.   Retreating to f4 is not better either, as  6.Bf4  Nc6  allows ...e5 next with ...Nd4 to come after White plays d5. }
6... Ng4
{ Black quickly takes over the initiative by harassing the white bishop. } 7.
Bc1 c5
{ This opens the long diagonal for the dark-squared bishop and gets control over the d4-square. }
8. d5
{ Taking on c5 is worse as after  8.dxc5  Bxc3!  9.bxc3  dxc5  Black has the better structure and the easier game as he can play against the doubled c-pawns @@StartBracket@@for example with ...Nc6-a5 and ...Be6 or ...b6 and ...Ba6@@EndBracket@@. }
8... Bd4 { Hitting the f2-pawn. } 9. Nh3 e5
{ Cementing the bishop on d4. It's already clear that Black has a fantastic version of the KID structure as instead of being on g7 his dark-squared bishop is on the dominating position on d4!  White cannot really weaken Black's grip on d4 as taking en passant only activates Black's pieces: }
10. dxe6 Bxe6 11. Be2 Qh4
{ Attacking f2 one more time and defending the knight on g4. } 12. O-O Nc6
{ With initiative thanks to his wonderful development and strong piece activity. Black would like to castle long and start attacking on the kingside while White finds it difficult to get his pieces into the game. }
