[White "7. Various Systems on Move 5"]
[Black "70. Various Systems. White plays 5.Be2 6.g4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Be2 O-O 6. g4
{ This is the alternative flank advance, but it is clearly worse than the push of the h-pawn. }
6... c5
{ Black would like to transform the structure to one from the Modern Benoni as in those more open structures @@StartBracket@@compared to the KID structures after ...e5,  d5@@EndBracket@@ Black can more easily try to take advantage of the weakening of White's kingside and the lack of shelter for the white king.  Apart from the move 6...c5 Black also has a shocking alternative like  6...b5!?  , literally saying to White 'if you can move a knight's pawn so can I!' The move should wrestle the psychological initiative from White as it gives Black good compensation after  7.g5  Nfd7  8.Nxb5  a6  9.Nc3  Nc6  with ...e5 and ...Nd4 to follow. }
7. g5 { Or  7.d5  e6  8.g5  Ne8  which transposes. } 7... Ne8
{ It's important to put the knight on e8 as from there it can go to c7 to support ...b5 @@StartBracket@@a useful idea in the Modern Benoni structures@@EndBracket@@. }
8. d5
{ Taking the pawn on c5 wrecks White's position after  8.dxc5?!  Bxc3  @@StartBracket@@this is the simplest@@EndBracket@@  9.bxc3  Qa5  with all @@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ White's pawns being weak. }
8... e6 { Undermining White's centre. } 9. h4 exd5
{ Black naturally seeks to open the game in order to punish White for his neglect of development. }
10. cxd5
{ In case of  10.exd5  Bxc3!  11.bxc3  Ng7  Black again managed to weaken almost all White's pawns and has the preferable game as all his pieces are easily coming into the game: ...Nd7-e5,  ...Re8,  ...Nf5 @@StartBracket@@or ...Bf5@@EndBracket@@, ...Qa5 etc. }
10... Qe7
{ Activating the queen and intending further opening of the game, though the immediate threat is to take on c3 and win the pawn on e4. }
11. Qc2 f5 { Black clearly takes over the initiative. } 12. gxf6 Nxf6
{ Black has a clearly superior Modern Benoni position with White's position in ruins as his king will never find a safe shelter while Black has play both in the centre and on the queenside @@StartBracket@@for example ...Na6-c7 to execute the ...b5-push@@EndBracket@@. }
