[White "7. Various Systems on Move 5"]
[Black "71. Various Systems. White plays 5.Be2 6.h4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Be2 O-O 6. h4
{ White can transpose to the Classical Variation with  6.Nf3  , to the Averbakh Variation with  6.Bg5  or  6.Be3  , but he can also try a couple of wing attempts with h4 or g4.   This line with  6.h4  became popular as a way to avoid the Grunfeld Defence after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  g6  3.h4  when play would usually transpose to our lines after  3...Bg7  4.Nc3  d6  5.e4  O-O  6.Be2  . }
6... h5 { Stopping White's idea is the simplest. } 7. Nf3
{ In case of  7.Bg5  Black first stays flexible with  7...a6  @@StartBracket@@just in case preparing Benko Gambit ideas like ...c5 followed by ...b5@@EndBracket@@ and waits for  8.Nf3  so that he can play  8...Bg4  , with similar play as after 7.Nf3. }
7... Bg4
{ The bishop uses the weakened g4-square to exert pressure on White's centre in an indirect way, by attacking the knight that controls the d4-square. }
8. Be3 { White lends extra support to the d4-pawn. } 8... Nbd7
{ Black finishes development and is ready to push ...e5, but he will only do so once White has castled short. He wants to be able to change plans and play ...c6, ...Qa5 and ...b5 in case White castles long. }
9. Qc2
{ After  9.O-O  e5  @@StartBracket@@only now, once White's committed to kingside castling@@EndBracket@@  10.d5  Bxf3!  11.Bxf3  Kh7!  @@StartBracket@@with the idea of ...Bh6 to exchange the dark-squared bishops@@EndBracket@@  12.Qd2  Ng4  @@StartBracket@@still with the same idea@@EndBracket@@ Black has a very good game without bad pieces. }
9... c6
{ Black stays flexible and waits for White to determine his king's position. }
10. Rd1
{ In case of  10.O-O-O?!  Qa5!  with the idea of ...Rab8 and ...b5 Black's idea with the flexibility pays off - he can start attacking White's king faster.  After the rook move, Black can prepare the ...e5-push since the opponent's king will hide on the kingside. }
10... Qc7 { Getting away from the pin on the d-file and preparing ...e5. } 11.
O-O e5 { Achieving the central push and putting pressure on White's d4-pawn. }
12. d5 cxd5
{ Black opens the c-file and avoids dxc6 when White could try to pile up on the d-file and target the pawn on d6. }
13. cxd5 Bxf3
{ The bishop didn't have better options and by taking on f3 it liberates the g4-square for the knight, thus making sure White doesn't remain with the pair of bishops. }
14. Bxf3 Ng4
{ Black wants to take on e3 or to play ...Bh6 to exchange the dark-squared bishops. }
15. Bxg4 hxg4 16. Rc1 Nf6
{ With ideas like ...Nh5 and ...f5 Black has good counterplay while White has little to attack on the queenside. }
