1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. g3
{ This is a strange mix of the classical development and the fianchetto, rarely seen nowadays. }
5... O-O
{ Black finishes the development of the kingside and castles in the usual way. }
6. Bg2 Nc6
{ Since White postponed the development of his king's knight and thus still doesn't have sufficient control over the d4-square Black immediately targets it and intends ...e5 and ...Nd4. }
7. d5 Na5
{ The pawn on c4 is attacked and in view of the exposure on the long diagonal White cannot easily defend it with b3. For example: }
8. b3
{ Defending the pawn with the queen is better,  8.Qe2  c6  9.Nf3  Bg4  when Black follows up with ...Rc8,  ...cxd5 and ...Nc4 with excellent play. }
8... Nxd5 { Black takes advantage of White's weaknesses on the long diagonal. }
9. Nxd5 c6
{ Taking on a1 is also possible,  9...Bxa1  10.Bd2  Nxc4  11.bxc4  Bg7  when Black has a rook and two pawns for two light pieces and a compact position. }
10. Rb1 cxd5 { Black regains the piece now. } 11. cxd5 Qb6
{ Black wants to bring his knight back into the game via c4. He also plans to play ...e6 to open up the game before White manages to finish his development. }
