[White "7. Various Systems on Move 5"]
[Black "75. Various Systems. White plays 5.Be3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Be3 O-O 6. Nf3
{ White can transpose to the Saemisch Variation with  6.f3  , to the Averbakh Variation with  6.Be2  or to the Makagonov Variation with  6.h3  .  Mixing Nf3 and Be3 was played by GM Bent Larsen in the 1960s, but it is far from a critical line today. }
6... e5 { The usual central thrust works well for Black. } 7. d5
{ The exchange on e5 is harmless. After  7.dxe5  dxe5  8.Qxd8  Rxd8  9.Nd5  Na6!  Black has excellent play and good prospects in the endgame thanks to the weakness of the d4-square. This was already indicated by Bobby Fischer in his book My 60 Memorable Games. }
7... Ng4
{ It is important to play this move immediately before White prevents it by playing h3, which would transpose to the Makagonov Variation and a line that is not recommended in this repertoire. }
8. Bg5 f6 { Forcing the bishop to h4. } 9. Bh4
{ In case of  9.Bd2  f5  Black immediately obtains great play in the centre. }
9... g5 { Pushing the bishop back to g3. } 10. Bg3 Nh6
{ Now Black wants to continue with ...f5 and recapture on f5 with the knight. }
11. Nd2
{ The only way back into the game for the stranded bishop on g3 is after f3 and Bf2, so White liberates the f3-square for the pawn. }
11... f5 { The threat is to trap the bishop by ...f4. } 12. exf5 Nxf5
{ The knight is well placed on f5 from where it keeps an eye both on the bishop on g3 and the d4-square. }
13. Bd3
{ White's play is based on the control of the e4-square, but Black has the d4-square as compensation. }
13... Na6 { The knight joins the game via the c5-square. } 14. Nde4 b6
{ Preparing ...Nc5 so if White takes on c5 Black can recapture with the b6-pawn, opening the b-file and strengthening the control over the d4-square. }
15. f3
{ The bishop needs to be able to drop back to f2 since on g3 it is biting on granite - the pawn on e5 is severely limiting its activity. }
15... Nc5 { Black continues his plan. } 16. Nxc5 bxc5
{ Now the b-file can be used for counterplay after ...Rb8. In addition to this Black has absolute control over the d4-square. Black also has the typical pawn sacrifice ...e4 at his disposal, which activates his dark-squared bishop along the long diagonal. These strategic ideas give Black good chances in the upcoming middlegame. }
*

