1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Bd3
{ This system was popularised by GM Yasser Seirawan. White intends to develop his king's knight to e2, thus allowing several things:    f3 to support the pawn on e4, like in the Saemisch Variation.  To play f4 as a reply to Black's ...f5, thus stopping Black's kingside advance.  To play Ng3, increasing White's control over the e4- and f5-squares.  
The drawback of this setup is the decreased control over the d4-square as the bishop on d3 severs the connection between the queen on d1 and the pawn on d4. }
5... O-O 6. Nge2 Nc6
{ Black immediately targets the weakened spot in White's position. } 7. O-O
{ The natural continuation.  The alternative is  7.Bg5  but after  7...e5  8.d5  Nd4  9.Qd2  c5  10.O-O  a6  we have a transposition to the line arising after @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/2np1np1/8/2PPP3/2NB4/PP2NPPP/R1BQK2R w KQ - 4 7@@EndFEN@@  7.O-O  e5  8.d5  Nd4  9.Bg5  c5  10.Qd2  a6  . }
7... e5 { Black attacks White's vulnerable d4-spot. } 8. d5 Nd4
{ Again Black takes advantage of White's insufficient control over the d4-square by placing his knight in a dominant position. }
9. Nxd4 exd4 10. Ne2
{ After  10.Nb5  Re8  11.Re1  a6  forces favourable simplifications after  12.Nxd4  Nxd5  13.cxd5  Bxd4  with comfortable equality for Black who has control over the long diagonal. }
10... Re8 { Attacking the pawn on e4. } 11. f3
{ White defends the pawn on e4. } 11... c5
{ Black secures the pawn on d4 transforming it to a protected passed pawn. }
12. Ng3
{ White cannot capture the pawn on d4 as  12.dxc6  bxc6  13.Nxd4  is most easily met by  13...Qb6  14.Be3  Ng4!  15.fxg4  Bxd4  with an excellent position for Black who managed to wreck White's structure. }
12... Nd7
{ With the pawn on e4 secure defended the knight on f6 wasn't very useful so it moves to d7 from where it can come to e5. }
13. f4 { White prevents ...Ne5. } 13... b5
{ An important idea for Black in this structure. He wants to undermine White's centre by attacking the pawn on c4. The point is that after... }
14. cxb5 a6
{ Black intends to set his central pawn pair of c5 and d4 going and combine that threat with play on the queenside along the open a- and b-files. For example: }
15. bxa6 Bxa6 16. Bxa6 Rxa6 { With ideas like ...Qa8, ...Rb8 and ...c4. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7. Various Systems on Move 5"]
[Black "77. Various Systems. White plays 5.Bd3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Bd3
{ This system was popularised by GM Yasser Seirawan. White intends to develop his king's knight to e2, thus allowing several things:    f3 to support the pawn on e4, like in the Saemisch Variation.  To play f4 as a reply to Black's ...f5, thus stopping Black's kingside advance.  To play Ng3, increasing White's control over the e4- and f5-squares.  
The drawback of this setup is the decreased control over the d4-square as the bishop on d3 severs the connection between the queen on d1 and the pawn on d4. }
5... O-O 6. Nge2 Nc6
{ Black immediately targets the weakened spot in White's position. } 7. O-O
{ The natural continuation.  The alternative is  7.Bg5  but after  7...e5  8.d5  Nd4  9.Qd2  c5  10.O-O  a6  we have a transposition to the line arising after @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/2np1np1/8/2PPP3/2NB4/PP2NPPP/R1BQK2R w KQ - 4 7@@EndFEN@@  7.O-O  e5  8.d5  Nd4  9.Bg5  c5  10.Qd2  a6  . }
7... e5 { Black attacks White's vulnerable d4-spot. } 8. d5 Nd4
{ Again Black takes advantage of White's insufficient control over the d4-square by placing his knight in a dominant position. }
9. Bg5 c5
{ Black secures his knight on d4. Now in case of an exchange he will have a protected passed pawn there. }
10. Qd2 a6
{ Both a prophylactic move @@StartBracket@@taking away the b5-square from the white knight so Black can play ...Qc7 not fearing attacks on his queen@@EndBracket@@ and an active move @@StartBracket@@preparing the ...b5-push, an idea we also see in the line @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp2pbp/3p1np1/3Pp3/2PnP3/2NB4/PP2NPPP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 1 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Nxd4  exd4  10.Ne2  @@StartBracket@@seethis line@@EndBracket@@ @@EndBracket@@. }
11. Nxd4
{ If White doesn't take then Black plays ...Qa5, ...Rb8 in order to achieve the ...b5-push. }
11... exd4
{ Black takes with the e-pawn in order to have a pawn mass in the centre connected with his queenside. The capture with the e-pawn also gives him access to the e5-square. }
12. Ne2 b5 { Activating the queenside pawn mass. } 13. b3
{ White cannot take twice on b5 as his pawn on e4 hangs:  13.cxb5  axb5  14.Bxb5  Nxe4!  . }
13... Qe8
{ Moving away from the pin, attacking the pawn on e4 and defending the pawn on b5. }
14. f3 Nd7
{ The knight is en route to e5 from where it puts pressure on the c4-pawn and allows Black to take on d3, thus obtaining the bishop pair. His play is on the queenside where he wants to use the b-file and the weakness of the c4-pawn. }
