1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3
{ Note that after  3.h4  Bg7  4.Nc3  d6  5.e4  O-O  6.Be2  we have a transposition to the lines after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppppp1p/5np1/8/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  Bg7  4.e4  d6  5.Be2  O-O  6.h4  @@StartBracket@@seethis line@@EndBracket@@ in the ChapterVarious Systems on Move 5.   White can also start with  3.Nf3  Bg7  4.e3  @@StartBracket@@a popular move-order to avoid the Grunfeld Defence, but for the KID player it matters little@@EndBracket@@  4...O-O  5.Be2  d6  6.Nc3  when we have a transposition to the system after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppppp1p/5np1/8/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  Bg7  4.Nf3  d6  5.e3  O-O  6.Be2  @@StartBracket@@seethis line@@EndBracket@@. }
3... Bg7 4. Bg5
{ This is another rare option where transpositions are possible. } 4... d6
{ Black plays the usual move and waits for White to play  5.Nf3  and transpose to the lines after @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppppppbp/5np1/8/2PP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nf3  d6  5.Bg5  @@StartBracket@@seethis line@@EndBracket@@. }
5. e3
{ As mentioned,  5.Nf3  h6  transposes to the lines after @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppppppbp/5np1/8/2PP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nf3  d6  5.Bg5  h6  @@StartBracket@@seethis line@@EndBracket@@.   5.e4  h6  transposes to the line @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppppppbp/5np1/8/2PP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4.e4  d6  5.Bg5  h6  @@StartBracket@@seethis line@@EndBracket@@ from the chapterVarious Systems on Move 5. }
5... c5
{ This is more precise than the immediate  5...h6  and the reason is seen in case White takes on c5. }
6. dxc5
{ The other moves either transpose, like  6.Nf3  h6  7.Bh4  g5  8.Bg3  Nh5  , which is analysed after @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppppppbp/5np1/8/2PP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nf3  d6  5.Bg5  h6  6.Bh4  g5  7.Bg3  Nh5  8.e3  c5  @@StartBracket@@seethis line@@EndBracket@@,   or are worse, like  6.d5?!  h6  7.Bh4  Qa5  with the threats of ...Ne4 or ...a6 and ...b5. }
6... Qa5
{ This was Black's idea of not inserting ...h6 - in view of the pin along the 5th rank White cannot take on d6 because the bishop on g5 is hanging. }
7. Qd2
{ White must break the pin on the e1-a5 diagonal. The automatic  7.Nf3?  loses to  7...Ne4  as there is an impending catastrophe on c3. }
7... dxc5
{ Black has very easy play here. His pieces are coming into the game quickly with ...Nc6, ...0-0, ...Be6@@StartBracket@@f5@@EndBracket@@, ...Rfd8 all following naturally. }
