[White "8. Miscellaneous Systems"]
[Black "79. Miscellaneous Systems. White plays 4.Nf3 5.Bf4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3
{ Note that after  3.h4  Bg7  4.Nc3  d6  5.e4  O-O  6.Be2  we have a transposition to the lines after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppppp1p/5np1/8/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  Bg7  4.e4  d6  5.Be2  O-O  6.h4  @@StartBracket@@seethis line@@EndBracket@@ in the ChapterVarious Systems on Move 5.   White can also start with  3.Nf3  Bg7  4.e3  @@StartBracket@@a popular move-order to avoid the Grunfeld Defence, but for the KID player it matters little@@EndBracket@@  4...O-O  5.Be2  d6  6.Nc3  when we have a transposition to the system after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppppp1p/5np1/8/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  Bg7  4.Nf3  d6  5.e3  O-O  6.Be2  @@StartBracket@@seethis line@@EndBracket@@. }
3... Bg7 4. Nf3
{ The move  4.g3  transposes to theFianchetto Variation after  4...O-O  5.Bg2  d6  . }
4... d6
{ This is a smart move-order. By not committing his king just yet Black is more easily ready to expand with ...h6 and ...g5 in case White plays Bg5. }
5. Bf4 { This is a solid choice for White, akin to the London System. } 5...
O-O { Black finishes the usual development of the kingside. } 6. e3
{ White can also play  6.h3  if he's worried about his bishop on f4,  but that only gives Black an extra tempo to use to play in the centre after  6...Nc6  7.e3  Qe8  with ...e5 next and similar play as in the lines after 6.e3,  but more favourable for Black because h3 doesn't really aid White's position.  A sample line is  8.Be2  e5  9.dxe5  dxe5  10.Bh2  Qe7  with comfortable development after ...b6 and ...Bb7 or ...Rd8 and ...Bf5. }
6... Nc6
{ Black has many good lines against White's unambitious setup, for example:  A@@EndBracket@@  6...Bf5!?  @@StartBracket@@with the idea of ...Ne4@@EndBracket@@   B@@EndBracket@@  6...Nbd7  @@StartBracket@@with the idea to sacrifice a pawn with ...e5 next@@EndBracket@@   C@@EndBracket@@  6...c5   The move with the knight to c6 is a more provocative one, tempting White to enter KID positions that he likely wanted to avoid by choosing the line with 5.Bf4. }
7. Be2
{ Black's provocation is seen in the line  7.d5?!  e5!  with a favourable KID position after  8.Bg5  Ne7  when White's pawn on e3 is definitely one square short of its best spot! }
7... Qe8
{ Black plays for the ...e5 push.  Again there are interesting alternatives, for example:  A@@EndBracket@@  7...Bf5  @@StartBracket@@with the idea of ...Ne4@@EndBracket@@   B@@EndBracket@@  7...Nd7  @@StartBracket@@with the idea of ...e5@@EndBracket@@   C@@EndBracket@@  7...Nh5 }
8. O-O
{ After  8.d5  e5!  is again Black's idea, obtaining a typical KID position after  9.Bg5  Ne7  with the standard play of aiming for ...f5,  this time aided by the fact that after ...h6 White will be forced to part with his dark-squared bishop. }
8... e5 { Achieving the main idea. } 9. dxe5
{ This is White's typical reaction. Moving away with the bishop is less critical, for example:  A@@EndBracket@@  9.Bg3  exd4  10.Nxd4  Ne4  with good play.   B@@EndBracket@@  9.Bg5  h6  10.Bxf6  Bxf6  11.Nd5  Qd8  @@StartBracket@@or even the more complex  11...Bd8!?  @@EndBracket@@ with equality. }
9... dxe5 { Recapturing with tempo. } 10. Bg3
{ White maintains the bishop on the h2-b8 diagonal. } 10... Bf5
{ Black finishes development and intends ...Rd8 or ...Ne4.  There is an interesting alternative in  10...a5!?  , a generally useful move on the queenside that controls the b4-square. }
11. Nd5
{ In case of  11.Qb3  the simplest is  11...b6  , even though Black has the more complex alternative  11...Ne4  at his disposal as well.  The knight jump is critical since it poses direct threats. }
11... Nxd5
{ The more direct move, though Black has a good alternative in  11...Rd8  . }
12. cxd5 Nd8
{ Black's idea is to undermine White's d5-pawn by ...c6. Now a sample line leading to unclear play is: }
13. Nd2 { Intending e4. } 13... c6 { Black executes his plan. } 14. e4 Bd7
{ No other sensible square for the bishop. } 15. Nc4 cxd5
{ Now Black obtains a majority in the centre while White obtains a passed d-pawn, leading to a double-edged position. }
16. exd5 f5
{ With the threat to trap the bishop by ...f4, but also liberating the f7-square for the knight. }
17. f3 Nf7
{ Activating the knight. The position is sharp and Black has the long-term prospects of the better structure - in an endgame, the pawn on d5 will become weak as it can be easily blockaded when Black's central majority can advance forward.  Now Black wants to improve the position of his pieces by ...Qe7 @@StartBracket@@connecting the rooks@@EndBracket@@ and then there are ideas like ...Bb5, putting the rooks on the central files, pushing ...e4 etc. }
