1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3
{ Note that after  3.h4  Bg7  4.Nc3  d6  5.e4  O-O  6.Be2  we have a transposition to the lines after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppppp1p/5np1/8/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  Bg7  4.e4  d6  5.Be2  O-O  6.h4  @@StartBracket@@seethis line@@EndBracket@@ in the ChapterVarious Systems on Move 5.   White can also start with  3.Nf3  Bg7  4.e3  @@StartBracket@@a popular move-order to avoid the Grunfeld Defence, but for the KID player it matters little@@EndBracket@@  4...O-O  5.Be2  d6  6.Nc3  when we have a transposition to the system after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppppp1p/5np1/8/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  Bg7  4.Nf3  d6  5.e3  O-O  6.Be2  @@StartBracket@@seethis line@@EndBracket@@. }
3... Bg7 4. Nf3
{ The move  4.g3  transposes to theFianchetto Variation after  4...O-O  5.Bg2  d6  . }
4... d6
{ This is a smart move-order. By not committing his king just yet Black is more easily ready to expand with ...h6 and ...g5 in case White plays Bg5. }
5. e3
{ White's setup is not ambitious, but this line has become popular as a way to avoid the Grunfeld Defence, usually via the move-order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  g6  3.Nf3  Bg7  4.e3  O-O  5.Be2  d6  6.Nc3  . }
5... O-O 6. Be2 Nc6
{ Against White's unassuming setup Black has many good plans, but they generally revolve around pushing ...e5 or ...c5. With the knight move Black intends ...e5 and at the same time provokes White to cross the equator with d5, thus initiating more complex play. }
7. O-O e5
{ Black has an excellent position already, having achieved the central push. }
8. b3
{ This is White's best.  Pushing  8.d5?!  Ne7  is bad for White because Black has a favourable version of the Mar del Plata Variation - White's pawn is still on e3 instead of e4,  which gives him great play by simple means: move the knight from f6,  push ...f5 and attack the kingside.   Similarly,  8.dxe5  dxe5  is excellent for Black as White has problems developing his dark-squared bishop. }
8... exd4
{ The simplest. By eliminating the tension in the centre Black obtains smooth development. }
9. exd4
{ In case of  9.Nxd4  Nxd4  10.exd4  d5  Black has the potentially better structure as the pawn on d4 is fixed on a dark square and can be targeted by the fianchettoed bishop. }
9... Re8
{ A natural move, putting the rook on the open file.  A good alternative is  9...Bf5  with the idea of ...Ne4.   Also fine but somewhat more complicated is  9...d5  , played in the blitz game So-Navara from Saint Louis 2019. }
10. Be3 Ne7
{ Re-routing the knight to f5. Black has good play as he has a compact position with all his pieces placed comfortably.  After playing ...Nf5 Black can play ...Ne4, opening the long diagonal for the dark-squared bishop and increasing the pressure on the d4-pawn. }
