{ Note that after  3.h4  Bg7  4.Nc3  d6  5.e4  O-O  6.Be2  we have a transposition to the lines after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppppp1p/5np1/8/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  Bg7  4.e4  d6  5.Be2  O-O  6.h4  @@StartBracket@@seethis line@@EndBracket@@ in the ChapterVarious Systems on Move 5.   White can also start with  3.Nf3  Bg7  4.e3  @@StartBracket@@a popular move-order to avoid the Grunfeld Defence, but for the KID player it matters little@@EndBracket@@  4...O-O  5.Be2  d6  6.Nc3  when we have a transposition to the system after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppppp1p/5np1/8/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  Bg7  4.Nf3  d6  5.e3  O-O  6.Be2  @@StartBracket@@seethis line@@EndBracket@@. }
3... Bg7 4. Nf3
{ The move  4.g3  transposes to theFianchetto Variation after  4...O-O  5.Bg2  d6  . }
4... d6
{ This is a smart move-order. By not committing his king just yet Black is more easily ready to expand with ...h6 and ...g5 in case White plays Bg5. }
5. e3
{ White's setup is not ambitious, but this line has become popular as a way to avoid the Grunfeld Defence, usually via the move-order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  g6  3.Nf3  Bg7  4.e3  O-O  5.Be2  d6  6.Nc3  . }
5... O-O 6. Be2 Nc6
{ Against White's unassuming setup Black has many good plans, but they generally revolve around pushing ...e5 or ...c5. With the knight move Black intends ...e5 and at the same time provokes White to cross the equator with d5, thus initiating more complex play. }
7. d5 { The critical move. } 7... Nb8
{ This is simpler than  7...Nb4  , which is a viable alternative that was played in the game Caruana-Carlsen played in Karlsruhe in 2018.  Now Black wants to undermine White's centre by ...e6. }
8. O-O
{ In case of  8.e4  e6  Black wants to continue with ...Re8 and ...exd5,  ideally forcing White to recapture with the e-pawn when he would have simple play after ...a5 and ...Na6-c5. }
8... e6 { Following the plan. } 9. dxe6
{ After  9.e4  Re8  Black wants to take ...exd5 when in view of the attack on the pawn on e4 White will be forced to recapture exd5. Then Black has easy development with ...a5 and ...Na6-c5.   If White decides to take on e6 then we will have a transposition to the lines after  9.dxe6  . }
9... Bxe6
{ Black can also try  9...fxe6  , which gives him good play as well. } 10. Nd4
Bd7 { Black preserves the bishop. } 11. e4
{ White takes over the centre, but after the next two moves we have a well-known theoretical position where Black is a tempo up @@StartBracket@@the bishop on d7@@EndBracket@@.  However, if White doesn't advance in the centre then Black simply plays ...Nc6 and ...Re8 with good play because he has smooth development while White's dark-squared bishop still has to be developed. }
11... Re8 { Attacking the pawn on e4. } 12. f3 Nc6
{ Black naturally finishes development. This position, with the bishop on c8,  is a well-known theoretical tabiya that arises after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  g6  3.Nc3  Bg7  4.e4  d6  5.Nf3  O-O  6.Be2  e5  7.O-O  exd4  8.Nxd4  Re8  9.f3  Nc6  and it is considered as quite a good one for Black.  Here, a tempo up @@StartBracket@@the bishop is already on d7@@EndBracket@@, Black has even less to worry about. Here's a brief overview of Black's plans: }
13. Nc2
{ White avoids possible problems with the knight on d4.  After  13.Be3  Nh5  14.Qd2  Nxd4  15.Bxd4  Nf4!  we see the idea of the pressure on the long diagonal, with Black simplifying the position in view of the zwischenschach on e2.   Taking on c6 is harmless as  13.Nxc6  bxc6  only helps Black to control the d5-square. }
13... Nh5 { With ...f5 or ...Be5 in mind. } 14. Be3 Be5
{ The move  14...f5  is a perfectly viable alternative. Now Black threatens ...Qh4. }
15. g3
{ Preventing ...Qh4.  In case of  15.Nd5  Ne7!  challenges the white knight on d5. }
15... f5
{ Attacking White's centre and intending either ...f4 or ...fxe4 followed by ...Bf5 @@StartBracket@@as White will recapture with a knight@@EndBracket@@. Black has an active position with good chances. }
