[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3
{ Note that after  3.h4  Bg7  4.Nc3  d6  5.e4  O-O  6.Be2  we have a transposition to the lines after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppppp1p/5np1/8/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  Bg7  4.e4  d6  5.Be2  O-O  6.h4  @@StartBracket@@seethis line@@EndBracket@@ in the ChapterVarious Systems on Move 5.   White can also start with  3.Nf3  Bg7  4.e3  @@StartBracket@@a popular move-order to avoid the Grunfeld Defence, but for the KID player it matters little@@EndBracket@@  4...O-O  5.Be2  d6  6.Nc3  when we have a transposition to the system after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppppp1p/5np1/8/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  Bg7  4.Nf3  d6  5.e3  O-O  6.Be2  @@StartBracket@@seethis line@@EndBracket@@. }
3... Bg7 4. Nf3
{ The move  4.g3  transposes to theFianchetto Variation after  4...O-O  5.Bg2  d6  . }
4... d6
{ This is a smart move-order. By not committing his king just yet Black is more easily ready to expand with ...h6 and ...g5 in case White plays Bg5. }
5. Bg5
{ Similar to the Averbakh Variation White puts the bishop on g5 in order to prevent ...e5. The problem is that this bishop can easily be pushed back and harassed. }
5... h6
{ Immediately forcing White to decide where he wants to put his bishop. } 6.
Bh4
{ Keeping the bishop on the h4-d8 diagonal is natural, but Black can now use the fact that he hasn't castled to his advantage. }
6... g5
{ Black wants to gain the bishop pair by exchanging his knight for White's dark-squared bishop. }
7. Bg3 Nh5
{ Thanks to the pawn being on d6 the bishop doesn't have the e5-square at his disposal. }
8. e3 c5
{ Black wants to activate his dark-squared bishop and undermines White's d4-pawn, provoking White to move it forward. }
9. d5
{ This is not very good, but the best way for Black is far from obvious. } 9...
Nxg3 { First Black obtains the bishop pair. } 10. hxg3 Bxc3+
{ Only to give it up immediately in order to exchange one advantage for another - now he obtains the better pawn structure. }
11. bxc3
{ Now the pawn on g5 is hanging as the rook on h8 is undefended. Black's next move is quite a shocking one, but nevertheless very strong! }
11... Kd7
{ An amazing idea. The king allows the queen to defend the rook on h8, thus eliminating the danger against the pawn on g5. The king is on the way to c7 where he will be very safe and will allow Black to play on both sides of the board. }
12. Nd2 Kc7
{ Arriving at the destination and liberating the d7-square for the development of the knight. }
13. Qc2 Nd7
{ The knight is flexible on d7, from where it can go to f6, e5 or b6. } 14. Be2
Qg8
{ Another fine move and atypical development for the queen. The idea is to place the queen on the long diagonal on g7 from where she will be very active.  Black's plan is to play on the kingside with ideas like ...Qg7, ...h5-h4 and ...Nb6, ...Bd7 to finish development and connect the rooks. }
