[Black "83. Miscellaneous Systems. White plays 4.Nf3 5.Bg5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3
{ Note that after  3.h4  Bg7  4.Nc3  d6  5.e4  O-O  6.Be2  we have a transposition to the lines after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppppp1p/5np1/8/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  Bg7  4.e4  d6  5.Be2  O-O  6.h4  @@StartBracket@@seethis line@@EndBracket@@ in the ChapterVarious Systems on Move 5.   White can also start with  3.Nf3  Bg7  4.e3  @@StartBracket@@a popular move-order to avoid the Grunfeld Defence, but for the KID player it matters little@@EndBracket@@  4...O-O  5.Be2  d6  6.Nc3  when we have a transposition to the system after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppppp1p/5np1/8/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  Bg7  4.Nf3  d6  5.e3  O-O  6.Be2  @@StartBracket@@seethis line@@EndBracket@@. }
3... Bg7 4. Nf3
{ The move  4.g3  transposes to theFianchetto Variation after  4...O-O  5.Bg2  d6  . }
4... d6
{ This is a smart move-order. By not committing his king just yet Black is more easily ready to expand with ...h6 and ...g5 in case White plays Bg5. }
5. Bg5
{ Similar to the Averbakh Variation White puts the bishop on g5 in order to prevent ...e5. The problem is that this bishop can easily be pushed back and harassed. }
5... h6
{ Immediately forcing White to decide where he wants to put his bishop. } 6.
Bh4
{ Keeping the bishop on the h4-d8 diagonal is natural, but Black can now use the fact that he hasn't castled to his advantage. }
6... g5
{ Black wants to gain the bishop pair by exchanging his knight for White's dark-squared bishop. }
7. Bg3 Nh5
{ Thanks to the pawn being on d6 the bishop doesn't have the e5-square at his disposal. }
8. e3 c5
{ Black wants to activate his dark-squared bishop and undermines White's d4-pawn, provoking White to move it forward. }
9. Be2
{ This is White's most solid option as the alternatives are weaker.  Exchanging queens after  9.dxc5  Nxg3  10.hxg3  dxc5  11.Qxd8  Kxd8  gives Black a pleasant endgame in view of his pair of bishops and especially the excellent dark-squared bishop. This was played in the game Benko-Fischer from the Candidates Tournament in 1959. }
9... g4
{ This forces the knight to leave the f3-square from where it defends the pawn on d4. }
10. Nd2
{ Putting the knight on the rim after  10.Nh4  Nxg3  11.hxg3  h5  makes it very difficult for the knight to find its way back into the game. }
10... Nxg3 { Black obtains the bishop pair. } 11. hxg3 cxd4
{ Black targets the d4-pawn now. } 12. exd4 h5
{ Black defends the pawn on g4 before continuing development with ...Nc6. Now the pawn on d4 hangs. }
13. Nb3 Nc6
{ Black has excellent play here. He has pressure on the long diagonal and on the d4-pawn in particular and he controls the dark squares, usually a good sign in the KID.  He can harass the knight on b3 by ...a5-a4 and would ideally like to force White to play d5, when the unopposed dark-squared bishop will reign supreme. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8. Miscellaneous Systems"]
[Black "84. Miscellaneous Systems. White plays 4.Nf3 5.Bg5 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3
{ Note that after  3.h4  Bg7  4.Nc3  d6  5.e4  O-O  6.Be2  we have a transposition to the lines after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppppp1p/5np1/8/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  Bg7  4.e4  d6  5.Be2  O-O  6.h4  @@StartBracket@@seethis line@@EndBracket@@ in the ChapterVarious Systems on Move 5.   White can also start with  3.Nf3  Bg7  4.e3  @@StartBracket@@a popular move-order to avoid the Grunfeld Defence, but for the KID player it matters little@@EndBracket@@  4...O-O  5.Be2  d6  6.Nc3  when we have a transposition to the system after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppppp1p/5np1/8/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  Bg7  4.Nf3  d6  5.e3  O-O  6.Be2  @@StartBracket@@seethis line@@EndBracket@@. }
3... Bg7 4. Nf3
{ The move  4.g3  transposes to theFianchetto Variation after  4...O-O  5.Bg2  d6  . }
4... d6
{ This is a smart move-order. By not committing his king just yet Black is more easily ready to expand with ...h6 and ...g5 in case White plays Bg5. }
5. Bg5
{ Similar to the Averbakh Variation White puts the bishop on g5 in order to prevent ...e5. The problem is that this bishop can easily be pushed back and harassed. }
5... h6
{ Immediately forcing White to decide where he wants to put his bishop. } 6.
Bd2
{ Mamedyarov called this 'an interesting idea for one game' but he has already played it three times! The idea is to wait for Black to castle, then play Qc1 and h4-h5. }
6... O-O { Black naturally castles. } 7. Qc1 Kh7
{ Black defends the pawn on h6 and doesn't weaken the g5-square, which would happen in case of ...h5. }
8. h4
{ White's last two moves are Mamedyarov's idea - White goes for a very blunt attack neglecting development. He threatens h5 to open the h-file for a further attack. }
8... Nh5
{ An important move that kills off White's idea. The knight not only blockades the h4-pawn but also by opening the long diagonal it supports the ...e5 push. }
9. e4 e5
{ A natural continuation for Black, aiming for a typical KID position. } 10. d5
a5
{ Another typical reaction by Black, grabbing queenside space and obtaining better control over the dark squares b4 and c5. }
11. Be2 Na6 { Developing the queenside knight with an idea to put it on c5. }
12. g3 { White controls the f4-square. } 12... Qe8
{ This nice move is an improvement over Grischuk's  12...Nc5  as played in his game against Mamedyarov at the Grand Chess Tour blitz event in Leuven in 2018.  Black defends the knight on h5 as he wants to continue with ...f5 so that after a possible exf5 ...gxf5 Black will be safe against a possible discovered attack once the knight from f3 moves. }
13. Be3 { Improving the position of the bishop. } 13... f5
{ Black executes his plan. The threat is to advance ...f4. } 14. exf5 gxf5
{ Black takes towards the centre, controlling the e4-square and again threatening ...f4. }
15. Ng5+ Kh8
{ Now we see the importance of the move ...Qe8 - the knight on h5 is protected, even though in view of the presence of the rook on h1 Black cannot capture the knight on g5 because then the knight on h5 will be pinned.  The immediate threat is still ...f4, but Black has great play here also because he has natural moves like ...Nf6, ...Bd7 and the undermining move ...c6, which give him smooth development, good central control and piece activity. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9. Strategy and Tactics"]
[Black "Exchange Sacrifice I"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2q1rk1/1p1b2b1/3p2p1/2pPp1n1/1nP1P1P1/pPN1B3/P2NB3/1KQR3R b - - 0 24"]
[SetUp "1"]

24... Rf4
{ White wants to organise an attack on the kingside, but Black has this strong exchange sacrifice with good counterplay as White can never take that rook as it will lead to the awakening of the bishop on g7 with catastrophic consequences for White on the long diagonal.  The exercise position stems fromthis line. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9. Strategy and Tactics"]
[Black "Exchange Sacrifice II"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bq1rk1/ppp3bn/3p2p1/2nPp1Pp/2P1P3/2N1BP2/PP1QB3/R3K1NR b KQ - 0 13"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ White defends the pawn on g5 but Black has a way to get to it. } 13... Rf4
{ Black uses the f4-square for his rook and is happy to sacrifice the exchange so that he obtains absolute control over the dark squares. The rook on f4 also closes the c1-h6 diagonal so Black now wants to collect the pawn on g5.  Taking the rook opens the long diagonal for the fianchettoed bishop and allows Black access to the e5-square, thus giving him tremendous compensation for the material.  The exercise position stems fromthis line. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9. Strategy and Tactics"]
[Black "Exchange Sacrifice III"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bq1rk1/pppn2bn/3p2p1/3Pp3/1PP1P3/2N1BB2/P2Q4/R3K1NR b KQ - 0 15"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ It seems that White will obtain a strong attack against Black's kingside along the open files. But after: }
15... Rf4
{ Black successfully takes control over the kingside. Black is happy to sacrifice an exchange for White's dark-squared bishop in order to dominate the dark squares.  As a general rule of thumb, whenever White accepts the sacrifice, Black obtains wonderful compensation thanks to his unopposed dark-squared bishop, his control over the long diagonal and access to the e5-square.  The exercise position stems fromthis line. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9. Strategy and Tactics"]
[Black "Exchange of Bishop for Knight I"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2qr1k1/pppn1pbp/2np2p1/8/2P1P3/2N1BB2/PP1Q1PPP/3R1RK1 b - - 0 13"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ White appears to be solid in the centre. However... } 13... Bxc3
{ Is a very surprising exchange, but an idea that every KID player must know - sometimes the great bishop has to be exchanged in order to achieve other gains!  The idea is very concrete here: Black eliminates the knight that solidifies White's centre and the knights now develop strong activity. }
14. Qxc3 Qf6
{ The first point, Black wants to take on c3 and wreck White's structure. } 15.
Qc1
{ After  15.Qxf6  Nxf6  we see the second point - White cannot defend the pawn on e4. }
15... Nc5
{ Hitting the pawn on e4. Black is already somewhat better here as his attack on White's centre is not easy to deal with.  The exercise position stems fromthis line. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9. Strategy and Tactics"]
[Black "Exchange of Bishop for Knight II"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqr1k1/1ppn1pbp/3pp1p1/p2P4/1nP1P3/1NN1B2P/PP2BPP1/R2Q1RK1 b - - 0 12"]
[SetUp "1"]

12... Bxc3
{ Is a curious way for Black to enter a strategically imbalanced position. After: }
13. bxc3 Na6
{ Black threatens ...e5 when he would have got rid of his bad bishop in a closed position, doubling White's c-pawns in the process. So White is forced to take on e6 and after... }
14. dxe6
{ Note that taking on a5 is good for Black as  14.Nxa5?!  Nac5  attacks both the knight on a5 and the pawn on e4. }
14... Rxe6
{ We have a double-edged position where White's trump is his unopposed dark-squared bishop while Black has the better structure and good squares for his knights in addition to White's weaknesses on the queenside.  The exercise position stems fromthis line. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9. Strategy and Tactics"]
[Black "Exchange of Bishop for Knight III"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqk2r/pp2ppb1/3p3p/2pP2p1/2P5/2N1PNP1/PP3PP1/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 0 10"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Black already has a good position, but after the exchange, it gets even better: }
10... Bxc3+
{ Black exchanges one advantage for another - he gives up his bishop pair to obtain a better pawn structure.  The exercise position stems fromthis line. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9. Strategy and Tactics"]
[Black "Exchange of Dark-Squared Bishops I"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2qnrk1/1ppn2bp/3p2p1/p2Ppp2/1PP1P3/P1N1BB1P/5PP1/R2Q1RK1 b - - 0 13"]
[SetUp "1"]

13... Bf6
{ Intending ...Bg5.  Playing  13...f4?  would be bad as after the bishop retreats to d2 Black's kingside play comes to a standstill - he cannot achieve an attack with ...h5 and ...g4 because White has strong control over the g4-square and his own dark-squared bishop is now a prisoner behind the pawn chain that stretches from c7 to f4.  The exercise position stems fromthis line. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9. Strategy and Tactics"]
[Black "Exchange of Dark-Squared Bishops II"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2q1rk1/1ppn1pbp/3p1np1/p2Pp3/2P1P3/P1N2B1P/1P3PP1/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 0 11"]
[SetUp "1"]

11... h5
{ Since White wants to start immediate play on the queenside with Rb1 and b4 Black's plan with ...f5 is rather slow. That is why he switches to the strategic idea to exchange the dark-squared bishops in one of two ways: With ...Kh7 and ...Bh6, or ...Nh7 followed by ...Bf6-g5.  The exercise position stems fromthis line. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9. Strategy and Tactics"]
[Black "Exchange of Dark-Squared Bishops III"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bq1rk1/1p2ppbp/p2p1np1/8/2PBP3/2N4P/PP2BPP1/R2QK2R b KQ - 0 11"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ In the Maroczy Bind structure the exchange of the dark-squared bishops is in Black's favour because without them White will lack the only piece that can control the dark squares. In order to achieve this exchange Black now plays: }
11... Bh6
{ With the threat ...e5 when Black manages to achieve his aim as the bishop on d4 will have to drop back to e3, for example: }
12. Qd3 e5 13. Be3 Bxe3 14. Qxe3 Be6
{ With an excellent position for Black who has the better long-term prospects thanks to the weakness of the d4 and f4 squares. His ideal is to exchange his light-squared bishop for White's knight and remain with a good knight against a bad bishop. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9. Strategy and Tactics"]
[Black "The ...Nxe4 Tactic I"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbr2k1/ppp2pbp/5np1/4p3/2P1P3/2N2N2/PP2BPPP/R1B1K2R w KQ - 0 9"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ The pawn on e5 is defended by the typical tactical shot: } 9. Nxe5 Nxe4
{ Black opens the long diagonal with a sacrifice when the fianchettoed bishop springs to life.  The exercise position stems fromthis line. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9. Strategy and Tactics"]
[Black "The ...Nxe4 Tactic II"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bq1rk1/ppp2pbp/3p1np1/3P4/2PBP3/2N4P/PP3PP1/R2QKB1R b KQ - 0 10"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ It seems that White won a pawn, but Black has: } 10... Nxe4
{ Thanks to this tactical shot Black regains the pawn. } 11. Nxe4
{ In case of  11.Bxg7  Re8!  threatening discovered check Black captures the bishop on g7 on the next move with easy game. }
11... Qh4
{ White's loose pieces in the centre are under tremendous pressure and Black easily regains his material.  The exercise position stems fromthis line. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9. Strategy and Tactics"]
[Black "The ...Nxe4 Tactic III"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bq1rk1/ppp2pbp/3p1np1/3P4/2PpP3/2N3P1/PP3PBP/R1BQK2R w KQ - 0 10"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Black will have a strong protected passed pawn on d4 after ...c5 because White cannot take it: }
10. Qxd4 { Is met by: } 10... Nxe4 { With a winning position for Black as... }
11. Qxe4 Re8
{ ... wins the queen.  The exercise position stems fromthis line. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9. Strategy and Tactics"]
[Black "The ...e4 Clearing Sacrifice I"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bq1rk1/1pp3b1/3p4/pPnPpP1p/2P3pP/2NB2P1/P5PN/1R1Q1RK1 b - - 0 19"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ If White could establish a blockade on e4 he would be fine, but Black doesn't allow it: }
19... e4
{ The typical clearing sacrifice that gives life to the fianchettoed bishop. }
20. Nxe4 Nxe4
{ Taking the bishop instead leads to unfavourable complications for Black:  20...Nxd3  21.f6!  Nc5  22.fxg7  Rxf1+  23.Qxf1  Nxe4  24.Qf4  Qf6  25.Qxe4  Bf5  26.Qf4  Kxg7  27.Re1  Rf8  . }
21. Bxe4 Qf6
{ With excellent compensation for Black, who has absolute control over the dark squares. He will continue with ...Bd7, ...Rae8-e5 and so on.  The exercise position stems fromthis line. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9. Strategy and Tactics"]
[Black "The ...e4 Clearing Sacrifice II"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bq1rk1/p1p3bp/3p4/2pPpnp1/2P5/2NB1P2/PP3BPP/R2QK2R b KQ - 0 17"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ White would like to establish a strong blockade on e4 by placing a knight there, but Black can counter that idea by: }
17... e4 { Opening the long diagonal for the bishop at the expense of a pawn. }
18. Bxe4 Rb8 19. Qd2 Be5
{ Black has excellent compensation as his dominant dark-squared bishop is worth the material investment. }
